<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Runner Trains for Eating Contest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Maine (AP) -- Some people dream of winning a marathon,  
maybe even an Olympic medal. For George Glum, real achievement 
means being able to shove 15 hot dogs down his throat in 12 
minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``By the fifth one, they're going to start tasting bad -- no  
matter how good they are,'' he said. ``Your mind says stop, but you 
have to find a way to get over that and keep going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Glum -- or ``Garbage Gut,'' as he is known competitively -- is  
currently in training for the Super Bowl of competitive eating: the 
Nathan's Famous hot dog eating championship, held July 4 on New 
York's Coney Island. 
</P>
<P>
	The 35-year-old's first big test comes this Saturday, when he  
must out-eat more than a dozen other hopefuls in his qualifying 
event in Jersey City, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll give it my best shot and if I make it to the finals, it  
would be pretty incredible,'' the Biddeford resident said while 
chewing the fat at Mark's hot dog stand in Portland. 
</P>
<P>
	Quite a challenge for a man who admits he rarely eats more than  
two franks at one sitting. But Glum says he's always shown signs of 
being a gustatory gladiator. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always cleaned my plate,'' Glum said. ``I've always eaten a  
lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At 6-feet-tall and 210 pounds, Glum is about 50 pounds heavier  
than he was in the mid 1980s when he ran the New York Marathon in 
less than three hours and qualified for the Boston Marathon. When 
knee problems halted his distance running, he turned to karate, 
reaching black belt status. 
</P>
<P>
	Entrants in the Nathan's contest come in all shapes and sizes.  
The man Glum will try to dethrone, three-time hot dog-eating champ 
Hirofumi ``The Tokyo Terror'' Nakajima, was a mere 135 pounds when 
he set the all-time record last year by inhaling 24 1/2 hot dogs. His 
closest rivals weighed in at 387 pounds and 381 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Glum's recalls his interest in fast eating being piqued by a  
scene in the 1967 movie ``Cool Hand Luke'' in which Paul Newman 
plays a prisoner who wins a bet with a guard by swallowing 50 eggs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw it several times,'' he said. ``It was an inspiration.''  
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't until last year that his latent talent came to the  
fore when he noticed a plaque heralding the local pasta eating 
champ at Fresh Market Pasta. 
</P>
<P>
	By March of last year he became sufficiently motivated to put  
his skills to the test. 
</P>
<P>
	Sure enough, ``Garbage Gut'' sucked down 4 1/2 bowls of pasta in  
two hours, eclipsing the previous mark of four bowls set by a 
competitor named ``Pig Boy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He demonstrated his prowess once again by consuming a  
three-pound hamburger in 45 minutes at Lena's eatery in Beverly, 
Mass., a feat that got his name alongside the 17 other big eaters 
on the restaurant's ``wall of fame.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Glum's primary training food remains pasta, just as it was in  
his marathon days. Within a few days of the competition, he plans 
to load up on cabbage and other vegetables, grains such as oats, 
and plenty of water to expand his stomach. 
</P>
<P>
	The Villanova graduate said his friends and co-workers at  
Northeast Paging in Westbrook, where he is an executive marketing 
assistant, are giving him plenty of support. 
</P>
<P>
	He sees the Nathan's contest as ``my last hurrah.'' But if he  
defies the odds and defeats Nakajima and the rest of the field, 
Glum would happily return to Coney Island to defend the bejeweled 
yellow belt awarded to the champion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd be honored to do that,'' he said.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
