<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Women Filing for Bankruptcy More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Women are turning to the shelter of bankruptcy  
court in greater proportion than men and married couples, according 
to new data from a Harvard law professor critical of legislation 
making it tougher for people to erase debts through bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
	As Congress debates the legislation to rewrite the bankruptcy  
laws, the new study being written by Elizabeth Warren, a widely 
quoted expert, is likely to become fresh ammunition for opponents 
of the proposed restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	But another bankruptcy expert voiced skepticism about the study  
Monday, saying it doesn't appear to demonstrate conclusively a link 
between gender and bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not much there,'' said Sam Gerdano, executive director  
of the American Bankruptcy Institute, a group of 6,400 attorneys, 
judges, bankers, and professors that does not take positions on 
bankruptcy issues. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Gerdano acknowledged that divorce is a major factor in  
bankruptcy for men and women and that divorced women are more 
likely than other women to have financial problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Warren was traveling Monday and not available for an  
interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Her study -- based on bankruptcy court filings in eight of the 94  
federal bankruptcy districts -- indicates that 39 percent of the 
filings in the 12 months ending March 31 were made by women. That 
compares with 28 percent for men and 33 percent for married 
couples. The findings were reported first in Monday's editions of 
USA Today and confirmed by a Harvard colleague. 
</P>
<P>
	The House, seeking to stop the nationwide increase in personal  
bankruptcies, last month passed a bill sought by credit card 
companies that would make it more difficult for people to erase 
their debts in bankruptcy court. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration has opposed the bill that cleared the  
House by a veto-proof 313-108 margin. The measure got solid support 
from Republicans but split the Democrats. Reps. George Gekas, 
R-Pa., and Jim Moran, D-Va., were the top sponsors. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have concerns about the hardships that this bill will  
impose on many responsible lower- and middle-income debtors who are 
trying to get a fresh start,'' White House spokesman Jake Siewert 
said Monday. ``And the fact that this hardship falls 
disproportionately on single women is further cause for concern.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parallel legislation, which is somewhat less stringent toward  
debtors, is pending in the Senate. Its chief author, Sen. Charles 
Grassley, R-Iowa, has been trying to work out compromises with key 
Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley and the House measure's sponsors say the legislation  
helps women whose husbands or former husbands have filed for 
bankruptcy by giving child support and alimony payments a higher 
priority than credit card debt and other obligations. Under the 
current law, debts such as bankruptcy lawyers' fees, student loans 
and other obligations must be paid before child support or alimony. 
</P>
<P>
	``Women would be treated a lot better than they are now,'' said  
Carey Dearnley, a Gekas spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	But opponents maintain that the legislation, by barring certain  
credit card debts from being erased in bankruptcy, would force 
single mothers and children owed support by bankrupt fathers to 
compete with credit card companies in collecting debts. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation ``will exacerbate the problems faced by the  
growing number of women in the bankruptcy system,'' said Sen. 
Edward Kennedy, D-Mass. ``The bill's supporters claim they are 
protecting women and children, but the protections are a sham.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
