<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbine Memorial Ideas Pour In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKEWOOD, Colo. (AP) -- Stained-glass steppingstones, each carved  
with a victim's name. A wish garden, for remembering those lost. A 
sobbing angel hovering over a field of flowers. 
</P>
<P>
	These are just a few of the ideas that artists, students and  
others have offered for a permanent memorial to the victims of the 
April 20 Columbine High School massacre. 
</P>
<P>
	Art Zohn, a Denver graphic artist whose daughter will be a  
senior at Columbine this fall, said he felt he had to submit a 
design ``to get it out of my system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His concept features 13 marble benches, a waterfall and a  
stained glass window looking out on the mountains, where ``friends 
and family could gather there and rally around one (bench) or all 
of them,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Easton, district executive director, is coordinating the  
project, along with school, parks and county officials, who are in 
the initial stages of reviewing designs, picking a site and lining 
up the money. 
</P>
<P>
	Although no budget has been set, three funds established by the  
parks district, school district and Jefferson County have set aside 
$25,000. About 28 offers of in-kind services have been made by 
contractors, landscapers and others. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are no preconceived notions at this point,'' Easton  
said. ``The real key is a high level of involvement by the high 
school students, the parents, victims and families. We want to be 
sure it accurately reflects their desires.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The site has not been chosen, although public sentiment seems to  
favor Clement Park, where a makeshift memorial sprang up next to 
the high school soon after two heavily armed students killed a 
dozen classmates and a teacher inside the school. 
</P>
<P>
	There is no talk of remembering the gunmen, Dylan Klebold and  
Eric Harris, who ended their rampage by killing themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Easton expects a committee of 20 to 25 people, including victims  
and other members of the public, to make the final decision. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposals stacked on Easton's desk arrived from as near as  
Littleton and as far away as Washington state. Many were created by 
artists, but just as many were not. Some people have children at 
Columbine or are alumni; others have no connection other than their 
sorrow. 
</P>
<P>
	The ideas range from a brief note asking that any design include  
the columbine -- the bell-shaped state flower -- to an elaborate 
floor plan for a memorial resembling a Greek temple, with a cafe, 
theater and library. 
</P>
<P>
	One artist sees a pair of 7-foot bronze hands cupping a  
columbine. Another proposes a sobbing angel in a field of 
columbines, her body draped over a tombstone inscribed with the 
victims' names. 
</P>
<P>
	Stained-glass artist Barb Fowler of Dayton, Ohio, proposed 13  
stained-glass steppingstones engraved with the victims' names. 
</P>
<P>
	``I must have heard about it the minute the news broke,'' she  
said. ``My reaction was probably the same as everyone else in the 
country -- total disgust and shock.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sculptor Randy Rau, a 1979 graduate of Columbine, has suggested  
a large bronze bell that would ring 13 times each year on the 
anniversary of the shootings. Thirteen concrete pillars intertwined 
by a bronze ribbon held up by 13 doves would surround the bell. 
</P>
<P>
	Many proposals call for stone tablets engraved with the victims'  
name or circular walkways around reflecting pools. Students at 
nearby Dakota Ridge and Chatfield high schools have designed a 
``Columbine Wish Garden'' with a brick path leading to a wishing 
well. Bricks would be sold to donors to pay for the monument. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fowler said whichever design is chosen, it is important for  
a memorial to be built ``so that nobody forgets. That would be the 
worst tragedy of all.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
