<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 16:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Layden Retires From Coaching Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Frank Layden's tenure as coach in the WNBA  
didn't even last one year. 
</P>
<P>
	The 67-year-old Layden, a former NBA Coach of the Year,  
unexpectedly resigned Monday because of the long workdays and 
traveling. 
</P>
<P>
	Layden said he leaves with more respect for professional women's  
basketball than the men's game. The women, he says, have superior 
work and team ethics. 
</P>
<P>
	``It gets old,'' said Layden, who was replaced by 42-year-old  
assistant Fred Williams, formerly the coach of Southern California. 
``I was getting tired. Time is a precious commodity right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Layden's resignation, however, was abrupt. His comments about  
the team were invariably optimistic and less than two weeks ago, he 
told a sportswriter that taking over the team gave him a newfound 
purpose in life. 
</P>
<P>
	He will remain president of the NBA's Jazz -- the Starzz' big  
brother. He came to Utah as general manager of the Jazz in 1979 
when the New Orleans team was moved to Salt Lake City. 
</P>
<P>
	He coached the Jazz for eight seasons (277-294) and was named  
NBA Coach of the Year in 1984. He retired from coaching in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	A decade later, in July 1998, he took over the Starzz team,  
replacing coach Denise Taylor. Layden won just two of 11 games in 
his first season. 
</P>
<P>
	But the team was revamped for this year and is 2-2 after beating  
Sacramento on Saturday. There is reason for optimism, especially 
with the addition of Natalie Williams, the former MVP of the 
defunct ABL, who is averaging nearly 18 points and 12 rebounds a 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	Layden said he planned to stay only two years as Starzz coach  
and is cutting that short to spend more time with Barbara, his wife 
of 41 years, their three children and six grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams' first game as head coach will be Thursday when the  
Starzz again play the Monarchs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a dream for me. I didn't think it would come so soon,''  
said Williams, who has been with the Starzz since 1998. A year 
before, he coached the Southern California women's team to a 20-9 
record and the second round of the NCAA tournament. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
