<DOCNO> APW19990621.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 18:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Finals Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Marcus Camby's smile and words gave away Jeff  
Van Gundy's big secret. 
</P>
<P>
	Camby started in place of Chris Dudley for the New York Knicks  
on Monday night in Game 3 of the NBA Finals against the San Antonio 
Spurs. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the shoot-around this morning, Jeff came up to me and said,  
`I might start you,''' Camby said in the locker room before the 
game Monday night. ``I said, `Fine. Whatever it takes to get the 
win.' 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to go. I can't wait. I know it's going to be crazy out  
there. I just want to get started.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Camby, making his first start for the Knicks, was the last  
player announced during pregame introductions. He jumped up and 
down in the middle of the huddle, pumping his fist wildly. 
</P>
<P>
	Camby provided a huge spark as a reserve in the Knicks' victory  
over Indiana in the Eastern Conference Finals, but has struggled 
with foul trouble as New York fell behind San Antonio 2-0 in the 
finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``To start the game, I can bring my energy and enthusiasm and  
hopefully get us going and get the crowd going,'' Camby said. 
``Then I can go out and get a blow and come out in the second 
quarter and do the same thing in the second half.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy refused to officially announce the change before the  
lineups were announced, but he laid out the compelling reasons for 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``His energy to us is critical, and I think playing him one long  
stretch at a time has left him more fatigued,'' Van Gundy said. 
``If I decide to start him, it's to try to finish the halves better 
and fresher.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition of Camby from Toronto for popular veteran  
Charles Oakley -- and Camby's subsequent lack of playing time under 
Van Gundy -- have divided the entire Knicks organization this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Camby's first start since he played for the Toronto  
Raptors against Philadelphia last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We lost that game,'' Camby said. ``One of the 66 that we lost.  
Big turnaround, though. Big turnaround. I'm happy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dudley has a badly hyperextended elbow that was so painful he  
has been practicing his free throws left-handed. He's a 46 percent 
foul shooter in his career right-handed. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *STERN VS. LJ:* NBA commissioner David Stern had some stern  
words for Knicks forward Larry Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson and the Knicks were fined $25,000 each Sunday after  
Johnson unleashed a profanity-laced tirade. It was directed toward 
an NBA official and reporters who were trying to interview him 
during a mandatory media session. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our players and teams are going to comply with our rules, and  
if they don't they will be dealt with accordingly,'' Stern said 
Monday at his annual NBA Finals news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``We recognize that there are individual pressures at times, and  
we are not mindless in our enforcement. We know that there are 
pressures on coaches and players and that the very event that we 
have here intensifies those pressure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy speculated -- tongue-in-cheek --  
before the game that pain medication was to blame for Johnson's 
outburst. Johnson is playing with a sprained knee that was injured 
in the Eastern Conference finals against Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's taking a lot of pain medication just to get out there,''  
Van Gundy said. ``I think you either have to ask him about it 
before the pain medication or after, I'm not sure which.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second time this postseason Johnson and the team were  
fined. The league fined them $10,000 each on June 8 because Johnson 
twice failed to make himself available to the media following 
practices on June 4 and 5. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ALL BUSINESS:* The Spurs' locker room was barren before the  
game. At one point when Tim Duncan and David Robinson came in, they 
were approached and asked one question. Both said they don't talk 
before games. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DUNCAN FOR MVP?:* Some believe that Spurs center Tim Duncan  
would have won the MVP award instead of Utah's Karl Malone if 
voters had waited until the regular season ended to send in their 
ballots. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe we should consider getting them in your hands later,''  
commissioner David Stern said. ``But I think we feel as though we 
are dealing with adults and they have a pretty good idea based upon 
a full season what they want to do.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
