<DOCNO> APW19990621.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 07:20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Review Jury Selection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to use an  
Arizona drug case to decide whether some criminal convictions must 
be overturned because of jury-selection errors. 
</P>
<P>
	The court will hear an appeal in which prosecutors say a  
drug-trafficking conviction was valid even though the judge failed 
to remove a potential juror who showed signs of bias. That failure 
caused the defendant to use one of his limited number of challenges 
to remove the man from the jury pool. 
</P>
<P>
	Judges are required to remove prospective jurors who show bias,  
leaving prosecution and defense lawyers free to use their 
challenges to remove jurors for other reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Abel Martinez-Salazar was arrested in Phoenix on charges of  
conspiracy, possession of heroin with intent to distribute and 
using or carrying a firearm during a drug crime. He was convicted 
and sentenced to 10 years and three months in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	During jury selection, one prospective juror said he probably  
would favor the prosecution and that he assumed ``people are on 
trial because they did something wrong.'' He also said, however, 
that he understood defendants are presumed innocent. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial judge refused to remove that man from jury service for  
bias. Martinez-Salazar's lawyer then used one of his automatic 
challenges to remove him as a potential juror. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez-Salazar had been allowed 11 automatic, or peremptory  
challenges, which can be used to remove prospective jurors without 
having to give a reason. 
</P>
<P>
	The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last year ruled that  
Martinez-Salazar is entitled to a new trial. Noting that he 
eventually used all of his automatic challenges, the appeals court 
said his due-process rights were violated because federal law does 
not require defendants to use their automatic challenges to remove 
potential jurors for bias. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, Justice Department lawyers said  
other courts have ruled that such errors do not require throwing 
out a conviction unless a biased juror was seated. All the jurors 
in Martinez-Salazar's case were impartial, and therefore the error 
should be considered harmless, government lawyers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez-Salazar's lawyers said such an error never should be  
considered harmless. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is U.S. vs. Martinez-Salazar, 98-1255.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 06:10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Develop Tiny Robot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese electronics companies have developed a  
micro-machine the size of an ant that can crawl around thin pipes, 
inspect and even fix problems at power plants, officials said 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The box-shaped robot is only 5 millimeters (0.2 inch) long, 9  
millimeters (0.36 inch) wide and 6.5 millimeters (0.26 inch) high. 
</P>
<P>
	It has a pair of round connectors on both sides that can be  
linked up with other robots for more extensive assignments. 
</P>
<P>
	With a weight of only 0.42 grams (0.0147 ounces), the robot can  
lift objects twice as heavy as itself and can move at a speed of 2 
millimeters (0.1 inch) per second, said Koji Hirose, spokesman for 
the Ministry of International Trade and Industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitsubishi Electric Corp., Sumitomo Electric Industries Ltd. and  
Matsushita Research Institute Tokyo, Inc. developed the machine 
under the government's 25 billion yen ($206 million) ``micro 
machine'' project that began in 1989, Hirose said. 
</P>
<P>
	The robots are one of three types of machines designed for use  
in different environments, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The robots, which can crawl into the tiniest gaps around bundles  
of pipes, are expected to speed up inspection and repairs at 
electric and nuclear power plants because they can be sent in while 
the plants keep running. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists are working to add new functions to them so the  
robots can climb up and down a pipe while connected to other 
machines. They also plan to develop robots with motors and 
problem-detecting sensors. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0017 </DOCNO>
