<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Promotes Abstinence Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush said Monday  
that if elected president, he would increase the federal 
government's role in encouraging sexual abstinence by teen-agers to 
prevent sexually transmitted disease and unwanted pregnancies. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, shown in polls as the front-runner for the Republican  
presidential nomination, congratulated students and community 
leaders in an abstinence education program in Greenville. The 
students were part of a Charleston-based abstinence program, 
Heritage Community Services. 
</P>
<P>
	Abstinence isn't just about not having sex, he said: It's about  
saying ``yes to a happier, healthier future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said family issues will be a central element of his  
campaign. He said he will use federal funds for abstinence 
education in amounts equal to that now provided for teen-age 
contraception. 
</P>
<P>
	He also wants to ensure that churches, synagogues and other  
faith-based groups can compete for education grants. And he said 
the General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress, 
should study of the effectiveness of federally funded sex education 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	A statement by Bush's campaign staff said that in texas, the  
Bush administrstion has contracted with 32 community organizations 
to provide abstinence education. 
</P>
<P>
	In his first campaign foray in South Carolina, Bush also made  
appearances in West Columbia and capped his visit with a 
fund-raising reception at the Greenville-Spartanburg International 
Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Another GOP contender, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., was in Myrtle  
Beach and Columbia on Monday. His campaign released a list of 17 
state legislators who are backing his effort and said as many as a 
dozen of them had earlier backed Bush, or leaning in that 
direction. 
</P>
<P>
	However, state House Speaker Pro Tem Terry Haskins and state  
Rep. Rick Quinn, two of McCain's supporters, said they could not 
name which of the lawmakers had previously supported Bush. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
