<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Early Campaign Finance Vote Slows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An effort to force campaign finance  
legislation to the floor ahead of Speaker Dennis Hastert's 
timetable appears becalmed in the House, where a petition drive has 
failed to gather any new GOP support in more than three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Chris Shays of Connecticut, the leading Republican advocate  
of the measure, says, ``I make no assumptions'' about whether any 
additional GOP lawmakers will sign the petition. 
</P>
<P>
	Thus far, 195 Democrats and independent Rep. Bernie Sanders have  
backed the effort to force the bill to the floor in advance of 
Hastert's date of mid-September. Six Republicans also have signed, 
leaving the petition drive a dozen short of the 218 needed to 
prevail. 
</P>
<P>
	But no Republican has joined them since the six added their  
names last May 26. 
</P>
<P>
	That was also the week that Hastert made a direct appeal to the  
GOP rank and file to work together on a common agenda, lest 
Democrats regain control of the House in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., convened the first  
in a series of House Administration Committee hearings last week to 
explore the issue. Democrats immediately charged it had been 
explored enough already. 
</P>
<P>
	The centerpiece of the legislation would ban so-called soft  
money, which are large, unregulated donations that parties and 
politicians solicit to advance their causes. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign finance measure is likely to pass the House when it  
finally reaches the floor, since a nearly identical bill cleared a 
year ago. Supporters say, however, that September is too late if 
the measure is to pass both houses this year 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Democrats forced an early, inconclusive skirmish with  
Republicans during the day over White House-backed legislation to 
enhance the rights of patients dealing with their health care 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Byron Dorgan of North Dakota offered the bill as an  
amendment to a routine agriculture spending bill. 
</P>
<P>
	That prompted Republicans to require the Senate reading clerk to  
read the health care measure word for word, a time-consuming 
process that customarily is dispensed with. Before the reading was 
over, Majority Leader Trent Lott went to the floor and pulled the 
spending bill from consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	In an exchange between Lott and the Democrats, the two sides  
agreed the issue would be back for a fuller debate and series of 
votes. 
</P>
<P>
	House Democrats are expected to begin a push for the same bill  
on Wednesday, when they plan to sign a petition to force the 
measure to the floor. Republicans are at work on a health bill of 
their own in the House, as well as in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	Across the Capitol, Democrats are already weighing a plan to  
force gun control votes on routine spending bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun control legislation failed in the House last week, but  
officials said Democrats on the Appropriations Committee were 
giving thought to trying to attach pieces of it to legislation 
providing funding for the Treasury Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Ready with amendments are Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md., whose  
proposal would tighten requirements for sales at gun shows; Rep. 
Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., who wants to raise the minimum age of hand-gun 
buyers from 18 to 21; and Rep. Rosa DeLauro, D-Conn., who favors 
mandatory safety devices with all hand guns. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 01:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO, KLA Agree on Demilitarization  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Kosovo Albanian rebels signed a  
wide-ranging demilitarization pact with NATO today, allowing the 
peacekeeping force to impose its control on the province and try to 
prevent a backlash of ethnic violence. The pact, which aims to 
neutralize the Kosovo Liberation Army as a military force, was 
signed just after midnight, only hours after the last of the 
Serb-led Yugoslav forces left the province. The role of the KLA has 
been a critical issue for post-war Kosovo. Around 50,000 Serbs have 
fled the province over the past week, fearing the guerrillas would 
exact bloody revenge for Serb forces' campaign of killings and 
expulsions against Albanians over the past 2 1/2 months. 

</P>
<P>
	India Claims Vital Peak in Kashmir  
</P>
<P>
	BATALIK, India (AP) -- Pounded by Pakistani artillery, Indian  
soldiers dug into newly won positions on a mountain ridge today and 
prepared for an assault on the last pockets of Islamic guerrillas 
in the mountainous Kashmir region. As India claimed new military 
victories, the leaders of the world's most industrialized nations 
and Russia urged a halt to the fighting in Kashmir. The divided 
territory has been the trigger for two wars since India and 
Pakistan won independence from Britain in 1947. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Confers With EU Leaders  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- While the United States and its European  
allies are cooperating in the rebuilding effort in Kosovo, the two 
major trading partners have a number of tough trade disputes that 
have split them recently. President Clinton was conferring with top 
officials of the 14-nation European Union today in advance of a 
quick trip to the Balkans to meet with officials in the area and 
discussion reconstruction efforts following the end of NATO's 
78-day air war that forced Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to 
withdraw his troops from Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Navy Carrier To Return to Pacific  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With NATO having officially declared its air  
campaign against Yugoslavia over, the Pentagon intends to return an 
aircraft carrier to the western Pacific in a move made more urgent 
by renewed tensions on the Korean Peninsula. The Navy has been 
without an aircraft carrier in the Pacific since early April, when 
the USS Kitty Hawk carrier battle group went to the Persian Gulf to 
cover for the USS Theodore Roosevelt. The Theodore Roosevelt 
diverted to the Adriatic Sea to bolster allied aircraft striking at 
Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	Malaysia Premier Moves Into Capital  
</P>
<P>
	PUTRAJAYA, Malaysia (AP) -- Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad moved  
into a grand new administrative capital today, calling it a 
showpiece of Malaysia's development. Bounding up a steep flight of 
stairs to the six-story granite building that loomed over manicured 
hills, Mahathir shook hands with his staff then performed a Muslim 
prayer before entering. Civil servants are expected to shift into 
Putrajaya, 25 miles south of Kuala Lumpur, in coming months. In the 
next three years, all government employees will be working from and 
perhaps living in the new township. 

</P>
<P>
	Royal Newlyweds Begin Honeymoon  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Honeymoon plans for royal newlyweds Prince Edward  
and Sophie Rhys-Jones remained officially a mystery today, but 
British newspapers contended the couple would take only four days 
off at the queen's Scottish retreat before returning to work. ``Too 
busy for a proper honeymoon,'' read the headline in the Daily Mail, 
which said the couple chose to spend their brief honeymoon on the 
royal Balmoral estate partly to deter the paparazzi. They 
reportedly spent the first night at Birkhall Lodge, a house on the 
estate usually used by Edward's grandmother, the Queen Mother 
Elizabeth. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stock Prices Advance  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices advanced Monday. The Nikkei rose  
307.59 to end the day at 17,738.85. 

</P>
<P>
	Indians Beat Mariners 13-5  
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Manny Ramirez's absence didn't stop the Indians  
from scoring for Jaret Wright and Cleveland rolled to another win, 
13-5 over the Seattle Mariners last night. The Indians, averaging 
6.8 runs, have scored 54 runs in their last six games and remain on 
pace to set the major league record for runs in a season. Ramirez, 
baseball's RBIs leader with 79, was struck by a pitch from 
Seattle's Frankie Rodriguez and left after two innings with a 
bruised left index finger. 

</P>
<P>
	Braves Defeat Diamondbacks 10-4  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Randy Johnson gave up four home runs for the  
first time in his career, including two by Javy Lopez, and the 
Atlanta Braves beat the Arizona Diamondbacks 10-4 last night. 
Johnson, who had won five straight decisions since May 20 at 
Colorado, gave up seven earned runs for the first time since last 
July 8. His ERA went from 2.96 to 3.36. Tom Glavine won his second 
straight start after losing three in a row. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief By VINCENT K. WILLIS  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
