<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Weyerhaeuser Purchases Mac. Bloedel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Weyerhaeuser said its purchase of Canadian  
forest-products competitor MacMillan Bloedel for $2.45 billion in 
stock will expand its product line and immediately add to earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Weyerhaeuser already is the world's largest producer of softwood  
lumber and market pulp, and the deal would make the Federal 
Way-based company a leader in packaging as well. 
</P>
<P>
	When complete, the transaction will boost Weyerhaeuser's annual  
sales to about $13.3 billion from $10.8 billion last year, 
Weyerhaeuser said in a news release. 
</P>
<P>
	Weyerhaeuser also expects to achieve some $150 million in annual  
benefits through savings in transportation and distribution, 
improving purchasing practices, increasing the balance in its 
manufacturing system and streamlining operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Weyerhaeuser shares fell Monday, closing at $67.12 1/2, down  
$2.62 1/2, or 3.8 percent on the New York Stock Exchange. MacMillan 
Bloedel shares were up 23 percent, or $3.37 1/2, to close at 17.81 1/4 on 
the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	The boards of both companies have approved an agreement under  
which MacMillan Bloedel shareholders would get 0.28 share of 
Weyerhaeuser stock for each share of MacMillan Bloedel. 
</P>
<P>
	The transaction, which is expected to close this fall, is  
subject to regulatory approval in the United States and Canada, 
court approval in Canada and a favorable vote by MacMillan Bloedel 
shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal took some analysts by surprise.  
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't looking for it. I don't think anyone else was  
either,'' said Seattle analyst Lee Childress, who has followed 
Weyerhaeuser for 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	But MacMillan Bloedel had become an attractive target for  
acquisition under CEO Tom Stephens, Childress said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The company had done a nice job in the last year and a half of  
turning things around in a tough pricing environment,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Weyerhaeuser is one of the world's largest integrated  
forest-products companies, with offices or operations in 12 
countries. Of its 35,000 North American employees, 5,900 work for 
Weyerhaeuser Canada, based in Vancouver, British Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	The company owns or manages 5.3 million acres of U.S. timberland  
and has timber licenses on 27 million acres in Canada. Its North 
American operations produce pulp, paper, packaging, lumber and 
structural panels that are sold around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	MacMillan Bloedel employs 9,500 people, with 5,500 in Canada. It  
has 6.9 million acres of productive timberlands -- 427,500 acres in 
the United States -- and 33 distribution centers in the United 
States and Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	Steven R. Rogel said Weyerhaeuser did not foresee laying off a  
large number of workers, since MacMillan Bloedel operations already 
are efficient and the companies meshed well. 
</P>
<P>
	Some job cuts likely will result from the merger of MacMillan  
Bloedel's corporate office in Vancouver, British Columbia, with 
Weyerhaeuser's own office there, he said. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
