<DOCNO> APW19990621.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 08:00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Geisha Chic' Takes Hold in America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Geisha chic is quietly taking hold.  
</P>
<P>
	It started with Arthur Golden's novel ``Memoirs of a Geisha,''  
which sold over 1 million copies. Then Steven Spielberg bought 
rights to the film. Then it hit the fashion runways. 
</P>
<P>
	Fashion shows introduced the obi, a carefully tied sash that is  
worn over a kimono, this spring; Madonna wore a red vinyl obi and 
gown with jumbo kimono sleeves to this year's Grammy Awards. 
Fashion magazines tell women to ``Geisha-ize.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But a veteran geisha who knows Golden is annoyed that her art  
has been appropriated by American pop culture. 
</P>
<P>
	``I took a very strict examination to become a geisha. I studied  
very, very hard,'' said Kiharu Nakamura, her eyes moist as she 
remembers long nights with drunken clients and exhausting days of 
lessons in traditional arts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to correct the idea of geisha,'' she said, ``but then I  
go to a party and see people putting chopsticks in their hair. 
Ridiculous!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the geisha's image as a sort of high-class prostitute,  
the women are really professional entertainers and generally do not 
sleep with clients. Traditionally, they dance, tell amusing stories 
and play party games; the name geisha means ``practitioner of 
arts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Nakamura, 87, spent years studying Japanese dance, flower  
arrangement, the tea ceremony, poetry, and other skills. Before 
becoming a geisha, she had to pass a grueling exam. 
</P>
<P>
	In pre-war Japan, she entertained scores of men -- including  
Charlie Chaplin and Babe Ruth -- in sake-drinking evenings at tea 
houses in Tokyo. In stunning kimono, hairdo and make-up, she had to 
ensure each client had a good time. 
</P>
<P>
	She has lived in the United States since 1956 and now lives in  
the borough of Queens. She dresses in kimonos, lives amid rice 
paper shoji screens and teaches the samisen, a traditional stringed 
instrument. 
</P>
<P>
	Golden was friends with Ms. Nakamura before writing his best  
seller but used another geisha, from Kyoto, as a primary source for 
the book. Steven Spielberg's film depiction of the novel is due out 
in December 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Golden, whose book seems so believable many readers forget it is  
fiction, spent years researching his story about the highly 
controlled and stylized world of Chiyo, a girl from a poor fishing 
village who is forced into life as a geisha in Kyoto. 
</P>
<P>
	Taking the name Sayuri, she becomes a hugely successful geisha.  
Eventually she moves to New York where she dictates her memoirs to 
a fictional Dutch scholar. 
</P>
<P>
	The beauty of the world of pre-war Japan so carefully described  
in the bestseller quickly proved irresistible to consumers a world 
away. 
</P>
<P>
	``Business has improved this year,'' confirmed Yumiko Sakuyama,  
manager of Kimono, a shop selling kimonos and Japanese accessories 
in New York's East Village. ``Maybe it's because of that book, or 
maybe Madonna. It's hard to tell.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Japanese-style clothes are easy to come by, Ms. Nakamura  
said real geisha chic requires hard work and discipline. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now young people have no patience, no obedience. ... If a girl  
has very good talent, she becomes a cocktail waitress, a bar girl -- 
that is more money,'' she said, shaking her head in dismay as she 
touches one of the ornate decorations in her hair. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike Golden's protagonist, Ms. Nakamura was a Tokyo geisha.  
She is from a wealthy family of doctors and chose to become a 
geisha, with her grandfather paying the hefty cost of her training 
and her silk kimonos. 
</P>
<P>
	But much like the protagonist, she has written her own memoirs --  
``Edokko Geisha Ichidai-ki'' (Biography of a Tokyo Geisha) -- along 
with more than a dozen other books. 
</P>
<P>
	Available only in Japanese and German, the memoirs will be  
translated into English next year, said Ms. Nakamura, who is now 
working on a book about the Japanese language. She is now invited 
to give lectures on her life. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Nakamura seems to thrive in the geisha-style world she has  
created for herself. But she has nothing for disdain for those to 
try and emulate the style. 
</P>
<P>
	``How phony it is. I don't like imitation for anything,'' she  
said. ``I'm proud of my job.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
