<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Move Lower / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean and grain futures prices were mostly  
lower in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade as 
doubts arose about last week's forecasts of hot, dry weather this 
week in the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, soybean and corn futures soared on reports that some  
forecasters expected temperatures could surpass the hundred-degree 
mark in key growing regions in the Plains states, possibly lowering 
yields. 
</P>
<P>
	But forecasters are now calling for more favorable growing  
temperatures and light rains in much of the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures prices found more support than corn and soybeans,  
in part because rain could cause further delays in the winter wheat 
harvest. 
</P>
<P>
	In early trading today, wheat for July delivery broke even at  
$2.54 3/4 a bushel; July corn fell 3 cents to $2.17 3/4 a bushel; July 
oats dropped 1/2 cent to $1.17 a bushel; and July soybeans fell 2 1/4 
cents to $4.72 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, meat and livestock futures prices fell in early  
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle fell 0.42 cent to 63.45 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell 0.67 cent to 76.45 cents a pound; July lean hogs 
fell 0.77 cent to 50 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell 1 cent 
to 42.20 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
