<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colder Climate May Stifle Volcanoes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The thick glaciers that accumulate during ice  
ages may put a lid on volcanoes. 
</P>
<P>
	A study of volcanoes in eastern California indicates that, over  
millions of years, eruptions alternated with cycles of colder 
climate. 
</P>
<P>
	While scientists have long known that the gases blasted into the  
air by volcanoes can briefly cool the weather, the new findings are 
prompting speculation that it works both ways -- glacial conditions 
can suppress volcanoes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The correlation between volcanic outbursts and climate  
suggests that the two are linked,'' a team of researchers write in 
a paper appearing in the journal Geophysical Research Letters. 
</P>
<P>
	California isn't the only place that a similar correlation  
occurs, lead researcher Allen F. Glazner said in a telephone 
interview. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought it was kind of crazy until I went to the library''  
and found similar patterns reported by other researchers, said 
Glazner, a University of North Carolina geology professor. 
</P>
<P>
	He said volcanoes could be suppressed in various ways, including  
changes in the stress on the earth's crust caused by the weight of 
ice or lake water, and changes in the amount and location of water 
underground in the area where magma builds volcanoes. 
</P>
<P>
	``None of those things is going to suppress a volcano forever,  
but they might delay it'' for thousands of years, Glazner said. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, he said, if a volcano is near eruption ``and you  
put the weight of 300 to 400 meters (975 to 1,300 feet) of ice on 
it, it might be enough confining stress to keep it from erupting 
another 10,000 years or so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also, he noted that glacial times had a lot more rainfall and  
snowfall so ``there might be a cooling of the crust by water flux 
through it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In at least one area studied, numerous stone deposits indicated  
early hot springs, showing that water seeping through the earth was 
heated and rose to the surface, which could have provided an 
efficient heat transfer to cool volcanic magma. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers studying California's Long Valley, Big Pine and  
Coso volcanic fields found peaks of volcanic activity 10 million, 
100 million, 185 million, 320 million and 690 million years ago, 
alternating with periods of glacial climate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although the short-term effect of volcanism on climate is  
clear, it is unlikely that the correlation ... is a result of 
volcanically induced climate change,'' the researchers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The climate impact of volcanoes has long been a topic of  
speculation, going back at least to Benjamin Franklin. The eruption 
of the Indonesian volcano Tambora was blamed for a worldwide 
cooling in 1816 -- the ``year without a summer'' when snow fell over 
New England in June. 
</P>
<P>
	The effect was more recently observed in the Philippines. The  
year after the 1991 eruption of Mount Pinatubo, the average global 
climate cooled a degree or two because dust in the atmosphere 
blocked the sunlight. 
</P>
<P>
	But such effects tend to last only a year or two, and  
researchers say they are unlikely to lead to anything as severe as 
a major glacial period. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the paper concludes, ``it appears that climate has  
affected the timing of volcanism in eastern California.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the coldest periods, glaciers averaged more than 300  
yards thick over the Sierra Nevada, increasing to 1,500 yards in 
some deep canyons. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
