<HEADLINE> Newspaper Comment Disputed NHL Goal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Brett Hull's goal near the end of the third overtime Sunday  
morning gave Dallas a 2-1 victory over Buffalo to win the NHL 
finals series 4-2. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Bryan Lewis, the NHL's chief referee, Hull's goal  
counted because he didn't lose control of the puck as his skate 
entered the crease in front of Buffalo goalie Dominik Hasek. A 
player is not allowed to enter the crease without the puck. 
</P>
<P>
	Here is a sampling of comments on the disputed goal:  
</P>
<P>
	 *Kevin Paul Dupont, Boston Globe:* The fact that Hull's foot was  
in the crease, in truth, had no bearing on his winning shot going 
in the net. If there is any solace here for Sabres fans, it should 
be that. Up until the league fell in love with its replay gadgetry, 
no one ever looked twice at the kind of goal the Golden Brett 
scored. Hull also has blue eyes. In this case, the color of his 
eyes and the placement of his foot had the same influence on 
whether Hasek could stop the shot: none. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *Gare Joyce, Ottawa Citizen:* There's only one plausible  
scenario. The review officials realized too late that the goal 
couldn't stand. The truth was plain in (NHL director of officiating 
Bryan) Lewis's demeanor. It was plain in the glassy-eyed gaze of 
(referee Bill) McCreary as he stood at the scorer's bench. They 
looked like (Buffalo goalie Dominik) Hasek in many ways. They had 
come so far, come so close and, in the end, let one get away. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *Jerry Sullivan, The Buffalo News:* That's where the NHL stands  
credibilitywise right now -- even with pro wrestling. That's the 
only other sport where the referees turn their heads and pretend 
not to see. Of course wrestling is fake. The NHL is real. Isn't it? 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *Keith Gave, Dallas Morning News:* As you'd expect, the winning  
goal that video replays suggested might not have been entirely 
kosher wasn't much of a topic of discussion while a bunch of guys 
sprayed bubbly all over the room. That was someone else's headache. 
The Stars would have theirs the next day, unless some chose to 
stickhandle around their hangovers by just not going to sleep. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *Joe Lapointe, The New York Times:* This is not the first time  
the Cup has been won on a disputed goal by a road team in a Game 6 
overtime. In 1966, the Montreal Canadiens beat the Detroit Red 
Wings at Olympia Stadium on a goal by Henri Richard, who, the Wings 
charged, swept the puck into the net with his arm as he slid along 
the ice. Had this happened in 1999, the goal would have been 
reviewed on videotape and possibly negated. Back then, there was no 
video review. The goal stood and the Canadiens won. That game, 
theoretically, could still be in progress. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *Les Bowen, Philadelphia Daily News:* In Buffalo, a city with an  
inferiority complex the size of Lake Erie, this one goes up on the 
mantel right next to Scott Norwood missing the field goal wide 
right, only this is worse -- to Buffalonians, it's as if the Giants 
had been caught on tape roughing the kicker, and it wasn't called. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *Jack Todd, Montreal Gazette:* Hull did not interfere with  
Buffalo goaltender Dominik Hasek, so without the crease rule no one 
would have filed the meekest protest. But the rule does exist. This 
time, flying by the seat of its pants as usual, the NHL decided not 
to apply it. The solution? Deep six the crease rule now. Call 
goalie interference tightly when it applies. And apologize 
profusely to the Sabres and their fans. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *Don Cherry, former Boston Bruins coach, in his syndicated  
column:@ It is a sad thing that they call back a zillion goals for 
a toe in the crease, then let the most important goal of the year 
count with Brett Hull's foot in the crease. They say (and I feel 
for head of officiating Bryan Lewis having to take the heat) Hull 
had control of the puck. No way. ... It was an accident waiting to 
happen. It was just a matter of time till they got burnt. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *Al Strachan, Toronto Sun:* There should have been no  
controversy whatsoever. When Hull first kicked the rebound on to 
his stick, he had neither foot in the crease. At the instant he 
kicked the puck, he became in control of it. It was only in the 
follow-through of that kick that his left foot moved into the 
crease. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *Terry Jones, Edmonton Sun:* Five years ago it would have been a  
goal. Next year it'll be a goal again. But at 1:33 a.m. EDT 
(Sunday) morning it wasn't a goal. If this toe-in-the-crease, 
let's-go-upstairs, wait-a-couple-minutes-before-you-can-cheer 
idiocy had any chance of surviving for another season, the good 
news is that it went out the window at 54:51 into overtime on the 
NHL clock in Game 6 of the Stanley Cup final. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *John Kernaghan, Hamilton Spectator: Unfortunately, the  
104-minute marathon will not get its due in the history of the game 
because of an ill-conceived and ill-explained crease rule. If you 
can get past that, though, it was a crackling contest that 
developed from some heavy-hitting and stages of cautious play in 
the first two periods to a third regulation and three OT periods 
which produced a series of thunderclaps. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
