<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Against Yen, Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose against the yen Monday as Japan  
yet again intervened to prop up its currency and lower the risk of 
prematurely cutting short any nascent economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also rose against the euro as Italy's prime minister  
made unsettling remarks that traders thought damaging to the euro. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just a demand for dollars,'' said Ralph DelZenero, a  
foreign exchange marketing vice president at First National Bank of 
Chicago's hometown office. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar rose to 122.42 Japanese yen  
from 120.44 yen Friday. The euro was quoted at $1.0345, down from 
$1.0384. 
</P>
<P>
	As the yen strengthened Monday, the Bank of Japan intervened  
several times to buy dollars and sell yen, in a bid to weaken the 
Japanese currency. Traders estimated the bank spent $5 billion in 
its efforts in what is believed to be the fourth intervention in 10 
days. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan has few options in fighting its worst recession since  
World War II. Recent economic reports indicate the picture is 
improving, but those gains largely come from government spending 
that creates jobs and allows workers to stimulate the economy by 
spending more. 
</P>
<P>
	Another way out is to export goods. But exporters can lose  
profits if they are less competitive because of a stronger 
currency. 
</P>
<P>
	``The BOJ is strong-arming the dollar,'' said Ken Landon, senior  
currency strategist at Deutsche Bank in Tokyo, but the impact is 
likely to be short term. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar-buying spread to euro/yen transactions, although the  
euro had larger concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	European Commission President-designate Romano Prodi was  
reported to say that Italy might have to leave the Economic and 
Monetary Union because of its economic problems. Already, the 
European Union has allowed Italy to default on its first-year 
obligation to lower the debt to GDP ratio. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market took it as an undermining of the euro,'' said  
DelZenero. When Prodi later tried to clear up his remarks, ``the 
market shrugged off the clarification,'' DelZenero said. 
</P>
<P>
	Against other currencies, the dollar was quoted at 1.5428 Swiss  
francs, up from 1.5383, and 1.4714 Canadian dollars, up from 
1.4645. The British pound rose to $1.5913 from $1.5997. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on the euro's exchange rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8907 
German marks, up from 1.8835; 6.3412 French francs, up from 6.3170; 
and 1,872.66 Italian lire, up from 1,864.67. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
