<HEADLINE> Bush To Meet With Senate Supporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush makes his first trip  
to the Capitol on Tuesday as the front-runner for the Republican 
presidential nomination, and will meet privately with his 
supporters in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no public announcement of the meeting, but word was  
spread by personal letter from Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush ``will be joined by 20-plus senators who have endorsed his  
candidacy and who are hosting a meeting,'' Coverdell wrote in a 
letter sent to all GOP senators except rival White House contenders 
John McCain and Bob Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	``You would be more than welcome to attend if convenient to  
you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's campaign web site lists the names of 14 senators who have  
endorsed him. He has the support of 121 Republican House members, 
more than half the GOP rank and file. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., gave the Texas governor a  
big political boost recently. 
</P>
<P>
	Interviewed on the CNN program ``Evans, Novak, Hunt &AMP; Shields,''  
Hastert said Bush had ``really done a phenomenal job'' of rallying 
support in the party. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether the Texas governor had just about wrapped up the  
nomination, Hastert replied, ``I think so. I think, from somebody 
who just observes politics for a long time, it looks like pretty 
much a done deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has the first Washington fund-raiser of his candidacy  
scheduled for Tuesday evening. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
