<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ascent Reaches Agreement in Suits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Ascent Entertainment Group announced Monday it had  
reached an agreement to settle lawsuits filed by shareholders who 
challenged the sale of the Denver Nuggets, Colorado Avalanche and 
the new Pepsi Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Ascent spokesman Arthur Aaron denied the agreement canceled the  
$400 million deal with Bill Laurie, whose wife, Nancy, is heiress 
to the Wal-Mart fortune. The sale had been scheduled to close June 
30. 
</P>
<P>
	``We anticipate announcing a three-way agreement with the  
Lauries and the plaintiffs in the near future,'' Aaron said. ``This 
has been a three-way negotiation for the last couple of weeks, and 
the agreement in principal includes all three parties.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Ascent's news release muddied the issue by saying ``the  
agreement in principle provides that Ascent will conduct a new open 
auction for these assets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aaron said the agreement canceled Thursday's scheduled hearing  
on the shareholder lawsuits in Wilmington, Del., where Ascent is 
incorporated. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholders contend the sale price is as much as $150 million  
too low. They filed three separate lawsuits and claim Ascent did 
not follow an open-bidding process. They have also questioned 
Ascent chairman Charlie Lyons' role in the sale because of his 
plans to become a partner with the Lauries in the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Denver financier Donald Sturm had reportedly bid $440 million  
for the teams. 
</P>
<P>
	In another lawsuit, Colorado businessman Bjorn Erik Borgen and  
ski resort magnate George Gillett claim they negotiated a deal to 
buy the Avalanche for $80 million from the Lauries. 
</P>
<P>
	Borgen, former owner of Denver-based Founders mutual funds, also  
claimed he was discouraged from bidding on both teams and the new 
$160 million Pepsi Center, scheduled to open in the fall. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
