<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Natural Gas Falls on Less Demand  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Natural gas futures fell sharply Monday on the New York  
Mercantile Exchange as cooler weather across the eastern half of 
the country reduced demand from utilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Unleaded gasoline and crude futures also retreated. On other  
markets, coffee fell sharply, while cocoa rose. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas futures tumbled as temperatures in the Northeast and  
Southeast returned to normal or fell below-normal, during a period 
when temperatures usually are on the rise. 
</P>
<P>
	The moderating temperatures took the steam out of a rally that  
saw prices jump nearly 30 percent in the past three months on fears 
supplies in storage will not meet summer cooling demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas is used to power turbines for utilities, who see  
increased consumer demand for powering air conditioners and fans 
during the summer months. Some analysts also noted that supplies in 
storage appear to be ample for the coming months. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas prices also were pressured by the Commodity Futures  
Trading Commission's release late Friday of a report detailing 
investors' positions in the market. That report showed speculative 
positions made up a large share of recent futures purchases. Such a 
stake leaves market participants vulnerable to a sudden selloff. 
</P>
<P>
	The outlook for unleaded gasoline led to additional weakness in  
energy markets. Investors continue to fret about summer driving 
demand despite a recent sharp increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Gasoline inventories, however, have maintained a year-over-year  
surplus. Investors also speculated that cheap imports soon may come 
to market as sales in the United States continue to fetch greater 
profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas for July delivery fell 7.1 cents to $2.237 for each  
1,000 cubic feet; July crude fell 29 cents to $17.70 a barrel; July 
unleaded gasoline fell 1.12 cents to 51.18 cents a gallon; July 
heating oil fell .58 cent to 43.89 cents a gallon. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, North Sea Brent Blend crude oil for delivery in  
August fell 13 cents to $16.37 a barrel. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee futures tumbled on the Board of Trade of the City of New  
York as the latest forecasts for weather in Brazilian growing areas 
showed no signs of crop-damaging frost. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee's fortunes in the past few weeks have been tied to the  
outlook for poor growing weather in Brazil, the world's largest 
producer. 
</P>
<P>
	A sustained frost could damage young trees and reduce  
production, but the early cold weather period has seen little 
chance of that occurring. 
</P>
<P>
	Futures prices have held support, however, as supplies of  
gourmet-style arabica coffee out of Colombia are being marketed at 
a slower-than-expected rate. 
</P>
<P>
	September arabica coffee fell 2.35 cents to $1.055 a pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa futures jumped on the New York Board of Trade amid  
continued concern that Ivory Coast's deregulation of its cocoa 
marketing system could lead to supply disruptions later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivory Coast and Ghana are the two West African countries that  
produce a majority of the world's cocoa for use in making 
chocolate. The two are set to meet in July to consider cooperation 
pacts aimed at boosting prices, but skeptical market participants 
believe the two competitors will be unable to reach agreement and 
could enter a new marketing year with no formula for exports. That 
could lead to short-term supply disruptions. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivory Coast, which is the world's largest cocoa producer, also  
has been plagued by dry weather that have resulted in weak 
flowering in many major growing areas. While the cocoa tree is 
hardy enough to bounce back ahead of the new marketing year that 
begins Oct. 1, speculators are betting production will be 
curtailed. 
</P>
<P>
	September cocoa rose $34 to $1,157 a ton.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
