<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 13:50:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Government Expecting Big Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal government recorded a budget  
deficit in May as receipts slowed from April's flood of last-minute 
tax filers. 
</P>
<P>
	The May budget deficit was $24 billion compared with a $113.5  
billion surplus in April, the Treasury Department said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the government is still running an overall surplus this  
year that is more than double what it was at this time last year -- 
the first year of budget surpluses since 1969. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first eight months of fiscal 1999, which began Oct. 1,  
1998, the government surplus totaled $40.7 billion, compared with 
$16 billion for the same period in fiscal 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration is forecasting a surplus of $79.3  
billion for all of 1999, and congressional accountants are 
predicting $111 billion. The total 1998 surplus was $69 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, government spending of $122.6 billion was 19.7 percent  
below April's outlays of $152.7 billion, and 8.6 percent lower than 
the $134.1 billion spent in May 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said spending was lower in part because May 1 fell on a  
Saturday this year so that many government payments were instead 
made on Friday, April 30. 
</P>
<P>
	And since tax refund checks are paid only on Fridays, some  
checks that would have come out of May's receipts came out of 
April's instead. Refunds are counted by subtracting from government 
revenues, not adding to outlays. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, tax refunds of $112.7 billion so far this year are  
running 24.3 percent ahead of last year. That's in part because of 
a new $400 per child credit. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, government receipts dwindled by 63 percent last  
month, to $98.6 billion from the $226.1 billion collected during 
the April's tax filing rush. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
