</P>
<P>
	U.S., Europeans Pledge Cooperation  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- President Clinton and European leaders  
pledged greater cooperation today to ensure that minor trade 
disputes between economic giants don't mushroom into full-blown 
conflicts. Officials said their new conflict resolution system 
could have helped defuse two simmering fights involving European 
bans on bananas sold by American companies and U.S. beef raised 
with growth hormones. U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky 
said the two disputes, in which the United States is threatening 
nearly $300 million in punitive tariffs on European products, were 
brought up during the talks between Clinton and European Union 
officials, but there were no breakthroughs. 

</P>
<P>
	Commerce Sec. Wary of Steel Quotas  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. farmers and businesses that rely heavily  
on exports to other countries might suffer if the domestic steel 
industry obtains quotas on foreign steel, Commerce Secretary 
William Daley said today. The quotas could hurt U.S. steel 
companies as well if an international trade war erupts, cutting off 
U.S. exports from foreign markets, Daley said. He said a fifth of 
the steel used domestically goes into products later sent abroad. 

</P>
<P>
	EU Seeks Larger Probe of Coca-Cola  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Union today requested  
further investigations to find what caused dozens of people to 
become ill after drinking Coca-Cola products. The call for 
additional study came as its local distributors launched a European 
ad campaign defending their products as beyond reproach. Belgium 
banned all Coca-Cola soft drink products on June 14, and restored 
only some of its brands to store shelves on Thursday. France has 
stopped sales of all Coke cans produced at Dunkirk, although it is 
allowing sales of cans produced at the country's other Coke plant. 
Meanwhile, Ivory Coast seized nearly 50,000 cans of Coke imported 
from Europe as a precaution, trade officials said today. Coca-Cola 
was at 61 9/16, down 1 7/8. 

</P>
<P>
	EU Still Split on Chocolate Purity  
</P>
<P>
	LUXEMBOURG (AP) -- The European Union governments today failed to  
find an answer to a question that has divided them for years: How 
much vegetable fat -- other than cocoa butter -- can you put in 
chocolate and still call it chocolate? The EU interior ministers 
were close to an answer until Belgium rejected a compromise 
proposal, officials said. The EU's chocolate debate pits eight 
purist nations against seven that take a relaxed view of chocolate. 
Belgium, France, Italy, Spain, Luxembourg, Germany, Greece and the 
Netherlands ban cocoa-butter substitutes in chocolate. The others -- 
Britain, Ireland, Denmark, Portugal, Austria, Finland and Sweden -- 
don't. 

</P>
<P>
	AOL Invests in Satellite TV Service  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- America Online Inc. will invest $1.5 billion  
in DirecTV creator Hughes Electronics Corp. in an agreement that 
deepens ties between the world's largest Internet provider and the 
leading U.S. satellite TV service. Company executives said the deal 
would help increase DirecTV's subscriber base while boosting the 
market for AOL's planned interactive TV and high-speed Internet 
services. Analysts consider access to cable -- with its wide reach 
into American households -- crucial to AOL's campaign to convert to 
high-speed Internet delivery. But cable companies have resisted 
calls for them to allow open access to Internet service providers. 
AOL shares were at 115 13/16, up 3 13/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Intel Chosen for TV Set-Top Boxes  
</P>
<P>
	SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- Intel Corp. will provide Hughes  
Network Systems with microprocessors for its latest television 
set-top receivers, the companies announced today. Hughes, a leader 
in satellite products and network systems, will use Pentium MMX 
microprocessors in set-top boxes enabling Internet access as well 
as its own satellite-driven DirecTV service. For the Santa Clara, 
Calif.-based Intel, the world's largest chip maker, it signals a 
significant foray outside the personal computer business. 

</P>
<P>
	Study: National Homeownership Soars  
</P>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- National homeownership soared in 1998  
and probably will continue increasing for the next decade, 
according to a new study. Low mortgage interest rates and low 
unemployment get the credit. The study released today by Harvard 
University's Joint Center for Housing Studies found that about 1.8 
million homes have been built each year since 1996, and that the 
national homeownership rate reached 66.3 percent last year. The 
report says more members of minority groups are buying homes but 
their homeownership rates still lag those of whites. Education is a 
factor, according to the report. 

</P>
<P>
	Allergy Drug Hismanal Withdrawn  
</P>
<P>
