<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 07:46:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Individuals Can Savor Stars' Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Ken Hitchcock kept saying his Dallas Stars didn't  
want this season to end because they were having so much fun 
chasing the Stanley Cup. Now that it's theirs, they probably won't 
mind taking time to savor what they've accomplished. 
</P>
<P>
	For Ed Belfour, Brett Hull and Mike Modano, winning the Cup  
means trading in their tainted reputation for a new identity: NHL 
champion. 
</P>
<P>
	For 39-year-old Guy Carbonneau, 38-year-old Craig Ludwig and  
36-year-old Brian Skrudland, former Cup winners who kept playing to 
relive the satisfaction, victory feels even better than they 
remembered. 
</P>
<P>
	And for grinders Derian Hatcher and Pat Verbeek, knowing their  
name will forever be engraved on their sport's most cherished 
trophy is affirmation that all the lumps and bruises were worth it. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a special, magical group that will never be  
repeated,'' Hitchcock said early Sunday following a 2-1 
triple-overtime victory over the Buffalo Sabres that secured a 4-2 
series win. ``We may have more talented teams or more skilled 
teams, but we'll never be as tight as this group.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars were the best regular-season team the past two years  
and, if they didn't win the Cup, critics would have said they 
peaked too soon. 
</P>
<P>
	But winning the Presidents' Trophy came in handy when Game 7 of  
the Western Conference finals between top-seeded Dallas and 
second-seeded Colorado was played at Reunion Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Sabres learned the Stars still had plenty of energy and  
passion left as they rallied from a loss in the opener, then won 
two straight games after being tied 2-2. 
</P>
<P>
	In their sixth season in Dallas, the franchise that began as the  
Minnesota North Stars ended a 32-year wait for the organization's 
first title, matching the longest in NHL history. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars also became the league's first champions from the Sun  
Belt -- a concept hockey fans never could have imagined when the 
'90s began. 
</P>
<P>
	A look at some of the people who made it possible and what it  
took to do it: 
</P>
<P>
	--Belfour had played more postseason games (107) without winning  
a championship than any goaltender in league history, which led to 
the knock he cracks under pressure. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``Eagle'' soared this postseason, maintaining his cool  
during a 16-7 championship run that included two triple-overtime 
victories. 
</P>
<P>
	``I stayed focused and I stayed strong,'' said Belfour, who  
outplayed Patrick Roy in the Western finals and was at least the 
equal of Dominik Hasek in the finals. 
</P>
<P>
	The championship also saved Belfour's job, as Dallas will look  
to trade promising backup Roman Turek rather than expose him in the 
upcoming expansion draft. 
</P>
<P>
	--Joe Nieuwendyk's absence from the playoffs last year left  
Dallas a scorer away from challenging Detroit in the conference 
finals. Now the Stars really know what they were missing as he led 
the playoffs with 11 goals, including a record-tying six 
game-winners. 
</P>
<P>
	He was voted postseason MVP for the second time, a decade after  
leading Calgary to the Cup. The Flames traded him to Dallas because 
they thought he was too fragile; overcoming surgeries on both knees 
and enduring a grueling rehabilitation that sidelined him early 
this season proved he's not. 
</P>
<P>
	--Hull was brought in to be a postseason sharpshooter and he was,  
scoring the Cup-winning goal and knocking in the game-winner in 
Game 2. He did it all despite groin and knee injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	--Modano shed the pretty-boy image that's hung over him his  
entire career. No one played better the last two games and he did 
it despite a broken wrist. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ludwig and Skrudland, teammates on the 1986 Cup-winning  
Montreal Canadiens, went 13 years between titles, the longest span 
in league history. 
</P>
<P>
	--Mike Keane, whose two goals in Game 7 of the conference finals  
ousted his former Colorado teammates, became the ninth player to 
win titles with three clubs. Next up for Keane is getting this Cup 
tattooed on his ankle next to ink images of the trophies he won 
with Colorado in 1996 and Montreal in '93. 
</P>
<P>
	Carbonneau, the league's oldest player this season, also won his  
third title. 
</P>
<P>
	--Benoit Hogue missed three weeks with two torn knee ligaments,  
then played the final two games. By delaying surgery, he risked 
further injury and guaranteed he won't be ready for the start of 
next season, which will make it tough for the free agent to find a 
job. 
</P>
<P>
	--General manager Bob Gainey, who won five Stanley Cups in his  
Hall of Fame playing career, put the team together in his own 
image. Third-year owner Tom Hicks opened his checkbook to let him 
do it. 
</P>
<P>
	--Hitchcock, a successful coach in midgets and juniors for 16  
years who didn't get a shot at the NHL until slimming down from 478 
pounds, pushed, pulled and laid off his players at all the right 
times to get the most out of the second-oldest team (30.6 years) to 
win an NHL title. Toronto in 1967 averaged 31.4. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you see the absolute joy and the raw emotions of the  
players, it's unbelievable,'' Hitchcock said. ``You appreciate what 
it takes to get here.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
