<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Evacuation Escalates to Near Riot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONROE, Va. (AP) -- Angry at being cooped up in stuffy buses  
after their job training center had been evacuated for a bomb 
threat, students clashed with police equipped with riot gear. 
</P>
<P>
	Students spat on officers and threw cigarette lighters and  
balled-up T-shirts at them during the confrontation Sunday at the 
Old Dominion Job Corps Center. No one was injured, police and 
school officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 40 police officers squared off against the students, and  
prepared to use a high-pressure water hose in case the students 
charged, said Amherst County Sheriff L.T. Ayers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just a mess there for about an hour or so,'' Ayers  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The residential training center was evacuated after authorities  
received two bomb threats telephoned from inside the campus. No 
bomb was found and no arrest had been made as of today, center 
administrator Bob Barlow said. 
</P>
<P>
	Students were told to sit in stuffy buses and vans for nearly  
two hours because it was raining and police had to wait for 
bomb-sniffing dogs to arrive, Barlow said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were sitting there for about two hours without bathrooms  
and proper ventilation,'' Barlow said. 
</P>
<P>
	The confrontation began after a 17-year-old became disruptive,  
and was dragged off a bus by deputies who sprayed him with pepper 
spray. 
</P>
<P>
	The 17-year-old was charged with obstruction of justice and  
assault on a police officer, Ayers said. The young man was being 
held in a juvenile detention center today and was not identified. 
</P>
<P>
	About 300 students from across Virginia and a few other states  
attend the center, operated by the U.S. Department of Labor. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
