<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Avalanch's Forsberg To Have Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Colorado Avalanche center Peter Forsberg will  
undergo surgery next week to repair an unstable left shoulder and 
is expected to be sidelined for four to six months. 
</P>
<P>
	``We anticipate nothing less than a complete recovery,'' said  
Avalanche trainer Pat Karns. 
</P>
<P>
	Forsberg aggravated the shoulder problems when he was hit by  
Dallas Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk during the playoffs. 
Avalanche coaches complained about the hit. 
</P>
<P>
	Forsberg led the Avalanche in points (97) and assists (67) and  
also was their leading scorer during the playoffs. His 24 playoff 
points led the league. 
</P>
<P>
	``Peter was examined by our medical staff at the end of the  
season, and after undergoing additional tests in Denver, sought a 
second opinion back in Sweden,'' Karns said. ``A few days ago, the 
same diagnosis was reached by the Swedish doctors, and the decision 
to move ahead with surgery was taken,'' Karns said. 
</P>
<P>
	Team orthopedist Dr. Andy Parker will perform the surgery.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
