<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Noon EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Praises Slovenia  
</P>
<P>
	LJUBLJANA, Slovenia (AP) -- President Clinton became the first  
U.S. president to visit Slovenia today and congratulated the former 
Yugoslav republic for breaking away from Slobodan Milosevic. 
Clinton and Slovenian President Milan Kucan shared two grinning 
handshakes as Clinton praised Slovenia for its economic revival and 
stability. Slovenia won independence in 1991 and now wants to join 
NATO. Clinton will also meet Milo Djukanovic, the president of 
Montenegro, the smaller of the two remaining Yugoslav republics. 
The pro-Western Djukanovic has opposed Milosevic's policies. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton: No Yugoslav Economic Aid  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- ``Not a penny'' of U.S. money will be used  
to help rebuild parts of Yugoslavia, President Clinton pledged 
today, especially with Slobodan Milosevic still in power. Clinton 
said rebuilding Yugoslavia's infrastructure would constitute 
economic assistance that he didn't feel comfortable extending while 
Milosevic is still president. Clinton did say the United States 
would help with humanitarian aid, such as repairing hospitals and 
power plants to restore electricity to the Serb population. 

</P>
<P>
	Court To Rule on TV Sex Channels  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to decide  
whether a federal law intended to shield children from sex-oriented 
cable TV networks violates the free-speech rights of channels such 
as Playboy Television. The justices said they will review a Clinton 
administration appeal aimed at reviving the law, which a federal 
judge in Delaware struck down. The judge said the law swept too 
broadly in trying to keep children from seeing adult programming on 
networks only partly scrambled for non-subscribers. The law 
required cable operators that don't fully scramble or block 
sex-oriented networks for non-subscribers to show those channels' 
``indecent'' programs only between 10 p.m. and 6 a.m. 

</P>
<P>
	AMA Wrestles With Doctors Union  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Doctors frustrated with the managed care system  
will discuss forming a physicians' union today at the American 
Medical Association convention. One doctor said his colleagues are 
angry that third parties have intruded into their day-to-day 
practice. The five-day convention includes 494 delegates 
representing about one-third of U.S. physicians. AMA board 
president Dr. Randolph D. Smoak Jr. said that the union might be a 
non-traditional one, without permitting strikes. 

</P>
<P>
	China Working on Cloning Panda  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Scientists have taken a step toward cloning a  
giant panda by growing an embryo that contains a dead animal's 
genes -- a development China hailed as a possible breakthrough in 
efforts to save the endangered species. Only about 1,000 pandas 
live in the wild, with another 100 in zoos. Experts have warned 
that the animal could become extinct in a couple of dozen years. 
Scientists grew the embryo by introducing cells from a dead female 
panda into the egg cells of a Japanese white rabbit. 

</P>
<P>
	Study: National Homeownership Soars  
</P>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- A new study shows that national  
homeownership soared last year and will continue to rise, thanks to 
the lowest mortgage interest and unemployment rates since the 
1960s. Harvard University's Joint Center for Housing Studies found 
that about 1.8 million homes have been built each year since 1996, 
and that the national homeownership rate reached 66.3 percent last 
year. Most of the growth has occurred outside of cities and in the 
South and the West. Although more minorities are buying homes 
because of low interest rates and specially tailored mortgage loan 
programs, the gap between white and nonwhite home ownership widened 
from 1994 to 1998, the study found. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 39  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before noon EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 39.26 to 10,816.30. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,390-1,282. The Nasdaq was up 30.13 to 
2,593.57. 

</P>
<P>
	Sampras Begins Defense of Title  
</P>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- Defending champion and top seed Pete  
Sampras returned to his favorite stage today and began his bid for 
a sixth Wimbledon title by beating Scott Draper 6-3, 6-4, 6-4. 
Sampras won the first three games and never faced a break point in 
eliminating the 63rd-ranked Australian in 88 minutes. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief By VINCENT CINISOMO  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
