<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Monday on the New York Stock Exchange, Nasdaq Stock Market, 
and American Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	
</P>
<P>
	Holophane, up 9 5/8 at 37 15/16  
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta-based National Service Industries agreed to acquire  
Holophane for $38.50 a share, or $450 million. The purchase of 
Holophane, based in Columbus, Ohio, will strengthen National 
Service's position as the largest North American producer of 
industrial and outdoor lighting equipment. 

</P>
<P>
	KN Energy, down 5 1/8 at 13  
</P>
<P>
	Sempra Energy and KN broke off their planned merger, saying the  
combined utility company would fall short of achieving its business 
objectives. Sempra, based in San Diego, will reimburse KN, based in 
Lakewood, Colo., $5.95 million for costs related to the deal. 

</P>
<P>
	Premier Bancshares, down 2 1/2 at 17 3/8  
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta-based company won't meet second-quarter profit  
forecasts due to weakness in its mortgage and commercial banking 
operations. Premier also noted one-time expenses related to pending 
acquisitions and a lawsuit settlement. 

</P>
<P>
	DLJdirect, up 2 11/16 at 31 1/4  
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch initiated coverage of the online broker with a  
near-term rating of ``accumulate,'' CNBC reported. DLJDirect, 84 
percent owned by Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, went public about a 
month ago, selling 16.0 million shares at $20 apiece. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	
</P>
<P>
	Metricom, up 4 13/16 at 15 7/8  
</P>
<P>
	Vulcan Ventures and MCI WorldCom are investing $300 million each  
in convertible shares of Metricom to fund a national rollout of 
Metricom's mobile data service. If converted, the shares would 
leave Vulcan, owned by Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen, with a 49 
percent stake in Metricom. MCI WorldCom would have a 38 percent 
stake in Metricom, which is based in Los Gatos, Calif. 

</P>
<P>
	Phoenix Technologies, up 4 3/8 at 16 1/16  
</P>
<P>
	Softbank Holdings is buying a 20 percent stake in ebetween, a  
new Phoenix unit designed to help Internet service and content 
providers to reach and retain online users. As part of the deal, 
Phoenix is acquiring Softbank's electronic registration unit, 
Softbank Marketing Solutions. 

</P>
<P>
	KeraVision, up 2 7/16 at 11 7/16  
</P>
<P>
	The developer of a non-laser surgical treatment for  
near-sightedness expects to report second-quarter revenue at least 
50 percent above analyst expectations. KeraVision, based in 
Fremont, Calif., said it has trained 187 ophthalmic surgeons to 
perform its Intacs myopia treatment since receiving FDA approval 
April 9. 

</P>
<P>
	Iridium World Communications, up 1 9/32 at 9 1/32  
</P>
<P>
	The near-bankrupt satellite phone service unveiled a new  
marketing initiative with price cuts of up to 65 percent and flat 
per-minute rates for international calls. Iridium backers Motorola 
and Kyocera also announced price cuts on mobile phones for the 
satellite service. 

</P>
