<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flamboyant Fashion Exec Killed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BATAVIA, N.Y. (AP) -- Fashion executive John Badum lived in New  
York's East Village, filling his fast-paced world with stylish 
friends and exuberant, over-the-top gestures. He loved costume 
parties, a good loud laugh, anything flamboyant. 
</P>
<P>
	If Badum's life was musical theater, his death was pure opera:  
He was killed with a meat cleaver by his former boyfriend, who then 
threw himself to his death in front of a minivan. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said it was a green card dispute that led Badum, 46, from  
New York's fashion world to his sister's apartment in Batavia, 
where the May 30 attack occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Badum's sister, Theresa Badum, 40, had married Hamid Ouhda, a  
23-year-old Moroccan, earlier this year at her brother's request in 
hopes that Ouhda could get a green card to stay in the United 
States, police said. But the relationship between Badum and Ouhda 
soon soured, and the Badums sought to dissolve the marriage and 
deport Ouhda. 
</P>
<P>
	Ouhda found out and apparently flew into a murderous rage.  
</P>
<P>
	Ouhda climbed to Ms. Badum's second-floor balcony, slammed a  
brick through a sliding glass door and went to the kitchen, where 
he found a cleaver and knife, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Badums locked themselves in a bedroom. But Ouhda broke the  
door and lunged inside. Ms. Badum, after fending off blows, fled 
through a fire escape. Ouhda stabbed Badum at least a half a dozen 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	With his dying breaths, Badum identified Ouhda as his attacker.  
</P>
<P>
	An hour after the attack, Ouhda died after apparently walking in  
front of a minivan on a country road. The driver told police it was 
as if Ouhda was attacking the van. 
</P>
<P>
	At a memorial for Badum last week, friends gathered at an  
elegant New York City hotel amid champagne, chandeliers and 
chocolate to read poems and share songs. 
</P>
<P>
	Barneys New York creative director Simon Doonan remembered his  
friend as ``a combination of Albert Einstein, Louis IX, Phyllis 
Diller, Mama Cass and Liberace,'' and said Badum maintained a salon 
where he gathered artists, aristocrats and rock stars together. His 
circle of friends included designers Todd Oldham and Thierry 
Mugler. 
</P>
<P>
	Heavyset with flowing black hair, Badum also ``had a bit of the  
old hippie about him,'' Doonan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mugler described how Badum would act out roles and bring him to  
a belly laugh. ``He was so incredibly brilliant,'' Mugler said. 
</P>
<P>
	Friends also recalled particular eccentricities: his fondness  
for hand-held fans and ``pinkie-popping,'' or flipping his pinkie 
straight into the air. And also his generosity, which ranged from 
opening his home to newcomers getting settled in town, to passing 
out money, vitamins and sneakers to Jamaican children during trips 
there. 
</P>
<P>
	``He combined an incredible joie de vivre with a genuine  
philanthropic streak,'' Doonan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years after Badum's arrival as national sales manager at  
L'Zinger, the Go Silk label was launched. At its height, L'Zinger 
generated $30 million in sales on the popularity of the oversized 
silk shirt. 
</P>
<P>
	He resigned from the company in 1995 and spent the last few  
years traveling around the world, only recently returning to New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	Weeks before his death, Badum and his sister feared trouble from  
Ouhda. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Badum contacted a lawyer to discuss divorce proceedings and  
Ouhda's status with the Immigration and Naturalization Service. The 
lawyer advised Ms. Badum to seek an order of protection. 
</P>
<P>
	She filed for the order May 27, three days before the attack.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
