<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Cuts Budget To Help Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Germany unveiled its most drastic postwar  
spending cuts today in an effort to make Europe's biggest economy 
more competitive and boost the euro currency. The proposed budget 
reform would cut corporate taxes next year by $4.2 billion and cut 
government spending by 1.5 percent, according to a Finance Ministry 
document. The plan's broader goal is a balanced budget sometime 
between 2002 and 2006. 
</P>
<P>
	If adopted, the reform ``will give an important signal for the  
stability of the euro,'' the document said. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said with the $15.9 billion in proposed spending  
cuts next year, it had sealed ``largest savings package in postwar 
German history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's Cabinet is expected to approve  
the plan before the end of June, then submit it to parliament. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
