<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lemieux Will Take Less Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Mario Lemieux's revised plan for rescuing the  
Pittsburgh Penguins calls for ousting both Civic Arena landlord SMG 
and broadcaster Fox Sports Net Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux filed his plan with bankruptcy court on Monday and  
representatives of SMG and Fox met with Lemieux's lawyers 
throughout the day. Lemieux's plan was scheduled to be confirmed in 
bankruptcy court Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The talks are accelerated and intense, because of the  
deadline,'' Fox spokesman Larry Eldridge said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the revised plan, the NHL Hall of Famer said he would pay  
himself substantially less than he originally proposed and give up 
his right to sue former Penguins co-owner Roger Marino for past 
wages. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the revisions, other creditors of the team also would  
abandon their claims against Marino. In return, Marino will make a 
$500,000 payment to the team's unsecured creditors and pay off a 
loan the team took from the NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux's new plan calls for converting $20 million of his $32.5  
million in debt into an ownership stake in the team. He will get a 
$5 million payment and forgive the other $7.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The old plan called for him to be repaid the entire amount over  
10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux also said he would have $50 million in new money to  
operate the team and satisfy some debts if his plan is approved. 
The Penguins have been operating with court protection from 
creditors since last fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides Lemieux's plan, the NHL has filed a plan to sell the  
team and move it from Pittsburgh or dissolve the franchise and 
auction off its players. SMG and Fox also have submitted a 
reorganization plan that would make Lemieux a minority owner and 
consultant. Lemieux has rejected that offer. 
</P>
<P>
	SMG lost its control over the Penguins' agreement at the Civic  
Arena when U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Bernard Markovitz invalidated the 
deal earlier this month. On Friday, he ruled that it was a loan, 
not a lease as SMG had argued. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux's new plan calls on Markovitz to determine how much is  
owed on the $24 million loan SMG made to help former Penguins owner 
Howard Baldwin buy the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux's plan also calls on SMG to repay with interest any  
amount the judge determines the Penguins may have overpaid in 
satisfying the loan. 
</P>
<P>
	As far as Fox's broadcast rights are concerned, the revised plan  
calls for a newly reorganized Penguins franchise to make a deal 
with a broadcaster without identifying the media outlet. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirby Campbell, chief executive of the Kittanning-based  
Armstrong Group of Companies, which includes a cable company, has 
said he is talking with Lemieux about joining the former center's 
investment team. Campbell did not return calls for comment Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox spokesman Eldridge said that his company remained interested  
in broadcasting Penguins games. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux's revised plan also calls for his investment team to  
retain rights to the American Hockey League franchise in the 
Scranton Wilkes-Barre area. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
