<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Police Can Search Cars for Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Police generally do not need a warrant to  
search a car they have reason to believe is carrying illegal drugs, 
the Supreme Court said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The court ruled in a Maryland case that a search warrant is not  
required even if police had plenty of time to get one after 
receiving a tip that a car would be carrying drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	The court reinstated Kevin Darnell Dyson's conviction of  
conspiracy to possess cocaine with intent to distribute. 
</P>
<P>
	Dyson was arrested early in the morning of July 3, 1996, in St.  
Mary's County. At 11 a.m. on the previous day, police received an 
informant's tip that Dyson would return to the county that night in 
a rental car after going to New York City to buy cocaine. 
</P>
<P>
	The informant gave a description and license number of the  
rental car, and police confirmed with the rental company that the 
car had been rented to Dyson. 
</P>
<P>
	Police stopped Dyson and searched his car at about 1 a.m.,  
finding 23 grams of crack cocaine in a bag in the trunk. Dyson was 
convicted after a trial judge ruled the police could search his car 
without a warrant once they had reason to believe it contained 
evidence of a crime. 
</P>
<P>
	A mid-level Maryland appeals court reversed, saying the search  
was unlawful because police would have had time to get a warrant. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, the Supreme Court ruled in an unsigned opinion that the  
police did not need a warrant. 
</P>
<P>
	The Constitution's Fourth Amendment generally requires police to  
get a warrant before conducting a search, but the court established 
an exception in 1925 for automobile searches. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices noted they ruled in 1982 and 1996 that once police  
have reason to believe a car contains contraband, they can search 
it without having to show some emergency existed. 
</P>
<P>
	All nine justices agreed the police did not need a warrant in  
Dyson's case. But Justice Stephen G. Breyer dissented from the 
result, saying the court should not reverse the lower court without 
hearing arguments in a case where the defendant's lawyer did not 
file a response to prosecutors' appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Maryland vs. Dyson, 98-1062.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 00:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sprewell May Play Point Guard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Desperation. It is a word that aptly describes  
the New York Knicks' predicament in the NBA Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	So here comes a new plot twist, just in time for Game 3 tonight  
between the Knicks and San Antonio Spurs. Expect some new lineups 
from the Knicks, who are open to suggestions on how to slow down 
the sweepmobile currently being driven down Broadway by co-pilots 
Tim Duncan and David Robinson. 
</P>
<P>
	While Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy hedged on his lineup  
intentions, Latrell Sprewell publicly lobbied for a change Sunday 
that would move him to point guard with Allan Houston at shooting 
guard. Van Gundy called Sprewell's suggestion a ``viable option, 
but we won't start that way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs lead New York 2-0 in the best-of-7 series, which is in  
need of rescuing on several fronts -- quality of play, television 
ratings and possibly, duration. If the Spurs keep playing their 
calm, effective style and the Knicks' changes don't make any 
difference, the broom-waving fans in San Antonio won't get to watch 
another game in the Alamodome. 
</P>
<P>
	The teams are tentatively scheduled to play three games at  
Madison Square Garden this week. The Spurs only need to win two. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to put serious pressure on them by winning the third  
game and kind of put the series out of reach,'' said Tim Duncan, 
averaging 29.0 points, 15.5 rebounds and three blocks in the first 
two games. ``But to stay alive, for them, that's the game they need 
right there. Going down 3-0 would be a tough thing, next to 
impossible, to come back from.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, no team in NBA history has ever come back from a 3-0  
deficit in any round of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody out in San Antonio thinks it's won already,'' the  
Spurs' Sean Elliott said. ``Guys in here know we still have a lot 
of work to do. The series probably isn't even started.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That is what NBC and the league must be hoping, but alas, it's  
not true. Ratings for Game 1 were down 36 percent from last year's 
Bulls-Jazz opener, and overnight ratings for Game 2 were even 
worse. Spurs guard Mario Elie said the quality of play might be one 
reason fans are reaching for the remote control. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been nasty,'' Elie said.  
</P>
<P>
	More so for the Knicks than for the Spurs. New York averaged 72  
points in the two losses and is still searching for a way to 
replace Patrick Ewing's offense. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks' point guards, Charlie Ward and Chris Childs, are  
averaging 9.0 points and 5.0 assists. Childs is 3-for-16. Larry 
Johnson, hindered by a sprained knee, is shooting 20 percent from 
the field, and Marcus Camby has been hindered because of foul 
trouble after playing a pivotal role in the Knicks' victory over 
the Indiana Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	Thus, Van Gundy was bombarded by questions about his lineup on  
Sunday. One possibility is sending Ward to the bench and playing 
Sprewell at the point with Houston at shooting guard. The Knicks 
used such a lineup in Game 2 against the Pacers when Ward and 
Childs were in foul trouble. Sprewell said the team has run plays 
in practice with him playing point guard. 
</P>
<P>
	``It worked then, who's to say if it'll work now,'' Sprewell  
said. ``We don't know, but at least it's worth a try, I think, at 
some point during the game. ... Maybe that's something that can 
create a mismatch that favors us. 
</P>
<P>
	``If something's working, then I think you need to work it until  
they find a way to stop it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It would mean the hobbled Johnson would have to guard the  
quicker Elliott. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the opportunity arises, I'll try to take him to the basket,  
absolutely,'' Elliott said. 
</P>
<P>
	Spurs coach Gregg Popovich said using a full-court press to  
exploit Sprewell's shaky ballhandling skills wouldn't be an option. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't remember the last time we pressed,'' Popovich said.  
``I don't think we've ever pressed, ever. Not once.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy said he doesn't necessarily favor changing the  
starters, but he doesn't rule out going to the big guard lineup at 
some point during the game. A more likely change is Kurt Thomas or 
Camby for Chris Dudley, who is so bothered by a hyperextended elbow 
that he was practicing free throws left-handed on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you make all the changes that everybody wants -- start  
Marcus, Kurt, Larry, Allan and Latrell -- your bench now has two 
point guards and an unhealthy Chris Dudley,'' Van Gundy said. 
</P>
<P>
	No tinkering should be expected from Popovich, whose team is on  
an NBA-record 12-game postseason winning streak -- including 6-0 on 
the road. San Antonio hasn't lost since Game 2 of the first round 
against Minnesota on May 11. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're a focused group,'' Elie said. ``We know what's at stake,  
we know what we have to do. We're the `Road Warriors.' We went to 
Minnesota and won two, to Portland won two, to the Lakers and won 
two. We don't feel any different coming into the Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we can get Game 3, we might as well finish them off.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
