<DOCNO> APW19990621.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 14:32:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Parade Honors Stanley Cup Champs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The Dallas Stars' bandwagon rolled through  
downtown today as thousands of fans gathered for a parade to honor 
the Stanley Cup champions. 
</P>
<P>
	Captain Derian Hatcher hoisted the silver NHL championship cup  
and forward Mike Modano chomped on a cigar while riding on a float. 
</P>
<P>
	The parade started at City Hall and snaked through downtown  
toward a victory party at Reunion Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Forward Dave Reid waved to fans while wearing a black cowboy  
hat. On another float, team owner Tom Hicks sported new cowboy 
boots emblazoned with an image of the cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans along the route waved green flags and cheered their  
champions, who won the cup with a triple-overtime victory over 
Buffalo that ended early Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've lost a lot of sleep but it's been thrilling,'' said one  
fan, who had green and white ribbons pinned to her shoulders. 
``It's so great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vendors along the parade route found booming business. A booth  
selling $25 T-shirts and $10 golf caps was crowded with buyers. 
</P>
<P>
	For the better part of this spring, the Stars managed to capture  
the imagination of a city that usually reserves its excitement for 
Super Bowls. 
</P>
<P>
	Flags flew from automobiles, power plays were discussed at water  
coolers and more attention was given to Modano's bum wrist than to 
Deion Sanders' bad toe. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stanley Cup victory sparked celebrations that began in  
sports bars and spilled into downtown streets. 
</P>
<P>
	``The city is appreciative of what the Stars have done,'' said  
Tom Burke of Dallas, who was one of hundreds waiting Sunday at a 
grocery store for tickets to the victory rally. ``The city has 
embraced the Stars. We feel like we know the players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 200 fans were waiting for the Stars when they arrived at  
the airport at 6:45 a.m. Sunday, and 16,000 tickets for today's 
rally were quickly snapped up. 
</P>
<P>
	The hysteria surrounding the first Stanley Cup's first trip to  
Texas hasn't been lost on the Stars themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've come from the point where people didn't know what a goal  
was or any of the rules to everybody being crazy about the sport -- 
it's gone 180 degrees,'' said Craig Ludwig, one of three former 
Minnesota North Stars still on the roster. ``It's incredible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before this weekend, no professional team from the Dallas area  
had ever won a championship in a major sport other than football. 
The Cowboys have won five Super Bowls. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas Rangers have been in Dallas since 1972, but have won  
just one playoff game. The Dallas Mavericks arrived in 1980 and 
haven't been in the playoffs since 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's brought the whole city together,'' Rob Parker of Dallas  
said. ``There are no barriers, racial or otherwise, when you talk 
about the Stars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first title in the franchise's 32-year history came six  
years after previous owner Norm Green moved the team from 
Minneapolis because of small crowds. 
</P>
<P>
	When the club arrived in Texas, the Dallas fans certainly  
weren't the most knowledgeable, but Hicks saw enough interest to 
buy the team in December 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Hicks had deep pockets but there was also the front-office savvy  
of general manager Bob Gainey and the steadiness of coach Ken 
Hitchcock. 
</P>
<P>
	As the wins started to multiply, so did the fans. The Stars had  
the NHL's best regular-season record in each of the past two years, 
and seats at Reunion Arena gradually became some of the hottest 
tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	And now, with the Cup theirs and the celebration still at a  
fever pitch, fans say they are just starting to realize how much 
progress the game has made in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a real struggle to attain a championship and  
respectability for the fans,'' Cliff Steward of Dallas said. ``The 
Stars have had to fight for any visibility.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 18:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> O'Brien Withdraws From US Nationals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- Olympic champion and world-record  
decathlete Dan O'Brien withdrew from the U.S. track championships 
on Monday because of turf toe. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Brien will not participate in the meet, held in Eugene, Ore.,  
from June 24-27, because of the injury to his left foot. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am extremely disappointed that I will not be able to compete  
this week in front of an Oregon home crowd,'' O'Brien said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Brien won the gold medal in the decathlon at the 1996  
Olympics, holds the world record in the 10-event competition and is 
a three-time world champion. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Brien, who turns 33 next month, said the International Amateur  
Athletic Federation may grant him a wild-card invitation that would 
allow him to compete for his fourth world championship despite not 
participating in the U.S. event. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am hopeful that I will be given this opportunity and that my  
foot will heal so that I can still reach my goal of 9,000 points at 
the 1999 World Championships.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The World Championships will be held from August 21-29 at  
Seville, Spain. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
