<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico City Rattled by Small Quake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Office buildings swayed and workers swarmed  
into the streets of the capital Monday when the second earthquake 
in as many weeks hit Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no immediate reports of damage or injuries from  
Monday's quake, whose epicenter was a sparsely populated mountain 
area 165 miles southwest of Mexico City, according to the U.S. 
Geological Survey in Golden, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency estimated the quake's magnitude at 5.7, while  
Mexico's National Seismological Service placed the temblor's 
strength at 5.8 -- neither approaching the strength of the 
6.7-magnitude quake that struck central Mexico on June 15. 
</P>
<P>
	That earthquake killed at least 17 people and injuring nearly  
200. It also damaged or destroyed more than 7,700 homes and 
numerous colonial-era churches in the states of Puebla and Oaxaca. 
</P>
<P>
	Radio reports from Puebla indicated the quake was felt only  
slightly there. There were no reports on whether any of the 
structures damaged in last week's quake had been weakened further 
by Monday's temblor. 
</P>
<P>
	Nervous residents in Mexico City poured into the streets, and  
some said they were disturbed by the length of the quake. The June 
15 temblor lasted a few seconds, while Monday's quake featured 32 
seconds of unpleasant swaying. 
</P>
<P>
	``These quakes are frequently felt more strongly in Mexico City  
than near the epicenter'' because the city is built on an extremely 
unstable former lake bed, said Bill Smith, a seismologist at the 
U.S. Geological Survey. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
