<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> San Diego Utility Expected To Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Sempra Energy is expected to shop around for  
new acquisitions after its planned purchase of Colorado-based KN 
Energy for nearly $2 billion collapsed Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Utility industry analysts said Sempra still seeks to expand its  
natural gas transmission and storage capacity and, with some $800 
million in cash on hand, has the resources to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	The San Diego-based utility, which has been aggressively  
expanding its Latin American investments this year, also badly 
wants to add new markets to its U.S. holdings -- something the KN 
Energy deal would have helped it to do, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They obviously have bigger ambitions and I'm sure they are on  
the prowl for another company,'' said Edward J. Tirello of Deutsche 
Bank Alex. Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	Likely candidates for an acquisition or merger are Columbia  
Energy Group, based in Herndon, Va., or El Paso Energy Corp., 
analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still think they would like to be a larger national company  
and I think they will look for ways to do so,'' said Michael Heim, 
a natural gas industry analyst for A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons. 
</P>
<P>
	If the KN Energy deal had gone through, Sempra would have  
assumed about $4 billion in the Colorado company's debt in addition 
to a payment of about $1.9 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Sempra would have extended its natural gas pipeline 25,000 miles  
throughout the Midwest and boosted its customer base to become the 
largest of any utility company nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	The two utilities provided little information about why the deal  
fell through. A joint statement said ``it was more prudent for both 
companies to pursue their business objectives individually.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the agreement to end the merger talks, Sempra agreed  
to pay KN Energy nearly $6 million as reimbursement for expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Sempra shares closed Monday down $1.12 1/2, or 4.7 percent, at  
$22.81 1/4 on the New York Stock Exchange. The volume of 5.3 million 
shares was more than seven times the average. 
</P>
<P>
	KN Energy, which also warned that its second quarter earnings  
would fall below expectations, was battered in heavy trading. The 
stock fell 28 percent, or $5.12 1/2, to close at $13. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it would see a loss of 20 to 25 cents per share  
in the second quarter instead of the 16 cent profit projected by 
analysts surveyed by First Call. 
</P>
<P>
	KN Energy, the nation's sixth-largest natural gas company, said  
the shortfall was caused by record warm winter temperatures two 
years in a row. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
