<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colder Climate May Stifle Volcanoes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Do ice ages suppress volcanoes?  
</P>
<P>
	Scientists have long known that the gases blasted into the air  
by volcanoes can cool the climate. Now, it appears, this may be a 
two-way street. 
</P>
<P>
	A study of volcanoes in eastern California indicates that, over  
millions of years, eruptions occurred in between cycles of colder 
climate, prompting researchers to speculate that glacial conditions 
may have suppressed the volcanoes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The correlation between volcanic outbursts and climate  
suggests that the two are linked,'' a team of researchers says in a 
paper appearing in the journal Geophysical Research Letters. 
</P>
<P>
	And California isn't the only place that a similar correlation  
occurs, lead researcher Allen F. Glazner said in a telephone 
interview. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought it was kind of crazy until I went to the library''  
and found similar patterns reported by other researchers, said 
Glazner, a University of North Carolina geology professor. 
</P>
<P>
	Volcanic suppression could have occurred in several ways, he  
said, including changes in the stress on the earth's crust caused 
by the weight of ice or lake water, and changes in the amount and 
location of water underground in the area where magma is building 
volcanoes. 
</P>
<P>
	``None of those things is going to suppress a volcano forever,  
but they might delay it'' for thousands of years, Glazner said. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, he said, if a volcano is near eruption ``and you  
put the weight of 300 to 400 meters (975 to 1,300 feet) of ice on 
it, it might be enough confining stress to keep it from erupting 
another 10,000 years or so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also, he noted that glacial times had a lot more rainfall and  
snowfall so ``there might be a cooling of the crust by water flux 
through it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In at least one area studied, there are many stone deposits that  
indicate early hot springs, he said, showing that water seeping 
through the earth was heated and rose to the surface, which could 
have provided an efficient heat transfer to cool volcanic magma. 
</P>
<P>
	The team of researchers -- who studied California's Long Valley,  
Big Pine and Coso volcanic fields -- found peaks of volcanic 
activity 10 million, 100 million, 185 million, 320 million and 690 
million years ago, alternating with periods of glacial climate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although the short-term effect of volcanism on climate is  
clear, it is unlikely that the correlation ... is a result of 
volcanically induced climate change,'' the researchers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The climate impact of volcanoes has long been a topic of  
speculation, going back at least to Benjamin Franklin. The eruption 
of the Indonesian volcano Tambora was blamed for a worldwide 
cooling in 1816 -- the ``year without a summer'' when snow fell in 
New England in June. 
</P>
<P>
	The effect was also observed recently. The year after the 1991  
eruption of Mount Pinatubo in the Philippines, the average global 
climate cooled a degree or two because dust in the atmosphere 
blocked the sunlight. 
</P>
<P>
	But such effects tend to last only briefly, and researchers say  
they are unlikely to lead to anything as severe as a major glacial 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the paper concludes, ``It appears that climate has  
affected the timing of volcanism in eastern California.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the coldest periods, glaciers averaged more than 300  
yards thick over the Sierra Nevada, increasing to 1,500 yards in 
some deep canyons. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
