<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Plans To Sell Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Ten months ago, Hong Kong propped up the stock  
market with a controversial $15.1 billion share purchase. Now that 
the market seems to be okay, the government wants to sell off its 
stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	After the government announced its sell-off plan today,  
investors showed no immediate fears that the market would be 
flooded with stock. The Hang Seng Index closed up 585.96 points at 
13,994.23 -- a 20-month high. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has long hinted that it would eventually sell its  
shares, and investors have feared that too hasty a sell-off would 
depress demand for stock, undercut prices and disrupt the market. 
</P>
<P>
	The government bought heavily in August during the height of the  
Asian financial crisis, saying it wanted to drive speculators out 
of Hong Kong to rescue shares and the Hong Kong dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, the market has nearly doubled from the Hang Seng's  
lows below 7,000 points before government buying began. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials today sought to assure investors any negative impact  
on the market from the sell-off would be minimal. 
</P>
<P>
	Ti-liang Yang, chairman of Exchange Fund Investment Ltd., which  
was set up to manage the government's shareholdings, said the 
stocks would be sold as unit trusts, or mutual funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The mutual funds will closely track the Hang Seng, making their  
dealings ``market neutral,'' unlike massive dealings in individual 
company shares, Yang said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It offers the prospect of the least disruption to the market  
of the alternatives we have considered,'' Yang said. 
</P>
<P>
	The paperwork will take four to five months to complete, so the  
earliest possible sale could come late this year, Yang told 
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The funds will be sold in packages small enough to let  
individual investors take part but also of interest to big 
institutional investors who want to bet on Hong Kong blue chips, 
Yang said, without saying what the minimum investment would be. 
</P>
<P>
	The government stock purchase raised criticisms that markets  
would not remain free in Hong Kong if authorities were willing to 
intervene to boost prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
