<HEADLINE> Wheat Mixed; Corn, Soybeans Lower / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat futures finished mixed Monday on the  
Chicago Board of Trade, while corn and soybeans retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures were supported by rains that once again delayed  
harvesting of the winter wheat crop. Agronomist say the longer 
harvesting is delay, the greater the chance of crop loss to pests 
and weather problems. Prices were pressured in some months by 
weakness in the corn and soybean markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans gave up some of their gains from late last  
week amid moderating forecasts for Midwest growing regions. 
Meteorologists said a high pressure ridge moving into parts of Iowa 
and other growing states would not be as severe as originally 
thought. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures were expected to remain moderate in the Midwest  
over the next few days, with plenty of relieving rains that should 
prove beneficial to crop development. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery was unchanged at $2.54 3/4 a bushel; July  
corn fell 1 1/2 cents to $2.19 1/4 a bushel; July oats fell 2 1/4 cents to 
$1.15 1/4 a bushel; July soybeans fell 3 1/4 cents to $4.71 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while  
pork futures finished mostly lower. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle fell .35 cent to 63.52 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .22 cent to 76.90 cents a pound; July lean hogs 
rose .23 cent to 51 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose .60 cent 
to 43.80 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
