<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Gives Special School Reprieve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today temporarily blocked  
the dismantling of a special public school district for disabled 
children in a New York community of ultra-Orthodox Jews. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices, granting an emergency request by state officials,  
postponed the effect of a ruling in which New York's highest court 
said creation of the school district violated the constitutionally 
required separation of government and religion. 
</P>
<P>
	The court had been told its help was ``the only apparent means  
of preventing nearly 220 handicapped students served by the Kiryas 
Joel Union Free School District from being locked out of their 
school.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The school district will be allowed to continue operations until  
the justices say whether they will grant full review to the state's 
still-pending appeal of the New York court's ruling. That word may 
not come for months. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiryas Joel, about 45 miles northwest of New York City in Orange  
County, has about 12,000 residents -- virtually all of them members 
of the Satmar Hasidic sect, which maintains an insular community 
where people wear special clothing, follow a strict schedule of 
prayer and religious study and usually speak Yiddish. 
</P>
<P>
	Children who are not disabled attend private religious schools  
in the village, where girls and boys are educated separately. At 
the public school, fulltime and part-time students are educated in 
mixed classes of boys and girls. 
</P>
<P>
	In the late 1980s, the community's leaders first asked the state  
Legislature to create a special school district so the village's 
disabled children could be educated at their own schools rather 
than in the local school district. It was said they could fare 
better in a Hasidic setting. 
</P>
<P>
	Two previous attempts to create the special school district were  
struck down by the New York Court of Appeals. One of those rulings 
was upheld by a 6-3 vote in 1994 by the nation's highest court. 
</P>
<P>
	In that ruling, the Supreme Court said creation of the special  
school district was unlawful because it ``singles out a particular 
religious sect for special treatment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case acted on today was sparked by the Legislature's third  
attempt to fashion a constitutionally acceptable special district. 
The state Court of Appeals ruled, 4-3, last May that the 
Legislature had failed. 
</P>
<P>
	Louis Grumet, executive director of the New York School Boards  
Association had challenged the third attempt, just as his group had 
challenged its two predecessors. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the state earlier this month asked Justice Ruth  
Bader Ginsburg, who hears emergency cases from New York for the 
Supreme Court, to save the school district by temporarily blocking 
the effect of the Court of Appeals ruling. She referred the request 
to the full court. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Pataki vs. Grumet, A-1023.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
