<HEADLINE> Marlins' Floyd Out 1 Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Florida Marlins outfielder Cliff Floyd will miss at  
least four weeks after being diagnosed Monday with a small tear in 
his right Achilles' tendon. 
</P>
<P>
	The Marlins placed Floyd on the 15-day disabled list and planned  
to activate reliever Archie Corbin from the DL in time for 
Tuesday's start of a three-game series at the New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd flew back to South Florida on Sunday from Denver, where  
the Marlins were in the midst of a two-week road trip. An 
examination Monday revealed a small tear in the bottom part of the 
Achilles' tendon. 
</P>
<P>
	The 26-year-old outfielder will wear an immobilizing boot for  
about two weeks before beginning rehabilitation, Marlins general 
manager Dave Dombrowski said. He is expected to miss 4-8 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	It is Floyd's second trip to the disabled list this season. He  
missed the first three weeks after undergoing arthroscopic surgery 
on his right knee. He is batting .275 this year with seven home 
runs and 33 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	Corbin, 31, is 0-1 with an 8.49 ERA in 10 appearances this  
season. He went on the disabled list June 2 with a pulled rib 
muscle. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
