<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> P. Bowes Denies Cornering Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Pitney Bowes denied Monday that it is  
trying to corner the Internet postage market, but confirmed that 
antitrust regulators are reviewing recent patent infringement 
lawsuits it filed against competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Wednesday, the U.S. Justice Department's antitrust division  
asked the company for various documents. 
</P>
<P>
	Pitney Bowes is clearly the dominant player in the postage-meter  
business -- holding about 85 percent of the market -- but is 
scrambling to match smaller competitors in delivering postage over 
the Internet that can be printed out on regular computer printers. 
</P>
<P>
	Company spokesman Sheryl Battles said the investigation appears  
to focus on its attempts to protect its patents for Internet 
postage technology. 
</P>
<P>
	On June 9, Pitney Bowes filed a lawsuit against E-Stamp Corp. of  
San Mateo, Calif. The lawsuit claims E-Stamp used patented Pitney 
Bowes technology to develop its online postage product. 
</P>
<P>
	A week later, Pitney Bowes filed a similar lawsuit against  
Stamps.com Inc. of Santa Monica, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	That same day, the Justice Department served Pitney Bowes with  
its demand for documents. Both E-Stamp and Stamps.com have been 
served with similar demands. 
</P>
<P>
	Stamps.com officials said Monday that the Justice Department  
said it was investigating possible conduct ``aimed at interfering 
with the entry of potential competitors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Battles said Pitney Bowes has been the subject of similar  
investigations over the past 20 years, but each concluded without 
further action by the Justice Department. 
</P>
<P>
	``We very strongly believe we've complied with all of the  
antitrust laws and are confident that this inquiry is going to be 
resolved successfully,'' Battles said. 
</P>
<P>
	E-Stamp officials denied the patent infringement claims. They  
said Pitney Bowes was trying to quash competition in a market where 
E-Stamp holds 20 patents of its own. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think (Pitney Bowes) may see the writing on the wall and is  
competing in the only manner it knows how -- to sue its 
competitors,'' said Ed Malysz, E-Stamp's general counsel. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement released Monday, Stamps.com also denied Pitney  
Bowes' claims of patent infringement and said it would cooperate 
with the demand for documents. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, E-Stamp became the first company to get approval from  
the U.S. Postal Service to test its online postage product. The 
company said it plans to roll out its full service sometime this 
summer, once it completes testing in California and Washington, 
D.C. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
