<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 15:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buffalo Still Steaming Over Goal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- The Buffalo Sabres are still steaming and  
insist the NHL botched its review of the final goal of the Stanley 
Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, I just want to crawl in a cave,'' Sabres coach  
Lindy Ruff said Monday. ``Every time somebody mentions the goal I 
get too wound up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brett Hull scored in the third overtime of Game 6 early Sunday,  
giving the Dallas Stars a 2-1 victory and the title. The Sabres 
contend the goal violated the man-in-the-crease rule. 
</P>
<P>
	Immediately after the 5 1/2-hour game, Ruff demanded to know why  
the league hadn't made an exhaustive review of the play, as had 
been the case with similar goals during the regular season and 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The league said it indeed reviewed the goal. It insisted that  
even though Hull was in the crease, he maintained possession of the 
puck. 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL did not follow the same procedure in reviewing the goal  
as with other similarly questionable scores. 
</P>
<P>
	``All the team wanted to see was the same procedure we had gone  
through in the regular year,'' Ruff said. ``They wanted to hear the 
horn sound. They wanted to hear the announcer say `This goal is 
under review.' They wanted somebody to say, two or three minutes 
later, after reviewing it that the goal stands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo players simmered as they cleaned out their lockers  
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just thinking about how they wouldn't review it,''  
defenseman Jay McKee said. ``Usually when a goal like that is 
scored it takes a couple of minutes for the ref to be on the phone 
with the review judge and there was none of that. They didn't even 
speak.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres ended their season much like the 1998 Buffalo Bills,  
who were burned by questionable calls in a regular-season loss in 
New England and a playoff loss in Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	The dubious calls against the Bills influenced the NFL owners'  
decision in March to bring back instant replay. 
</P>
<P>
	It was no consolation to the Sabres that their plight might  
affect future games. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can debate about the rule forever, and I'm sure it will be  
debated forever,'' Buffalo center Brian Holzinger said. ``There's a 
lot of instances that I've seen that are very similar to this 
situation that were called back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most Sabres agree that the rule is bad and that Hull's goal was  
good. They just wish the league had been more consistent. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hate to say it, but his foot being in the crease was a  
nonfactor,'' Sabres defenseman James Patrick said. ``My feeling was 
they scored on us. But even if it was good, there was no review 
process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ruff contends the league lost its nerve once the goal was scored  
and the Dallas Stars starting pouring onto the ice along with 
sticks, gloves and debris. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stop the chaos that happened within 15 seconds there,'' Ruff  
said. ``Have one referee keep the doors closed, another one keep 
the players on the bench and say `We're going to review this 
thing.' If we win the game in that fashion, or we score that goal, 
it would be reviewed because there's no celebration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rule was intended to reduce career-threatening injuries near  
the goal. One Sabres player would like to see the rule remain 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rule is pretty clear and safe,'' goaltender Dominik Hasek  
said. ``In the second half of the season, the players knew they 
could not go to the crease, and they were very careful. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were not too many goals disallowed because of somebody  
standing in the crease. I don't want to change anything. The rule 
is right.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
