<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aetna-Prudential Merger Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Treating a Justice Department plan as a  
promising first step, the American Medical Association is gearing 
up for an offensive against an insurance merger that is about to 
produce the largest HMO in the country and reduce competition. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision Monday by the Justice Department to make some  
modifications but otherwise give the go-ahead for Aetna's $1 
billion acquisition of Prudential Insurance's health care ``leaves 
an awful lot of markets badly out of whack,'' said AMA President 
Dr. Nancy Dickey. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department and the Texas attorney general's office  
filed a civil antitrust lawsuit to block the merger. At the same 
time, they filed a proposed consent decree allowing the purchase to 
go forward as long as Aetna sells its NYLCare health maintenance 
organization business in Houston and Dallas-Fort Worth. 
</P>
<P>
	But David Vanderpool, a Dallas surgeon who hasn't read the  
decree himself, said, ``I don't think that's enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``A massive conglomerate of insurance companies like that can  
roll over patients, doctors and just about anyone else,'' 
Vanderpool said from the AMA's convention in Chicago. He added that 
with control over an estimated 40 percent of the market in the 
Dallas-Fort Worth area, the combined company would wield ``too much 
control over people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The AMA asked the Justice Department last year to block the  
acquisition, arguing that it would harm patient care. Aetna 
provides health care benefits to more than 15 million plan members 
nationwide, while Prudential provides care to 5 million plan 
members. 
</P>
<P>
	Joel Klein, the assistant attorney general in charge of the  
Justice Department's antitrust division, said Aetna's divestiture 
of the Texas operations will halt the company's ability to ``unduly 
depress physician reimbursement rates and thereby impair the 
quantity and quality of physician services.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Dickey said New Jersey has a ``potentially worse''  
anti-competitive situation than Texas. She identified New York and 
Georgia as other states that would be adversely affected by the 
merger, as well as Florida, despite the fact that its large 
population of Medicare patients protects it to some extent. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas is ``a big win, but it's a first step,'' Dickey said. ``We  
clearly will have to work with other states.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The merger is ``a harbinger of bad things to come for New Jersey  
with regard to our patients,'' said Dr. Irving P. Ratner, president 
of the Medical Society of New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	``Together they will have a monopolistic organization which will  
control upwards of 35 or 36 percent of all of the patient care in 
the state of New Jersey if the merger goes through,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ratner said physicians want to manage the care for patients.  
</P>
<P>
	``This merger will diminish our ability to do that,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Mathis Becker, president-elect of the Florida Medical  
Association, said the organization would review the merger between 
Aetna and Prudential, which has a large market penetration in his 
state. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our first reaction would be that we were pleased to see that  
the attorney general has recognized a potential problem for 
patients in Texas, but we'll be taking a closer look and pursue 
appropriate remedies if necessary,'' said Becker. ``We have been 
part of objecting to these mega-mergers. It disenfranchises more 
and more patients from choices.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Critics of the merger have 60 days to file objections. A federal  
judge in Dallas could then approve or disapprove the decree. 
</P>
<P>
	Klein said the proposed settlement underscores the department's  
efforts to preserve competition. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a statement, Aetna U.S. Healthcare said it did not share  
the Justice Department's ``view regarding the potential effect of 
the acquisition on competition and physician reimbursements in 
Texas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Health care consumers are demanding more choice -- in products  
and in physicians. It simply wouldn't make good business sense for 
us to take actions that would be contrary to this, including 
economic actions that could significantly reduce the number of 
physicians in our networks,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard L. Huber, Aetna's chairman and chief executive officer,  
said the divestiture in Texas ``was the most expeditious way'' to 
close out the Justice Department review process. Aetna expects to 
complete its divestiture by the end of the year and close its deal 
with Prudential in July. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 08:40:27 </DATE_TIME>
