<HEADLINE> Boston Chicken, Heinz Accord OK'd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- A licensing agreement that will allow H.J.  
Heinz Co. to sell packaged food products under the Boston Market 
name has been approved by the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston Chicken officials said today it would license its Boston  
Market trademarks to Heinz for the worldwide manufacture and sale 
of packaged food products to retailers. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement is separate and independent of Boston Chicken's  
restaurant business. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies announced the licensing agreement April 23,  
pending approval by the bankruptcy court. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston Chicken, which operates and franchises restaurants under  
the Boston Market brand name, filed a voluntary petition for 
Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection Oct. 5, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement Heinz will pay Boston Chicken an undisclosed  
royalty fee based on sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston Chicken said it anticipates the national exposure  
provided by Heinz' placement of Boston Market-branded food products 
in grocery stores would have a positive impact on Boston Chicken's 
business operations. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
