<HEADLINE> Dollar Rises in European Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The dollar rose against most major currencies in  
European trading today. Gold prices were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose to 122.14 Japanese yen from 120.71 yen late  
Friday, and was higher against the euro and the British pound. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0316, down from $1.0411 Friday, while  
the British pound fell to $1.5858 from $1.5957. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates compared with late Friday included 1.5465  
Swiss francs, up from 1.5341, and 1.4685 Canadian dollars, up from 
1.4645. 
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar was worth 122.27. yen,  
1.5460 Swiss francs and 1.4725 Canadian dollars. The euro was worth 
$1.0326 and the British pound was worth $1.5901. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8959 German marks, up from 1.8786; 
6.3586 French francs, up from 6.3006; and 1,876.96 Italian lire, up 
from 1,859.83. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $259.00 bid per troy ounce, unchanged  
from Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich the bid price was $258.85, up from $258.55.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold fell 50 cents in Hong Kong to close at $259.25.  
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $4.98, unchanged.  
  	   	
</P>
