<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Kosovo Blast Kills 4  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- British peacekeepers said they are  
investigating the cause of today's blast at a Kosovo school that 
killed two Nepalese soldiers and two civilians. The soldiers from 
the 69th Gurkha Field Squadron, who were attached to the British 
peacekeeping force, were helping clear ammunition in the village of 
Negrovce, 20 miles west of Pristina, when a mine or booby trap went 
off, NATO said. The deaths were the first allied fatalities since 
the NATO-led force entered Kosovo on June 12. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Calls on Serbia for Change  
</P>
<P>
	LJUBLJANA, Slovenia (AP) -- From this pro-Western country that  
broke from Slobodan Milosevic's grip, President Clinton urged Serbs 
Monday to ``reject the murderous rule'' of the Yugoslav leader and 
follow Slovenia into democracy. ``I can't wait for the day,'' 
Clinton said, when a democratic leader replaces Milosevic, accused 
of war crimes for the killings and terror in Kosovo. The president 
pledged there would be no U.S. money -- ``not a bit, not a penny'' -- 
to help Milosevic rebuild bridges and roads destroyed in Yugoslavia 
by 78 days of NATO airstrikes. 

</P>
<P>
	Koreas Open High Level Negotiations  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- After a daylong delay over a late fertilizer  
shipment, rivals North Korea and South Korea on Tuesday opened 
their highest level government negotiations in 14 months. The talks 
at the neutral site of a Beijing hotel signaled political 
willingness by the normally antagonistic governments to improve 
ties despite a skirmish between their navies and a dispute over a 
detained South Korean. North Korea has threatened retaliation for 
last week's skirmish, during which South Korean warships sank a 
North Korean gunboat in disputed waters in the Yellow Sea. 

</P>
<P>
	Suspected Serial Killer Charged  
</P>
<P>
	MURPHYSBORO, Ill. (AP) -- The FBI put an alleged serial killer  
who hops freight trains to move around the nation's midsection on 
its 10 Most Wanted List on Monday. Fugitive Rafael 
Resendez-Ramirez, who is already wanted for questioning in five 
killings in Texas and one in Kentucky, was charged with murdering a 
father and daughter in Illinois. All eight slayings took place on 
or near railroad tracks. 

</P>
<P>
	2 Officers Indicted in Torture Case  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Two plainclothes police officers were indicted  
Monday on federal charges of lying to authorities investigating the 
torture of Haitian immigrant Abner Louima. Rolando Aleman and 
Francisco Rosario, decorated members of the Street Crime Unit, were 
booking a suspect at the precinct at the time of the 1997 assault. 
They ``repeatedly lied and misled the federal government about what 
they saw in the stationhouse that morning,'' said prosecutor Alan 
Vingrad. Patrolman Charles Schwarz already was convicted of holding 
down Louima while another officer, Justin Volpe -- who pleaded 
guilty -- sodomized him. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S.: World Better Prepared for Y2K  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The United States believes the world is better  
prepared than it was six months ago to cope with the Year 2000 
computer bug -- even though key countries like Russia and China 
still face serious problems. Six months after the first global 
conference on the millennium bug, experts from over 170 countries 
will meet tomorrow at the United Nations to assess progress in 
dealing with Y2K. The United States alone is probably spending $80 
billion to $100 billion to cope with the bug, said John Koskinen, 
head of President Clinton's Council on Year 2000 Conversion. 

</P>
<P>
	More Women Filing for Bankruptcy  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Women are resorting to personal bankruptcy  
more frequently than men and married couples, according to new data 
released by a Harvard law professor. Elizabeth Warren's data show 
that 39 percent of bankruptcy court filings in the 12 months ended 
March 31 were made by women. That compares with 28 percent for men 
and 33 percent for married couples. The new study will likely 
become fresh ammunition for opponents to legislation being debated 
in Congress that would make it harder for people to erase 
bankruptcy debts. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Fall in Midday Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks slipped Tuesday as investors took  
profits on recent gains, while the dollar fell against the yen. The 
Nikkei Stock Average lost 36.72 points, closing the morning session 
at 17,702.13. In New York on Monday, Dow Jones Industrials were 
down 39.58 at 10,815.98 

</P>
<P>
	Red Sox Defeat Rangers 5-4  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Texas catcher Ivan Rodriguez's seventh-inning  
throwing error led to tonight's winning run for the Boston Red Sox 
as Nomar Garciaparra went 4-for-4 to beat the Rangers 5-4. 
Garciaparra two doubles, two singles and a stolen base, giving his 
a .382 career average against Texas. Texas lost for the eighth time 
in its last 10 games against Boston and has just three wins in its 
last 10 games overall. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief By ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  
</P>
