<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Banks Warned About Money Laundering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Treasury Department planned to issue new  
warnings today to banks and exporters in the United States about a 
money laundering scheme involving exports to Colombia, The Wall 
Street Journal reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The so-called black market peso exchange system launders up to  
$5 billion a year in drug profits, the Journal said. 
</P>
<P>
	Colombian businesses buy narcotics dollars at a steep discount  
and use them to fund imports from the United States and elsewhere, 
the newspaper said. The kitchen appliances, cigarettes, shoes and 
other goods are smuggled into Colombia, bypassing government 
tariffs and hurting legitimate businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury plans to launch a campaign to educate exporters  
about the problem. Companies will be encouraged to watch for signs 
that a customer might be using illegal funds, such as paying for an 
order with checks or bank drafts issued by a third party unrelated 
to the transaction. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
