<DOCNO> APW19990621.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 07:54:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Va. To Hold Presidential Primary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Virginia's Republican Party leadership has  
voted to hold a presidential primary, a decision party leaders say 
will give the state more national clout. 
</P>
<P>
	On a voice vote Saturday, the Republican's Party's State Central  
Committee passed a resolution to hold a primary on Feb. 29, 2000. 
The vast majority of committee members voted in favor of the 
resolution. 
</P>
<P>
	``This opens it up to Republicans around the state and will  
expand the base of the party,'' said Chris LaCivita, executive 
director of the state GOP. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the Virginia GOP's old process, some delegates to the  
national Republican convention were chosen at congressional 
district conventions in May. The remainder were elected at-large at 
a state party convention in June, usually well after the nominee 
had been decided. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, a February primary transforms Virginia into one of  
the first five states to endorse a candidate for the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters said the primary will make Virginia far more  
influential. ``While Virginia may be the mother of all presidents 
we are the selector of none,'' said David Hummel of Virginia Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents said a primary could hurt the party because under  
Virginia's open registration system, Democrats can vote in the 
Republican primary, thus influencing the choice of the other 
party's nominee. 
</P>
<P>
	``This isn't going to be helpful to us and it might be harmful  
for us,'' said Morton Blackwell of Arlington. ``This is the system 
that is easiest for Democrats to invade.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the new primary system, registered voters will be able to  
vote for the nominee of their choice. State Republicans will 
continue to select delegates to the national convention, but 
delegates will have to vote for the candidate that wins the 
Virginia primary. 
</P>
<P>
	Virginia Democrats still nominate delegates at a convention.  
They have shown no interest in changing their system. 
</P>
<P>
	Virginia is one of several states that have established  
primaries or moved the dates of primaries in an attempt to have 
more say in national elections. 
</P>
<P>
	South Carolina Republicans recently decided move their primary  
to Feb. 19, and Louisiana's Republican leaders decided earlier this 
month to hold a 2000 presidential caucus one week ahead of Iowa's 
traditional first-in-the-nation caucus. That decision must be 
approved by the Republican National Committee. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 12:50:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Women's World Cup Soccer Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP)- The media is embracing this year's Women's World  
Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Accreditations for the tournament are up to 1,975, a number that  
far exceeds any other women's soccer event. 
</P>
<P>
	Of those accreditations, 900 went to reporters, 400 to  
photographers and 600 to representatives from radio and television 
stations. Of these journalists, 500 come from outside the United 
States, with China and Nigeria making up the largest overseas 
contingents. 
</P>
<P>
	For the opening game, the United States vs. Denmark in Giants  
Stadium on Saturday, 416 reporters, 124 photographers and 17 radio 
and television stations were accredited. 
</P>
<P>
	Interest in the U.S. team has increased dramatically since it  
won the 1991 Women's World Cup in China. On their return to the 
United States in '91, only one reporter met the players at the 
airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Another difference is the number of matches that will be  
televised. In 1995, only the six U.S. games were broadcast. This 
year, all the games will be televised. Seventy-four countries will 
broadcast the matches, with a possible television audience of 1 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SYDNEY 2000:* The Women's World Cup is not just an event in  
itself, it is also the qualifying tournament for the Sydney 
Olympics in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The tournament is especially significant to Australia, hoping to  
make a strong showing before the Olympics. As the host country, the 
Australian team automatically gets one of the eight spots, but the 
team wants to win a place on its own merits. 
</P>
<P>
	The eight quarterfinalists of the Women's World Cup will  
automatically advance to the Sidney Games if Australia is among 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	Should the Australian team fail to make the quarterfinals, the  
four winning quarterfinalists and only the best of the three losing 
quarterfinalists get a spot in Sydney. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *NICKNAMES:* The Black Queens tied the Waltzing Mathilda's, the  
Super Falcons beat North Korea and the Samba Queens waltzed over 
Mexico in ``the group of death.'' This may sound like a video game 
score, but all these titles are nicknames in the World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nigerian team is called the Super Falcons, while its men's  
team is known as the Super Eagles. The Black Queens are from Ghana 
and the Waltzing Mathilda's were named after the Australian song. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil has no official nickname, but the media calls the  
Brazilians the Samba Queens, because they play the ``samba soccer'' 
that Brazil is famous for. 
</P>
<P>
	Group B, featuring Germany, Brazil, Italy and Mexico, was  
nicknamed ``the group of death'' because of the high quality teams 
in the draw. It would have been even more impressive had those four 
nations been together in the men's event. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SWEET SIXTEEN:* Nigerian midfielder Ifeanyichukwu Chiejene, who  
played in Sunday's win over North Korea, is the youngest player in 
the Women's World Cup. Chiejene turned 16 a little over a month 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The Super Falcons have another 16-year-old in the ranks,  
Florence Iweta, who turned 16 in March. Mexico also sports a sweet 
16, Moni Vergara, who celebrated her birthday in May. 
</P>
<P>
	The tournament's oldest player is Norway's team captain Linda  
Medalen. The veteran of the 1991 and 1995 Women's World Cup turned 
34 last Thursday, June 
</P>
<P>
	17.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
