<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kings Land Proven Scorer in Palffy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Ziggy Palffy knew the New York Islanders were  
slashing their budget, so it was only a matter of where, not when, 
the right wing would go. 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles Kings were only too happy to acquire Palffy, a  
proven scorer and star player they hope will attract fans next 
season when the team moves into the new downtown Staples Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really happy now and I can't wait to go play hockey  
again,'' Palffy said Monday in a conference call from New York. 
``They try to build a good team and I want to be part of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The six-player deal completed Sunday sends Palffy, center Bryan  
Smolinski, goaltender Marcel Cousineau and a 1999 fourth-round 
draft choice from the Islanders to Los Angeles in exchange for 
forwards Olli Jokinen and Josh Green, defenseman Mathieu Biron and 
the Kings' first round choice in this month's entry draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ziggy's a marquee player who generates excitement each time he  
touches the puck,'' Kings general manager Dave Taylor said. ``Ziggy 
Palffy is a proven NHL scorer and a true gamebreaker.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Kings increased their payroll by $6 million to sign Palffy,  
and Taylor said it was no problem convincing the owners to approve 
the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	That wasn't the case in New York.  
</P>
<P>
	Palffy, the Islanders' leading scorer last season with 22 goals  
and 28 assists in 50 games, has four more years and $24 million to 
be paid on a contract he signed last December. He missed 32 games 
because of a contract dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard because everything is about money,'' he said.  
``Owners don't want to spend any money on the hockey, so they're 
going to trade players who make $1 million. I was ready for 
anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palffy, 27, was a two-time All Star and had three 40-goal  
seasons, but never made the playoffs in five seasons with the 
Islanders. 
</P>
<P>
	The trade reunites Palffy with Kings center Jozef Stumpel, a  
fellow Slovak who played youth hockey with Palffy and remains his 
close friend. The duo could end up on the same line, along with Luc 
Robitaille, under new coach Andy Murray. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like to play offense and score goals and make a play for  
other guys,'' Palffy said. ``Hockey is two ways, so I'm playing 
anything what the coach wants to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now that his future is secure, Palffy's biggest dilemma is  
selling the New York house he moved into three months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you can find somebody who can buy it from me, I'd  
appreciate it,'' he joked. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
