<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Upholds Texas Death Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Jurors choosing between life and death for  
convicted murderers do not have to be told what happens if they 
cannot agree, the Supreme Court ruled Monday as it upheld a Texas 
killer's federal death sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	By a 5-4 vote, the justices ruled that Louis Jones' death  
sentence for a 1995 murder at an Air Force base is valid. Jones 
became the first person in the nation condemned under a 1994 
federal death penalty law, and Monday's ruling marked the first 
time the Supreme Court studied that law. 
</P>
<P>
	Only the federal death penalty law was at issue, but the  
decision means the 38 states with capital punishment laws also have 
no constitutional duty to tell jurors the consequences of their 
failure to reach a unanimous decision on punishment. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a capital sentencing proceeding, the government has a  
strong interest in having the jury express the conscience of the 
community on the ultimate question of life or death,'' Justice 
Clarence Thomas wrote for the court. ``A charge to the jury of the 
sort proposed by (Jones) might well have the effect of undermining 
this strong governmental interest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones had argued that jurors should have been told he would be  
sentenced to life in prison without chance of parole, as provided 
for in the 1994 law, if they could not reach unanimous agreement on 
his punishment. 
</P>
<P>
	The court also rejected Jones' arguments that the trial judge's  
sentencing instructions to the jury were so confusing they violated 
his 8th Amendment protection against cruel and unusual punishment 
and his due-process rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones failed as well in his attempt to convince the court that  
some of the aggravating factors the sentencing jury considered were 
too broad and too vague to be valid. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if they were, Thomas said, ``the error was harmless.''  
</P>
<P>
	He was joined by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices  
Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	Justices Ruth Bader Ginsburg, John Paul Stevens, David H. Souter  
and Stephen G. Breyer dissented. ``The misinformation rendered the 
jury's death verdict unreliable,'' Ginsburg wrote for the four. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones killed Tracie Joy McBride, a 19-year-old Army private at  
Goodfellow Air Force Base in San Angelo, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, who had retired from the Army in 1993 after a 22-year  
career, confessed to abducting McBride from an on-base laundry room 
and taking her to his home. He said he later took her to an 
isolated area about 20 miles from the city and beat her to death 
with a tire iron. 
</P>
<P>
	He led police to McBride's body.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 15:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
