<HEADLINE> Galarraga Says Cancer Almost Beaten </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Atlanta Braves first baseman Andres  
Galarraga said Monday he's almost won his battle with cancer and he 
expects to start working out by September. 
</P>
<P>
	Galarraga, 38, said radiation treatments have destroyed 98  
percent of the tumor, which had been pressing against his spine's 
third vertebra. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel very good,'' Galarraga said during a news conference.  
``It was very difficult, but thank God I am here in Venezuela.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said his radiation treatments will be over in July and he  
should be training with the Braves as early as late August. He 
probably won't play in games until next season 
</P>
<P>
	Galarraga's face was puffy and his hair was short and thin. He  
said his bones, weakened by radiation, will not be ready for 
intense weight training for several months. 
</P>
<P>
	``The doctors have recommended that I don't take any batting  
practice so that I can avoid breaking a bone,'' Galarraga said. 
</P>
<P>
	Galarraga had back pain throughout last season, which caused him  
to miss several games, including the All-Star game. He was the 
Braves' top hitter last season with a .305 average, 44 homers and 
121 RBIs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
