<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jeter Leads in All-Star Voting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Derek Jeter's lead over Nomar Garciaparra in  
balloting to start at shortstop for the American League in next 
month's All-Star game was cut to less than 8,000 votes. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeter, the leading hitter on the World Series champion New York  
Yankees with a .377 average, had 378,587 votes in totals released 
Monday by the commissioner's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra, hitting .339 for the Boston Red Sox, had 370,656  
votes and trailed by 7,931. Last week, Jeter led by 14,964. 
</P>
<P>
	Voting continues through Sunday, with AL starters to be  
announced July 5. The All-Star game is scheduled for Fenway Park on 
July 13. 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore's Cal Ripken still leads at third base (486,344) and  
is on track for his 17th consecutive All-Star appearance and 16th 
straight start. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, who led balloting in 1992 and '95, would tie Rod Carew  
as the only players elected to start 15 times -- in 1988 Alan 
Trammell was elected but got hurt and Ripken started in his place. 
</P>
<P>
	Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr. remained the overall leader in voting,  
topping outfielders at 1,224,553. He was followed by three 
Cleveland Indians: Manny Ramirez (707,330), Kenny Lofton (623,540) 
and David Justice (480,696). 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey was the AL's leading vote-getter in 1991 and 1993 and  
led all players in 1994, 1996, 1997 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other Indians maintained leads at their positions: first  
baseman Jim Thome (442,083) and second baseman Roberto Alomar 
(1,082,221). 
</P>
<P>
	Ivan Rodriguez of Texas (785,979) leads at catcher, and Jose  
Canseco of Tampa Bay (648,741), who began the day leading the major 
leagues with 27 home runs, topped designated hitters. 
</P>
<P>
	An update on NL voting will be released Tuesday, and NL starters  
will be announced July 6. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
