<DOCNO> APW19990621.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 09:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Stephen King Alert After Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEWISTON, Maine (AP) -- Stephen King was conscious, alert and  
even cracking jokes following an operation to treat a shattered leg 
other injuries he suffered when he was struck by a van. But he will 
probably be in rehabilitation for months, his office said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The prolific, best-selling horror author remained in serious but  
stable condition today at Central Maine Medical Center, hospital 
officials said. King, 51, faced additional surgery this afternoon 
on his leg and hip, with more surgery tentatively scheduled for 
later in the week. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been alert and he's in pretty good spirits,'' Chuck Gill,  
the hospital's vice president, said earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Hospital spokesman Laird Covey said King had been talking with  
his wife, Tabitha, adding, ``I know that he has been cracking some 
jokes to the staff about his condition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A statement released by King's office in Bangor said he will  
remain at the Lewiston hospital for two or three weeks and require 
``major rehabilitation'' over the next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. King's mental state is great -- the accident has not  
affected him mentally,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said King was thrown 14 feet when he was hit Saturday  
by a Dodge Caravan in rural Lovell, where he owns a summer home. 
Lovell is about 115 miles southwest of Bangor. 
</P>
<P>
	King was walking south on the shoulder of the road at about 4:30  
p.m. when a motorist approaching from behind lost control of his 
vehicle after his dog got loose inside the van, Oxford County 
Sheriff's deputy Matt Baker said. 
</P>
<P>
	The driver stopped immediately after striking King, according to  
witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was hurting, but he was able to communicate,'' said Baker,  
who responded to the accident. ``He was talking to me. He gave me 
phone numbers of where to call his family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He was in a lot of pain,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Gill said King suffered a collapsed lung and multiple fractures  
of the right leg and hip. He was also treated during surgery for a 
scalp laceration. 
</P>
<P>
	According to witnesses, the driver, Bryan Smith, 41, did not  
appear to be speeding, Matt Baker said. He said no charges will be 
filed against Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	King, who lives in Bangor, may have been on one of his daily  
long walks at his summer home when he was struck, Covey said. 
</P>
<P>
	King has written more than two dozen novels, including ``The  
Shining,'' ``Carrie,'' and ``Pet Sematary.'' His story ``Misery'' 
is about a writer laid up in a car accident. His ``The Girl Who 
Loved Tom Gordon'' was on several best seller lists this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The hospital has been deluged with calls wishing King well.  
</P>
<P>
	``We heard from the Times of London,'' Gill said. ``We've had  
people wanting to know where to send flowers and cards. We've had 
calls from all over the world from both his fans and the media.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
