<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Asian Stock Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed higher Monday,  
with the key index in Hong Kong surging more than 4 percent after 
the government announced that it will sell stocks it bought 10 
months ago to prop up the market. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hong Kong market's Hang Seng Index rose 585.96 points, or  
4.4 percent, closing at 13,994.23, its highest level since Oct. 13, 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hong Kong government said it plans to put the U.S. $15.1  
billion blue-chip stocks it bought in August into mutual funds and 
sell them. 
</P>
<P>
	Ti-liang Yang, chairman of Exchange Fund Investment Ltd., which  
was set up to manage the government's shareholdings, said the sale 
of the mutual funds, called unit trusts, would be carried out ``in 
an orderly manner without disrupting the market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The news eased fears that those shares, now valued at more than  
U.S. $26 billion, will be dumped onto the market directly. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices in Tokyo soared to their highest level since  
October 1997 amid strong buying from overseas financial 
institutions, on hopes that the Japanese economy is finally picking 
up steam. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 307.59 points,  
or 1.76 percent, ending the day at 17,738.85. On Friday, the 
average fell 39.19 points, or 0.22 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	During a three-day meeting of the Group of Seven major  
industrialized nations, which ended Sunday in Cologne, Germany, 
other leaders urged Japan to do more to ensure it is on a 
domestic-led growth path. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said that the Japanese government  
will take every measure available to ensure stable growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar rose sharply against the yen  
following what traders believed was dollar-buying intervention by 
the Bank of Japan to push down the Japanese currency. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 122.34 yen in the late afternoon, up  
3.02 yen from late Friday in Tokyo and also above its late Friday 
level in New York of 120.44 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In Seoul, the key index rose 3.7 percent as concerns eased over  
a possible increase in U.S. interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 31.27 points to close  
at 869.00, its highest level since June 19, 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Thai shares also soared on buying from local speculative  
investors, who were in a buoyant mood given the strong performance 
across the region's bourses and declining interest rates at home. 
The SET index rose 19.55 points, or 3.8 percent, to 538.36. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares closed sharply higher, boosted by  
better-than-expected May trade data. The benchmark Straits Times 
Index rose 2.4 percent, or 49.75 points, to close at 2,120.38. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed higher on heavy buying of select  
electronics issues. The market's key Weighted Stock Price Index 
rose 139.12 points, or 1.7 percent, to 8,413.48. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed slightly lower. The  
benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index slipped 1.91 points, or 0.09 
percent, to 2,089.90. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed higher, boosted by the latest  
rate cuts by the central bank. The Philippine Stock Exchange index 
of 30 selected companies rose 18.98 points, or 0.7 percent, to 
2,448.62. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: The Australian stock market closed slightly lower  
following a late bout of profit-taking. The All Ordinaries Index 
fell 3.3 points, or 0.1 percent, to 2,981.7. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares closed higher on continued blue-chip  
buying. The Composite Index rose 1.2 percent, or 8.576 points, to 
716.460 points. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian share prices closed slightly lower. The  
Composite Index slipped 0.6 points to 786.02. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
