<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cisneros Seeks To Quash Tapes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorneys for former Housing Secretary Henry  
Cisneros pressed their case in court today to thwart prosecutors' 
use of 88 tapes of telephone conversations secretly recorded by his 
ex-mistress. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros lawyer Barry Simon, at a pretrial hearing today, said  
the government's special prosecutors are ``not entitled to put on 
tampered, inauthentic evidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The tapes shouldn't come in,'' Simon said.  
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Mark Jackowski acknowledged that Linda Jones had  
deleted portions of some taped conversations that included threats 
to Cisneros, mentioned other people or discussed aspects of their 
sex life. 
</P>
<P>
	``She just edited out these offensive passages or what she  
believed to be offensive passages,'' Jackowski said, adding that 
she destroyed the originals after copies were made. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said only five of the 33 tapes the government intends to  
use at Cisneros' September trial were altered. The government wants 
to use the tapes to corroborate witness testimony that the former 
Cabinet officer conspired with his one-time lover to conceal his 
``hush money'' payments to her, which exceeded $264,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors summoned Ms. Jones to the stand today to explain her  
relationship with Cisneros, how the payments began and when she 
initiated the taping. 
</P>
<P>
	Saying she was ``devastated'' when word of their extramarital  
affair appeared in the media, Ms. Jones said Cisneros agreed to pay 
her $3,000 monthly, later raised to $4,000, after her marriage and 
career foundered amid the controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	``He knew all of the press stories were his fault,'' said a  
poised Ms. Jones, who was transferred from the prison facility 
where she is incarcerated to testify. Her appearance came on her 
50th birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros was not in court.  
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros' lawyers also are pressing for a defense psychiatric  
examination of Ms. Jones. She has acknowledged a years-long bout 
with depression, addiction to antidepressant medication and a 
suicide attempt. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jones is serving a 3 1/2-year prison sentence at a federal  
medical facility in Fort Worth, Texas. She pleaded guilty last year 
to 28 counts involving fraud, conspiracy, money laundering and 
obstruction after becoming a target herself of Independent Counsel 
David Barrett. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros, a former San Antonio mayor who served as housing and  
urban development secretary from 1993 to 1996, was indicted in 
December 1997 on 18 felony counts of conspiracy, obstructing 
justice and making false statements to the FBI about the payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he acknowledged providing financial support for Ms.  
Jones, prosecutors have said Cisneros falsely told the FBI during 
his Cabinet background check that he never paid her more than 
$2,500 at one time or more than $10,000 annually. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment alleges that he paid her more than $264,000  
between 1990 and 1993, in installments as high as $15,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros has pleaded innocent, as have his co-defendants, former  
aides Sylvia Arce-Garcia and John Rosales. The two, who accompanied 
Cisneros from San Antonio to Washington, are charged with 
conspiring with their boss to conceal the payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros is the second former Clinton administration Cabinet  
member to be indicted on criminal charges. Former Agriculture 
Secretary Mike Espy was acquitted in December of all 30 counts 
involving gifts he accepted from a California agricultural 
cooperative and others. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
