<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McKesson Fires Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- McKesson HBOC fired its chairman today and  
accepted the resignations of its chief executive and chief 
financial officer less than two months after accounting problems 
forced it to restate earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Its share price skidded 4.3 percent by midday, dropping $1.56 1/4  
to $34.50 in trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	McKesson HBOC is the largest pharmaceutical supply management  
and health care information technology company in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	McKesson acquired software maker HBOC in January in a deal  
widely criticized by analysts who follow the drug distributor. HBO 
sells computer software to help health care providers manage their 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The earnings restatements reflected improperly recorded software  
sales. 
</P>
<P>
	McKesson's board said it fired chairman Charles W. McCall and  
said Mark A. Pulido, president and chief executive, and Richard H. 
Hawkins, its chief financial officer, have resigned effective July 
15. 
</P>
<P>
	John H. Hammergren, president of the company's supply management  
unit, and David L. Mahoney, president of pharmaceutical services, 
were appointed co-chief executive officers and named to the board. 
Controller Heidi E. Yodowitz was named acting chief financial 
officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``These changes reflect our need to move the company forward as  
quickly as possible,'' board member Alan Seelenfreund said in a 
statement. ``Under the circumstances, strong leadership is 
essential to this effort.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On April 28, the health care company said it would be forced to  
revise its fourth-quarter and 1998 earnings reports because it had 
improperly recorded software sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said transactions of $26.2 million in the company's  
fourth quarter ended March 31, and $16 million in prior quarters, 
were improperly counted because they were subject to contingencies. 
</P>
<P>
	A week earlier, McKesson HBOC had reported a net loss of $60.4  
million, or 22 cents per share, for the quarter ended March 31, and 
had net income of $237.1 million, or 84 cents per share, for the 
full year. 
</P>
<P>
	But after the April 28 restatement, the company said it lost 27  
per cents for the quarter and reduced full-year earnings to 75 
cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	McKesson's shares plummeted nearly 50 percent to $34.50 after  
the restatement. The stock's 52-week high had been $89.75. 
</P>
<P>
	In late May, McKesson HBOC said it would revise its fiscal 1999  
earnings downward after discovering more accounting problems at 
HBO. 
</P>
<P>
	McKesson did not offer specific revisions, other than to say the  
restatement may also affect previous years' earnings reports. 
</P>
<P>
	At least four law firms have been retained by investors to  
consider a class-action suit alleging that false statements 
artificially inflated the profits of McKesson HBOC. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 16:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McKesson Ousts Top Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- McKesson HBOC Inc. ousted its top  
management on Monday, trying to contain damage from accounting 
problems that have eroded the value of its stock by nearly 50 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The board fired chairman Charles W. McCall, who was chairman of  
HBO &AMP; Co. before McKesson, a major wholesaler of drugs and medical 
supplies, bought the medical software company in January. His 
ouster removes the person seen as most responsible for earnings 
reports that had improperly recorded software sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The top executives from McKesson got slightly gentler treatment:  
Mark A. Pulido, president and chief executive of the merged 
company, and chief financial officer Richard H. Hawkins were 
allowed to resign, effective July 15. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a positive step because they really needed to clean  
house. Somebody needed to take the blame,'' said Mike Krensavage, a 
Brown Brothers Harriman &AMP; Co. analyst. ``It's a step in the 
direction the company needs to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of McKesson HBOC fell nearly 50 percent when it announced  
on April 28 it would have to restate some of its earnings reports. 
</P>
<P>
	McKesson has been unable to recover from that blow. On Monday,  
shares of the San Francisco-based company fell $2.31 1/4 to $33.75 in 
trading on the New York Stock Exchange, well off their 52-week high 
of $89.75. 
</P>
<P>
	The company still can't report bona fide numbers, despite an  
exhaustive audit. McKesson said Monday it will miss a June 30 
deadline for submitting its annual report. Previously, it said it 
will have to revise earnings reports for 1999, 1998 and possibly 
previous years as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``Under the circumstances, strong leadership is essential,''  
said board member Alan Seelenfreund, who was named non-executive 
chairman. ``These changes reflect our need to move the company 
forward as quickly as possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several of Pulido's lieutenants were promoted to top jobs. John  
H. Hammergren, president of the company's supply management unit, 
and David L. Mahoney, president of pharmaceutical services, were 
appointed co-chief executive officers and named to the board. 
Controller Heidi E. Yodowitz was named acting chief financial 
officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors are still considering class-action lawsuits alleging  
that HBOC, now McKesson's Information Technology Business unit, 
artificially inflated its profits. 
</P>
<P>
	The problems stem from side letters that told customers not to  
pay the total purchase price for business-management software 
unless HBO met a series of contingencies. Despite these letters, 
HBO apparently claimed the total price had been paid, thereby 
inflating its earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Seelenfreund said Monday that the existence of the contingencies  
and side letters had been improperly concealed from McKesson's due 
diligence teams before the $12 billion merger was consummated. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would even term that fraudulent,'' said Joseph Chiarelli, an  
analyst with J.P. Morgan. He said the side deals ``would not be the 
easiest thing in the world to find.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chiarelli said J.P. Morgan's own questioning of HBO's customers  
did determine the sales had taken place, although the purchase 
prices may have been claimed prematurely. 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur Andersen was HBOC's accountant before the merger, though  
the merged company now uses Deloitte &AMP; Touche. Andersen, which last 
audited HBOC on Dec. 31, 1997, is cooperating with McKesson's 
effort to restate the earnings, spokeswoman Jane Ostrander said. 
</P>
<P>
	Accounting standards for the software industry changed in 1998,  
restricting firms from claiming profits more than a year before 
getting paid in full, said Larry Marsh, who follows the company for 
Lehman Brothers. ``I think that there were very loose standards 
used in a lot of this industry,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The real issue is whether McKesson HBOC can deliver its products  
on time, Chiarelli said. Despite all the financial questions, he 
said he's seen no evidence that the company can't produce what it 
promises. 
</P>
<P>
	``When they're able to do that,'' he said, ``much of these  
issues will get resolved.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
