<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stewart: I Thought About My Father  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PINEHURST, N.C. (AP) -- Payne Stewart stood in front of the  
television and cried his eyes out. Ahead lay the crucible of 
another U.S. Open. What made tears flow, though, was something lost 
in his past. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before I came to the course today, NBC ran a piece about  
myself and my father,'' Stewart said. ``I just stood there and 
bawled. I thought a lot about my father. I probably got a lot of 
strength from that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	William Stewart was a furniture salesman who went out the door  
some mornings wearing a canary yellow sport coat on the theory that 
it was better to have a customer remember you for something than 
not at all. 
</P>
<P>
	But he never had to impress more than a half-dozen people at  
once. And when his oldest son stood over a 15-foot par putt on the 
last green Sunday at Pinehurst No. 2, the audience was several 
million times that. 
</P>
<P>
	But this time, it wasn't so much about inviting attention as  
proving he was worthy of it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that I learned a lot from last year,'' he said. ``If  
you can learn from defeat, I think it makes you a much stronger 
player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Failure, it turns out, changed Payne Stewart more than all his  
past success ever could. A year ago, on a shimmering Sunday at the 
Olympic Club near San Francisco, he began the final round four 
strokes clear of the field, then missed a birdie putt from that 
same 15 feet at the last hole to let the championship escape his 
grasp. 
</P>
<P>
	Olympic is nicknamed the Graveyard of Champions because the same  
thing had happened to Ben Hogan in 1955, Arnold Palmer in 1966 and 
Tom Watson in 1987. And in the way that a curse hounds its victims 
through the years, none of the three ever got hold of another major 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	When Stewart walked away from that disappointment, he vowed it  
wouldn't bury him. As a steady drizzle ranked the Carolina 
sandhills, he made good on that promise. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I wanted to do,'' he said, ``was give myself a chance. I  
never gave up. I kept plugging and I kept playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	William Stewart, a two-time Missouri State Amateur champion,  
wouldn't have settled for anything less. When Payne was younger, 
his father had him stand on his shoes and then waltzed around the 
room teaching him to dance. William died in 1985, but he willed his 
son more than good footwork, a golf game and a taste for outlandish 
clothes. Resolve was a quality that topped the list. 
</P>
<P>
	When Stewart won his first major championship, the 1989 PGA, it  
was cast as much the result of fortune than fortitude. Everybody 
remembered Mike Reid slumped over his putter after dropping three 
strokes to par over the last two holes -- not Stewart tearing up 
Kemper Lakes' back nine in 31 and closing with a flurry of birdies. 
</P>
<P>
	Even his first U.S. Open win, at Hazeltine in 1991, had the feel  
of a man in the right place at the right time. Twice, eventual 
loser Scott Simpson let Stewart climb out of a two-stroke ditch 
over the final three holes -- first to earn a shot at the playoff on 
Sunday, then again to win the national championship. 
</P>
<P>
	But there were no questions left by the end of this one.  
</P>
<P>
	Stewart began the day at 1 under par, one stroke ahead of Phil  
Mickelson and two ahead of Tiger Woods. Another stroke back was 
David Duval and Vijay Singh. Stewart knew one or two of them might 
flinch over the course of the afternoon on a layout as tough as 
this one. But he also knew he was going to have beat one or all of 
them himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Ultimately, it was Mickelson, about to become a father himself,  
who pushed Stewart the hardest. 
</P>
<P>
	Twice on the back nine, the left-hander wrested the lead away.  
But he gave it back the final time at the 191-yard, par-3 17th. 
There, Mickelson hit his tee shot to 8 feet and Stewart to about 
half that distance. Mickelson missed his birdie try and Stewart 
made his, setting up the final act. 
</P>
<P>
	On 18, Stewart dumped his drive into the right rough, hacked it  
out with a 9-iron and then hit a lob wedge to 15 feet. Mickelson 
took the more conventional Open route -- hit the fairway, hit the 
green -- to 25 feet. Again, this time much more improbably, he 
missed and Stewart made. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would have made a cool story for my daughter to read  
about,'' Mickelson said, ``but it's still something special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Exactly how special Mickelson may not realize until he's  
actually raised a family of his own. 
</P>
<P>
	But Stewart had no problem remembering the feeling when someone  
asked him whether this victory would supplant his first win out on 
Tour -- the 1982 Quad Cities Open -- as his most cherished memory. 
</P>
<P>
	``That will never change,'' Stewart said, ``because my dad was  
there to see it.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@ap.org. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
