<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. Planes To Return From Balkans  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States will begin bringing home  
planes and pilots dispatched to Europe during the NATO bombing of 
Yugoslavia. More than 350 military planes, representing about half 
the number of U.S. aircraft that flew during the bombing campaign, 
will begin the return trip as soon as tomorrow. NATO troops who 
have moved into Kosovo have turned their attention to the 
peacekeeping duties of establishing security and laying the 
groundwork for democratic elections. Two Nepalese soldiers attached 
to the British force were killed today while clearing booby traps 
and land mines from a school near Pristina. They were the first 
allied fatalities since NATO entered the province on June 12. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Makes 1st Trip to Slovenia  
</P>
<P>
	LJUBLJANA, Slovenia (AP) -- Thousands of Slovenes cheered  
President Clinton today on the first visit by an American president 
to this small nation that broke away from Yugoslavia and Slobodan 
Milosevic in 1991. Clinton's visit was intended to draw attention 
to a prosperous Slovenia as a success story for Balkan nations, in 
contrast to the grim hardships Yugoslavia faces as it struggles to 
recover from NATO attacks. 

</P>
<P>
	Energy Dept. Plans Polygraph Tests  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Energy Department plans to give lie  
detector tests to as many as 5,000 nuclear weapons scientists and 
other employees in sensitive jobs with wholesale testing to begin 
later this summer, senior department officials said. It will be the 
first time any agency outside of the Central Intelligence Agency 
and the National Security Agency will engage in widespread use of 
polygraph tests on workers. The FBI uses the devices to screen 
prospective employees. There is concern about the reliability of 
the polygraph, known informally as a lie detector. Polygraph 
results are not admissible in court because of questions over their 
reliability. 

</P>
<P>
	Suspected Serial Killer Charged  
</P>
<P>
	MURPHYSBORO, Ill. (AP) -- An alleged serial killer who is  
apparently making his way from town to town by hopping freight 
trains was charged today with two murders in Illinois, bringing to 
eight the number of slayings the fugitive is linked to. Rafael 
Resendez-Ramirez was also put on the FBI's 10 Most Wanted list. 
Authorities believe Resendez-Ramirez has been riding the rails, 
finding victims along the way. All eight slayings took place on or 
near railroad tracks. 

</P>
<P>
	No Implants-Illness Link Found  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Silicone breast implants do not cause major  
illnesses, yet they frequently break open and leak, which can cause 
pain, disfigurement and repeat surgery, concludes a long-awaited 
report sought by Congress. The report by the Institute of Medicine 
is unlikely to end a decade-long controversy over implants, which 
thousands of women blame for severe illnesses from cancer to 
rheumatoid arthritis. Up to 1.8 million American women have 
received silicone breast implants since 1962 -- a time before the 
FDA required proof that all medical devices were safe and 
effective. 

</P>
<P>
	Some Sprint Customers Go Digital  
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Residential customers in three cities  
will get a first shot at Sprint's new digital-age phone service, 
which will allow them to talk on the phone, send a fax and check 
e-mail at the same time. Sprint's new ION -- Integrated On-Demand 
Network -- promises delivery of local and long-distance phone 
service and high-speed Internet access through a single connection. 
The nation's third-largest long-distance company has chosen Kansas 
City, Mo., Denver and Seattle to launch the service this fall. 
Sprint proposes charging a flat monthly rate, likely between $100 
to $150. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Mixed; Dow Down 39.58  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks pulled back slightly today with  
the Dow industrials finishing 39.58 lower at 10,815.98. On the 
NYSE, advancers led decliners 1,599-1,420. The Nasdaq rose 66.84 to 
2,630.28. 

</P>
<P>
	Sprewell May Play Point Guard  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Expect some new lineups from the New York Knicks  
tonight in Game 3 of the NBA finals as they look to slow down the 
San Antonio Spurs. While Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy hedged on his 
lineup intentions, Latrell Sprewell has publicly lobbied for a 
change that would move him to point guard with Allan Houston at 
shooting guard. The Spurs lead the Knicks 2-0 in the best-of-7 
series. 

</P>
<P>
	Devil Rays Edge Twins 3-2  
</P>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Jose Canseco singled home the go-ahead run in  
the seventh inning today as the Tampa Bay Devil Rays beat the 
Minnesota Twins 3-2. Tampa Bay extended its winning streak to 
three, completing a 15-day roadtrip -- the longest in the team's 
1 1/2-year history, with a 5-8 record. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief By SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  
  	   	
</P>
