<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 07:10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Trade Surplus Soars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's trade surplus soared in the first four  
months of the year and domestic production posted modest growth, 
officials said today. The trend was apparently caused by a drop in 
imports forced by the fall of the ruble. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's foreign trade surplus rose to $9.1 billion in the first  
four months of 1999 from $100 million in January-April of last 
year, the Russian Statistics Agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	The fall of the ruble -- from six to the dollar before the onset  
of an economic crisis in August to around 25 to the dollar -- has 
made imported goods too expensive for many Russians. But it also 
helped Russian manufacturers by boosting sales of cheaper domestic 
goods. 
</P>
<P>
	Imports in the first four months of 1999 shrank 47 percent  
compared to the same time last year, to $13 billion. Exports fell 
by 10 percent, to $22 billion, the agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's overall foreign trade was down 29 percent to $35  
billion, the statistics agency said. The slide slowed in April, 
when foreign trade totaled $10 billion, down 18 percent on the 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia also enjoyed a $2.9 billion trade surplus in April,  
compared with a deficit of $100 million a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's industrial output in the first five months of the year  
was up 1.5 percent from the corresponding period in 1998, and 
totaled 1.02 trillion rubles ($42 billion), the statistics agency 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Government officials hope Russia's economy will reverse its fall  
and the gross domestic product will grow 1.5 percent to 3 percent 
growth next year. But many experts doubt that will occur. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's GDP has fallen about 40 percent since the collapse of  
the Soviet Union in 1991. The GDP has only posted an increase in 
one year since then, rising a modest .8 percent in 1997. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
