<DOCNO> APW19990621.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 09:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Settles Prison Awards Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New limits on attorney-fee awards to inmates  
who sue over prison conditions apply only to legal work performed 
after the law took effect in 1996, the Supreme Court ruled today. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling in a Michigan case said the legal-fee provisions of  
the Prison Litigation Reform Act, enacted by Congress to rein in 
prisoner lawsuits, do not affect legal work performed on inmates' 
behalf before the law was enacted. 
</P>
<P>
	``To impose the new standards now, for work performed before the  
PLRA became effective, would upset the reasonable expectations of 
the parties,'' Justice Sandra Day O'Connor wrote for the court. 
</P>
<P>
	The prison-litigation law, which took effect on April 26, 1996,  
aims to discourage frivolous lawsuits. It imposes a cap on 
attorneys' fees that can be awarded to inmates who successfully sue 
on a claim that prison conditions violate their civil rights. 
</P>
<P>
	All nine justices agreed the fee limits could not be applied to  
legal work performed before the law's effective date. 
</P>
<P>
	Justices Ruth Bader Ginsburg and John Paul Stevens voted to go  
further and decide the fee limit would apply only to cases filed 
after the law took effect. They said the fee limit should not apply 
to cases filed before April 1996, even if the legal work was 
performed after the law's effective date. 
</P>
<P>
	Lower courts had split on whether the fee limit applied to cases  
pending in April 1996. In today's case, a federal appeals court had 
ruled that the limit did not apply to two lawsuits filed by 
Michigan inmates. 
</P>
<P>
	Female inmates sued in 1977 over programming and access to the  
courts, and male inmates sued in 1980 over prison conditions 
including sanitation, health care, overcrowding and protection from 
harm. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge ruled for the female inmates after a trial, and  
the male inmates' lawsuit was resolved in a 1985 agreement with the 
state. In each case, the inmates were awarded $150 an hour in 
lawyers' fees for monitoring of the court's order. 
</P>
<P>
	After the prisoner litigation measure took effect, Michigan  
officials argued that the limits should be applied to reduce the 
fee to $112.50 an hour for all fees awarded after April 1996, no 
matter when the work was performed. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge ruled partly for the state, saying the fee limit  
applied to legal work performed after the law took effect, but not 
to work performed before then. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said the fee limit did  
not apply to pending cases at all, no matter when the work was 
performed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court decided the main issue was not when the case  
was filed, but when the legal work was performed. 
</P>
<P>
	``In other words, as applied to work performed after the  
effective date of the PLRA, the PLRA has future effect on future 
work; this does not raise retroactivity concerns,'' O'Connor wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Martin vs. Hadix, 98-262.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 22:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Net Marketing Firm a Pyramid Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Barbara Edelman saw International Heritage  
Inc. as liberation from a job delivering newspapers in the middle 
of the night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had visions of driving a Cadillac,'' said the 62-year-old  
from Crowley, La. 
</P>
<P>
	Randall Peter, 44, a Pearland, Texas, electrical engineer, also  
envisioned riches. International Heritage's showy catalog with 
Coach leather bags and expensive crystal overcame his suspicion of 
get-rick-quick schemes. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Waterford crystal is going to let us sell their products,  
we must be legitimate,'' Peters remembers thinking. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Securities and Exchange Commission says International  
Heritage was nothing more than a huge pyramid scheme. And luxury 
goods makers such as Callaway Golf and Bosca claim International 
Heritage was reselling their merchandise without their knowledge. 
</P>
<P>
	Four years after it was started in Raleigh, International  
Heritage is bankrupt and being liquidated and its three founders 
face federal civil penalties. More than 150,000 distributors in the 
United States and Canada may have lost their investments, and 
12,600 creditors have filed claims against International Heritage 
totaling more than $30 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, a federal bankruptcy trustee unveiled a tentative  
settlement that would force Stanley Van Etten, the company's 
charismatic president, to surrender a $3.5 million bond he had 
posted and to pay the Securities and Exchange Commission another 
$150,000. The settlement contains no admission of guilt on Van 
Etten's part. 
</P>
<P>
	Pyramid schemes are marketing plans in which investors or  
distributors make their money back primarily from fees paid by 
newer investors. A scheme cannot survive, and its distributors 
cannot make money, without a steady stream of new participants. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Trade Commission warns against pyramid schemes in  
its Web site (www.ftc.gov), noting that most states outlaw the 
plans. ``When a plan collapses, most people -- except perhaps those 
at the very top of the pyramid -- lose their money,'' the FTC says. 
</P>
<P>
	An SEC complaint filed in March 1998 in Atlanta alleged  
International Heritage defrauded investors and generated more than 
$150 million in revenue by promoting merchandise with snob appeal, 
but said it profited mostly from new distributors and collecting 
their sign-up fees. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency quotes International Heritage's sales kit as actually  
discouraging representatives from recruiting a person with a retail 
sales background because, ``odds are that he will do that (sell the 
products) at the expense of neglecting to build a sales 
organization beneath himself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Van Etten disputes the SEC's charges, and its characterization  
of his marketing company. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of the money came from product purchases from new sales  
reps to the company,'' he said. ``I would offer in response, that's 
the same for the whole network marketing industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really an unfair situation,'' Van Etten said. ``Network  
marketing has a problem with perception. People think it's illegal 
to begin with. Then, to complicate it, a regulator can just allege 
it's a pyramid with no judicial process, and we're virtually forced 
out of business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	International Heritage distributors paid $250 each to start up  
to seven marketing networks plus $100 for training materials. 
Investing the maximum $1,850 could return up to $15,400 a week in 
revenue, the SEC quoted the company's sales pitch as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Randall Peter paid $250 for the right to sell the merchandise.  
He also paid $750 to sponsor three family members in Iowa and 
hundreds of dollars more for training materials for them. Barbara 
Edelman said she figures she and her son are owed about $400 each. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Etten, 37, marketed International Heritage by sounding  
themes such as personal freedom and spirituality at meetings in 
churches and halls across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	He estimates he made ``a couple million dollars'' last year and  
about $5 million in 1997 from all his business ventures. He now 
runs a venture capital and consulting firm. 
</P>
<P>
	International Heritage filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy, which  
leads to liquidation, in November. The SEC then filed a civil 
complaint alleging Van Etten and co-founders Claude Savage and 
Larry G. Smith were responsible for fraud, filing false reports and 
illegal sale of unregistered securities. The FBI is also 
investigating Van Etten and International Heritage. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week's tentative settlement must be approved by the SEC  
commissioners, a bankruptcy court judge and the Atlanta federal 
judge overseeing the SEC's complaint. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
