<HEADLINE> New San Diego Padres Park Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- The start of construction on the San Diego  
Padres' new downtown ballpark will be delayed until after a study 
on its impact on the neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	Superior Court Judge Judith McConnell ruled Monday that the city  
of San Diego and the team broke state law by going forward with the 
project before the completion of an environmental impact report, 
expected in September. 
</P>
<P>
	``This does not dissuade us in the slightest from building the  
ballpark,'' Padres owner John Moores said. ``We're going to keep 
pace with the voters. They approved the project and by God we're 
going to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The judge's ruling came in response to a lawsuit by the  
Coalition Advocating Redevelopment Excellence, comprised of 
residents in communities surrounding the project site who want the 
stadium moved a few blocks east to save historic buildings from 
demolition. 
</P>
<P>
	The city has argued it was working from a 1992 master  
environmental impact study prepared for the nearby Horton Plaza 
shopping center. 
</P>
<P>
	The 42,000-seat stadium, approved by voters in November, would  
serve as the anchor for a 26-block development that includes 
offices, hotels, retail outlets and homes. 
</P>
<P>
	The project will cost an estimated $1 billion; the ballpark, a  
joint city-Padres effort, is estimated at $411 million, including 
$296 million from public financing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
