<HEADLINE> Cubs' Gonzalez To Have Arm Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Chicago Cubs right-hander Jeremi Gonzalez will  
have additional surgery on his right elbow, yet another blow to the 
team's pitching staff. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez, 24, had ulnar nerve surgery last August on his  
pitching elbow. He has been experiencing continuing discomfort in 
his elbow, and an MRI showed abnormalities. 
</P>
<P>
	Surgery will be performed as soon as possible to determine the  
severity of the injury, the Cubs said. 
</P>
<P>
	As a rookie in 1997, Gonzalez was the club's winningest pitcher  
despite spending the first two months of the season at Triple-A 
Iowa. In a four-start span early last year, he went 3-1 with a 
shutout and a 1.86 ERA. He was 7-7 with a 5.32 ERA when his season 
ended because of the injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight Cubs pitchers have been on the disabled list this season,  
including Gonzalez and two other 1998 starters: Kerry Wood and 
Kevin Tapani. Wood is missing the entire season following ligament 
replacement surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	Cubs closer Rod Beck is sidelined following arthroscopic surgery  
on his right elbow. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago also activated outfielder Robin Jennings, who had been  
on an injury rehabilitation assignment. Jennings will rejoin the 
Cubs on Tuesday in Denver, taking the roster spot of reliever Doug 
Creek, who was optioned to Iowa. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
