<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU Still Split on Chocolate Purity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LUXEMBOURG (AP) -- The European Union governments today failed to  
find an answer to a question that has divided them for years: How 
much vegetable fat -- other than cocoa butter -- can you put in 
chocolate and still call it chocolate? 
</P>
<P>
	The EU interior ministers were close to an answer until Belgium  
rejected a compromise proposal, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The EU's chocolate debate pits eight purist nations against  
seven that take a relaxed view of chocolate. 
</P>
<P>
	Belgium, France, Italy, Spain, Luxembourg, Germany, Greece and  
the Netherlands ban cocoa-butter substitutes in chocolate. 
</P>
<P>
	The others -- Britain, Ireland, Denmark, Portugal, Austria,  
Finland and Sweden -- don't mind chocolate containing milk and 
non-cocoa fats and object to their chocolate being banned from sale 
in the purist countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany, which currently holds the EU presidency, put forward a  
compromise Monday allowing up to 5 percent vegetable fats other 
than cocoa butter in chocolate provided the packaging clearly said 
that. The compromise listed six non-cocoa vegetable fats that could 
be used in chocolate making. 
</P>
<P>
	But Belgium -- a country with a sector devoted to making  
chocolates from 100 percent cocoa butter -- refused to go along, 
effectively scuttling the compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	The chocolate debate dates back to 1992 when EU governments  
agreed to clean up laws, such as the ones on the content and sale 
conditions of chocolate, that prevent the EU from being a truly 
single market. 
</P>
<P>
	The European Commission proposed changes in 1996. On Oct. 23,  
1997, the European Parliament agreed to allow non-cocoa vegetable 
fats into chocolate, though that is unlikely to occur soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Countries wanting to stick to a 100 percent cocoa butter rule  
said they feared that diluting chocolate with palm oil and other 
fats would destabilize the economies of cocoa-exporting countries 
and undermine consumer confidence in chocolate. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
