<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Lawyer Turns Victims' Advocate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Nina Salarno was strolling along a  
beach one recent sunny day, her fiance at her side, when she burst 
into tears of grief. 
</P>
<P>
	It had been 20 years, yet time hadn't blocked images of her  
sister on the same beach in Mexico shortly before she returned home 
to California and was murdered by an estranged boyfriend. 
</P>
<P>
	Salarno, 33, hasn't hidden from the tragedy.  
</P>
<P>
	She became a deputy district attorney, prosecuting sexual  
predators and spouse abusers. She became a victims' rights 
activist. And now, she's been appointed to run the new crime 
victims' aid office for the state attorney general. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those memories of my sister come back. That doesn't happen a  
lot but sometimes it does,'' Salarno said. ``But sometimes it's 
that hurt, too, that makes you go on and makes you even stronger. 
</P>
<P>
	``I sit here at my job now and think, 'I know what it's like.'  
If I can try to make it a little bit better for someone else, then 
my sister's death hasn't gone in vain and I've gained from that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Bill Lockyer chose Salarno in April. California  
must be as determined to aid crime victims as it's been to punish 
criminals, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I looked around for someone with energy, commitment to the  
task and appropriate life experience that would help them do a good 
job,'' Lockyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Salarno acknowledged an irony in her appointment by Lockyer.  
Like her mother, with whom she founded Crime Victims United, she 
became a Republican activist pushing for crime victims' rights. 
</P>
<P>
	That movement opposed Lockyer, a Democrat who led the Senate for  
four years, instead backing GOP lawmakers who wanted tougher 
criminal penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockyer said he doesn't care about Salarno's party affiliation.  
And Salarno, while remaining a Republican, said she will take a 
bipartisan approach in her new job. 
</P>
<P>
	The path to that job started in 1979.  
</P>
<P>
	Her sister Catina tried to end her relationship with her  
boyfriend, but he didn't want to break up. During one of their many 
quarrels, Nina Salarno, then 12, watched in the family's San 
Francisco home as he told her 18-year-old sister, ``I'm going to 
kill you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A week later, on Sept. 3, 1979, he did.  
</P>
<P>
	Steven Burns shot and killed Catina Salarno on her first day at  
Stockton's University of the Pacific. Burns was sentenced to 17 
years to life in prison and remains behind bars. 
</P>
<P>
	Then age 13, Nina Salarno was called to testify but was left on  
the stand waiting, next to a big picture of her sister's body and 
her sister's purse, covered in dried blood. After 15 long minutes, 
she fled the courtroom in tears. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is what made me become a deputy district attorney,'' she  
said. ``I didn't want people to go through what I went through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Salarno received a law degree in 1992 and worked as a prosecutor  
for Tulare, Placer and Sacramento counties. She worked her way up 
from drunken driving cases to prosecuting felonies such as sexual 
assaults and domestic violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Sacramento County Judge James Long calls Salarno a ``tough but  
fair prosecutor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Salarno, with a startup staff of two, advises the attorney  
general on victims issues and will work to improve and coordinate 
aid, which includes counseling, emergency assistance such as 
shelter and medical care, and legal advice. 
</P>
<P>
	Joan Irving, whose 17-year-old son was wounded in 1994 by a gang  
member, said she had trouble finding a prosecutor who would 
aggressively pursue the attempted-murder case. 
</P>
<P>
	Salarno got a conviction.  
</P>
<P>
	``She took into account my thoughts and considerations,'' Irving  
said. ``She understood my pain.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
