<DOCNO> APW19990621.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 17:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of France Urges Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The Bank of France said Monday that the three banks  
involved in a protracted takeover battle should meet to resolve 
their differences. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of France Governor Jean-Claude Trichet said in a statement  
that he would invite the three parties involved -- Societe Generale, 
Paribas and Banque Nationale de Paris -- to participate in a working 
meeting to find a solution ``as soon as possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The request came as investors await several key rulings on the  
takeover battle that has roiled the French banking world for close 
to four months. 
</P>
<P>
	BNP made an unsolicited $37 billion bid for both Societe  
Generale and Paribas March 10, a month after the two banks had 
themselves announced a friendly merger to create SG Paribas. 
</P>
<P>
	The two banks have been fighting off the bid. Should BNP  
succeed, it would create the world's first $1 trillion bank in 
terms of assets. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Societe Generale sweetened its bid for Paribas  
shares, a move that will further delay the outstanding offers, most 
likely until the end of July or even August. 
</P>
<P>
	Conseil des Marches Financiers, a market regulator, was  
scheduled to rule late Monday on whether to clear Societe 
Generale's new bid for Paribas, but may not make the decision 
public until Tuesday. The stock market watchdog Commission des 
Operations de Bourse must also rule on the bid. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of France said it would delay its own recommendation on  
Societe Generale's counter-bid for Paribas shares until it receives 
more information on the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of France officials declined to announce a date for the  
final decision, saying only that it would be made as soon as 
possible. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
