<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall in Midday Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks slipped Tuesday as investors took  
profits on recent gains, while the dollar fell against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 36.72 points,  
or 0.21 percent, closing the morning session at 17,702.13. On 
Monday, the average closed up 307.59 points, or 1.76 percent, at 
17,738.85 -- its highest closing level since October 6, 1997, when 
the Nikkei closed at 17,824.78. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.98 yen, down 0.36 yen from late Monday in  
Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 122.42 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo share prices started higher as investors bought  
high-technology shares and shares of blue-chip exporters, but fell 
as the day went on. 
</P>
<P>
	``Profit-taking was natural as the pace of recent gains was  
fast,'' said Shigeharu Shiraishi, managing director at SG Yamaichi 
Asset Management Co. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar slipped as players nudged the  
U.S. currency down to see how low the Bank of Japan will let it go, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the Bank of Japan intervened several times to buy  
dollars and sell yen in an attempt to stem the Japanese currency's 
rise. Monday's intervention was the fourth action by Japan's 
central bank in 10 days. 
</P>
<P>
	``The recent fast rise in the yen is due to excessive hopes for  
a Japanese economic recovery. I think the rise is disruptive to the 
market, and the purpose of recent interventions was to preempt such 
moves,'' Japan's Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said at a regular 
news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts say the market is far from bullish on the dollar.  
The Bank of Japan is virtually the only buyer in the market, while 
many others are lined up to sell the currency at current levels and 
higher, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although recent government data indicate there are some signs of  
improvement in Japan's economy, the nation is still struggling to 
overcome its worst recession since World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank's repeated interventions are seen by analysts  
as an attempt to make sure that the nascent recovery is not 
torpedoed by a sudden surge in the value of the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 126.18 yen, down  
from 126.66 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.7600 percent from Monday's finish of 1.7500 percent, driving 
its price down to 96.94 yen from 97.02 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
