<HEADLINE> Bonds Prices Slip as Yields Jump / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices fell Monday, as investors sold  
Treasury securities ahead of several upcoming corporate bond 
offerings. The drop pushed yields back over 6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond, fell 5/8 point,  
or $6.25 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the 
opposite direction, rose to 6.02 percent from 5.97 percent late 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated $10 billion in new corporate debt is set to hit the  
market this week as issuers take advantage of a lull in economic 
data that could influence interest rates. This week's offerings are 
expected to include a mammoth offering from Ford Motor Credit Co., 
which could be worth $6 billion or more. 
</P>
<P>
	The outlook for corporate bonds has improved since Federal  
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan hinted last week that the central 
bank will raise rates only modestly over the next few months and 
some investors sold Treasurys to make room for the new issues. 
Corporate bonds usually pay higher rates than government bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader bond market, prices of short-term Treasury  
securities were up 1/16 point to 3/32 point and intermediate 
maturities were up between 7/32 point and 15/32 point, reported 
Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.71 percent, as the  
discount rose 0.06 percentage point to 4.59 percent. Six-month 
yields were 5.02 percent, as the discount rose 0.06 percentage 
point to 4.83 percent. One-year yields were 4.99 percent as the 
discount rose 0.03 percentage point from late Friday to 4.75 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 4.75 percent from 4.69 late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 1/32 point to 120 15/32 from 120 1/2 late 
Friday. The average yield to maturity was unchanged at 5.44 
percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
