<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Players May Have To Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Former major leaguers who claimed they were  
cheated out of baseball card royalties may wind up owing money to 
owners because of the meager success of their lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury found last year that the ex-players had been underpaid  
but rejected a claim of fraud and awarded only $75,000 in damages. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial judge reduced the award to about $25,000 -- an average  
of $65 for each of the 384 players -- and granted a new trial on the 
dispute over the other $50,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge's decision was upheld by the state's 1st District  
Court of Appeal in a 3-0 ruling made public Monday. The damage 
award is less than the $47,000 they were offered in a pretrial 
settlement, said Martin Glick, a lawyer for Major League Baseball 
Properties Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Under California law, plaintiffs whose damages are less than  
they were offered before trial must reimburse the other side for 
court expenses incurred after the settlement offer. The payment, if 
any, would come only from the five ex-players who filed the suit 
and not from all 384 covered by the class action, Glick said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his client's costs after the settlement offer were about  
$84,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Ronald Katz, lawyer for the former players, could not be reached  
for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit was filed by a group of retirees led by Pete Coscarart,  
86, an infielder for the Brooklyn Dodgers and Pittsburgh Pirates in 
the 1930s and 1940s. 
</P>
<P>
	The other lead plaintiffs are longtime New York Yankees player  
and coach Frank Crosetti, former outfielders Bernie Carbo and Ken 
Landreaux and former piitcher Milt Pappas. 
</P>
<P>
	They challenged the operation of a program established by MLBP  
and a charitable organization in 1990 to license ex-players' names 
and likenesses on baseball cards and other products, such as 
decorative pins. 
</P>
<P>
	Royalties from products that used the name or picture of any  
ex-player among the 384 who joined the program were pooled and 
shared with all the players. Hall of Famers, the most in demand, 
got shares five times as large as those of other players. 
</P>
<P>
	The program paid $1 million in royalties before it was shut down  
at the end of 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The ex-players lost their chance for substantial damages when an  
Alameda County Superior Court jury found that MLBP had 
miscalculated some of their royalty payments but hadn't 
deliberately cheated them. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court agreed with Superior Court Judge Demetrios  
Agretelis that the program didn't cover royalties from films and 
videos showing the ex-players, or from products created and sold by 
MLBP itself rather than by third-party licensees. 
</P>
<P>
	The opinion by Presiding Justice Barbara Jones also agreed with  
Agretelis' decision to order a new trial on disputed royalties from 
a baseball card series by Hi-Pro. Agretelis said the jury's 
decision that the program covered those royalties -- a majority of 
the total damages -- was not supported by the evidence. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 22:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Biologists Creating Beefier Tomato </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAYTON, Ohio (AP) -- Three Ohio researchers are using  
gene-splicing technology to try to grow a beefier tomato they hope 
will save the makers of ketchup, tomato paste and soup millions of 
dollars in processing costs. 
</P>
<P>
	``A beefier tomato will have higher solids,'' Jerome Servaites,  
research biologist at the University of Dayton who is part of a 
three-member team, said Monday. ``In making ketchup and tomato 
paste, you have to remove more than half the water, and that's very 
expensive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tomatoes grown for the processing market are usually about 95  
percent water. If that figure could be reduced by 5 percent or 6 
percent, the researchers say, it could save the makers of ketchup, 
tomato paste and other processed tomato products $75 million a 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Servaites and fellow researchers Richard Sayre, an associate  
professor of plant biology at Ohio State University, and Candance 
Lowell, associate professor of biology at Central State University, 
want to amplify the activity of one gene and depress the activity 
of another to boost the production of starch in the tomato and 
reduce a natural loss of starch that occurs as tomato plants 
mature. 
</P>
<P>
	The scientists expect to confirm the genetic alterations in  
starter plants later this year and transplant them into soil. The 
plants are being kept inside a greenhouse at Ohio State. 
</P>
<P>
	Margaret Mellon, director of the Union of Concerned Scientists'  
agriculture and biotechnology program, questioned the benefit to 
consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	She said crops that are genetically engineered could pose risks  
and should first be checked for safety before being put on the 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, she said, changing a food through genetic  
engineering might cause allergic reactions in people who are 
normally not allergic to that food. 
</P>
<P>
	``The disturbing thing to me is there is no requirement that  
folks producing a tomato like this go to the FDA (Food and Drug 
Administration) and have it reviewed for safety,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Margulis, a genetics engineer campaigner for the  
environmental group Greenpeace, echoed Mellon's concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's likely to be problems,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	But Servaitis said he is confident in the safety of the tomato.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see any problems with this kind of thing,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The researchers' $44,000 project is funded by a grant from the  
Ohio Board of Regents. Similar work has been done at the University 
of Illinois. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 22:00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Is Your Head in the Clouds? / Commentary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *AP Business Analyst    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Achieving your financial goals may depend on how  
near to being correct you are on a seemingly simple question: Does 
reality lie with history or in the expectations of today? 
</P>
<P>
	Or, to be more specific, is the real world to be found in the  
period 1926-1998, when investors in stocks earned an average of 11 
percent a year? Or now, when day traders seek to make that in a 
day? 
</P>
<P>
	Simple to ask, hard to answer. And whether you're a small  
individual investor or the manager of a large portfolio, the answer 
becomes all the tougher after you've experienced triple-digit 
gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Stated differently: Could times really have changed so much that  
investors should routinely seek to double their money in months, 
when on average it took nearly seven years to do this in the past? 
</P>
<P>
	It's hard to believe that the record of history no longer  
applies. It's just as hard to disbelieve when you've quintupled 
your money in less than a year, as owners of Broadcom Corp. or 
Qualcomm Inc. have. 
</P>
<P>
	Has progress speeded up that much? Has time shrunk?  
</P>
<P>
	Nobody can offer proof positive, and reliance on so-called  
experts provides no assurance one way or another. You can take your 
pick of advice; they range from warnings that history will soon 
reassert itself to declarations that the best is yet to come. 
</P>
<P>
	Your choice, a tough one considering the consequences, which  
might include the affordability of tuition payments, early vs. late 
retirement, and general financial comfort as opposed to stress. 
</P>
<P>
	A bit of advice you can rely on: Given time, you can be a rather  
conservative investor and still have your big gains. Compounding 
makes it possible; given time, compounding works miracles. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts at Standard &AMP; Poor's not long ago worked up a startling  
illustration of that miracle, to wit, an investment totaling just 
$16,000 that provides the investor with $531,188. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, it takes time -- 40 years, in fact. But assuming a  
$2,000-a-year contribution for eight years, and a compounding rate 
of 10 percent a year, you would have that sum in retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	Contrast that with the investor who waited eight years before  
making the same $2,000-a-year contributions. This person could 
contribute $2,000 a year for the next 32 years -- and have only 
$442,496. 
</P>
<P>
	That's what time does, but the power of time is often lost sight  
of in an age of impatience. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerald Perritt, statistician, believer in history's relevance  
and founder of the ``Mutual Fund Letter,'' reminds us of a sobering 
statistical concept called ``gravitation toward the mean.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In short, those long-term averages have a tendency to prove  
themselves again and again. It suggests, he suggests, that high 
equity returns could be headed lower than their long-term averages. 
</P>
<P>
	He can offer a basketful of evidence that prices are too high,  
but just one example illustrates: 
</P>
<P>
	Stock prices, measured by the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, a  
relatively conservative indicator, have grown at a 24.5 percent 
annual rate since 1995. But corporate earnings, upon which prices 
are based in the long run, have grown by only 1.9 percent a year. 
</P>
<P>
	With statistical gravitation in mind, he warns, ``Don't be  
fooled into extrapolating recent returns when setting your 
investment objectives.'' To do so, he says, is to have your head in 
the clouds. 
</P>
<P>
	But you can find plenty of advisers who take the opposite view.  
They emphasize that the market's recent gains are real, tangible, 
usable. ``Don't bury your head in the sand,'' they say. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 17:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors Decry Claims by Dietary Aids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A delegation of doctors Monday asked the American  
Medical Association to seek a stronger federal law on dietary 
supplements that promise everything from banishing cellulite to 
boosting brain power. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're seeing doctors continuing to be frustrated by this,''  
said Dr. Ronald M. Davis, a member of the AMA's Council on 
Scientific Affairs, after speaking at the organization's annual 
policymaking convention. 
</P>
<P>
	``Patients are asking about these products,'' he said.  
``Patients are using these products and not telling the doctor 
about them. They have unclear, unproven efficacy; no government 
regulation; and now big pharmaceutical companies are getting into 
the act, and there's massive advertising.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The AMA enacted such a policy six months ago at its winter  
meeting, but doctors on Monday said the AMA needs to put teeth into 
the policy. A vote on the issue could come this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the current law, dietary supplements -- often used for  
medicinal purposes such as garlic for heart benefits and St. John's 
wort to relieve depression -- are allowed to be marketed without the 
prior approval required of drugs. But they are prohibited from 
making health claims. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're putting out a lot of medications out there that have no  
standards,'' said Dr. Richard A. Beach of Pensacola, Fla., a board 
member of the American Society of Addictions Medicine. He was 
referring to dietary supplements. 
</P>
<P>
	``St. John's wort has been shown to be very effective for  
depression,'' he said in an interview after addressing the group. 
But he recalled a study in Florida of 13 large pharmacies showing 
that their brand names of St. John's wort contained anywhere from 5 
percent to 250 percent of the amount of active ingredient claimed 
on the label. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Judy Linger, a child and adolescent psychiatrist in  
Lexington, Ky., testified about a woman she saw who had a seizure 
as a result of taking St. John's wort along with a prescription 
antidepressant. The woman was taking three prescription drugs and 
about 25 over-the-counter dietary supplements, mostly to lose 
weight, Linger said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would like to see the AMA work with the federal government  
to create accountability in the companies that are producing these 
products, and with the FDA, to have them regulate them as real 
drugs, because so many of them do contain active ingredients,'' 
Linger said. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis singled out Cellasene, which is marketed for reducing  
cellulite. He displayed a full-page newspaper ad that touted the 
product as ``the safe, clinically studied dietary supplement with 
natural herbal extracts that helps reduce cellulite.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then, he pointed to a footnote on the ad that said the  
statements had not been evaluated by the FDA and the product is not 
meant to treat, cure or prevent disease. 
</P>
<P>
	``To make a health claim in the headline, and then to say we're  
not really making a health claim is disingenuous, at best, and 
outrageous and needful of immediate remedy by the federal 
government and the FDA,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The day after the ad ran, the Italian manufacturer of Cellasene,  
Medestea Internazional, released studies it said backed the 
assertions about the supplement's effectiveness. It claimed Italian 
studies, using several dozen women, demonstrated that women could 
reduce their hip and thigh circumference within eight weeks of 
treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Executives at Rexall Sundown Inc., the U.S. distributor of  
Cellasene, were not available for comment, said company spokeswoman 
Lisa Givens. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 01:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up, Tokyo Stocks Advance / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was still sharply higher against  
the yen at midday Monday, boosted by talk that the Bank of Japan 
bought dollars to stem the Japanese currency's rise. Tokyo stocks 
advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.94 yen at midafternoon, up 2.62 yen from  
late Friday in Tokyo and also above its late Friday level in New 
York of 120.44 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 307.59 points,  
or 1.76 percent, ending the day at 17,738.85. On Friday, the 
average fell 39.19 points, or 0.22 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealing, traders believed the Bank of Japan bought  
dollars and sold yen Monday morning, although it was not 
immediately known at what level the bank stepped in. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders believe the apparent intervention came shortly after the  
Finance Ministry announced that Japan's trade surplus shrank by a 
greater-then-expected 31.5 percent in May. 
</P>
<P>
	``If in fact the BOJ did intervene above the 120.00 yen level,  
it shows their resolve to push the dollar up even further,'' said 
Shuji Takano, assistant manager of foreign exchange at ABN AMRO 
Bank in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	If the intervention did occur, it would mark the fourth time in  
less than two weeks that Japan's central bank has done so. On 
Friday, at the BOJ's bequest, the European Central Bank bought 
euros for yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 126.66 yen, up from  
122.73 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices started higher as foreign investors  
continued to buy stocks in hope that Japan's tenuous economic 
recovery may finally be picking up steam. 
</P>
<P>
	During a three-day meeting of the Group of Seven major  
industrialized nations, which ended Sunday in Cologne, Germany, 
other leaders maintained pressure on Japan to do more to ensure it 
is on a domestic-led growth path. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said that the Japanese government  
will take every measure available to ensure stable growth. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange was up 22.76 points, or 
1.63 percent, to 1,419.05. The TOPIX lost 2.88 points, or 0.21 
percent, on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 213 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.7800 percent from Friday's finish of 1.7300 percent, 
driving its price down to 96.77 yen from 97.18 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
