<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 17:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aetna-Prudential Merger Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Prompting immediate objections, the Justice  
Department announced Monday that it will permit Aetna Inc.'s 
proposed acquisition of Prudential Insurance's health care business 
if Aetna sells its health maintenance organization business in two 
Texas metropolitan areas. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department and the Texas attorney general's office  
filed a civil antitrust lawsuit to block the merger, simultaneously 
filing a proposed consent decree allowing the purchase to go 
forward providing that NYLCare in Houston and Dallas-Fort Worth is 
sold. 
</P>
<P>
	This ``leaves an awful lot of markets as badly out of whack'' as  
the ones in Texas would be if they were included in the merger, 
said Dr. Nancy Dickey, president of the American Medical 
Association. She said New Jersey has a ``potentially worse'' 
anti-competitive situation than Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	The AMA asked the Justice Department last year to block the  
acquisition, arguing that Aetna's $1 billion bid to become the 
largest HMO in the country would harm patient care. 
</P>
<P>
	Dickey identified New York and Georgia as other states that  
would be adversely affected by the merger, as well as Florida, 
despite the fact that its large population of Medicare patients 
protects it ``to some degree.'' She said other states would be 
harmed as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas is ``a big win, but it's a first step,'' said Dickey. ``We  
clearly will have to work with other states.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Irving P. Ratner, president of the Medical Society of New  
Jersey, called the merger ``a harbinger of bad things to come for 
New Jersey with regard to our patients.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Together they will have a monopolistic organization which will  
control upwards of 35 or 36 percent of all of the patient care in 
the state of New Jersey if the merger goes through,'' said Ratner. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics of the merger have 60 days to file objections. A federal  
judge in Dallas could then approve or disapprove the decree. 
</P>
<P>
	The head of the Justice Department's antitrust division, Joel  
Klein, said the proposed settlement ``demonstrates the department's 
commitment to preserve competition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aetna U.S. Healthcare responded in a statement, ``We do not in  
any way share (the Justice Department's) view regarding the 
potential effect of the acquisition on competition and physician 
reimbursements in Texas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Health care consumers are demanding more choice -- in products  
and in physicians -- it simply wouldn't make good business sense for 
us to take actions that would be contrary to this, including 
economic actions that could significantly reduce the number of 
physicians in our networks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Richard L. Huber, Aetna's chairman and chief executive officer,  
said the divestiture in Texas ``was the most expeditious way'' to 
close out the Justice Department review process. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit said Aetna would have become the dominant provider  
of HMO and HMO-based point-of-service plans in Houston and Dallas, 
with 63 percent and 42 percent of enrollees in those areas. 
</P>
<P>
	A combination of Aetna, NYLCare and Prudential would have  
enabled Aetna to depress physicians' reimbursement rates in Houston 
and Dallas, said the department. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Attorney General John Cornyn said patients ``will benefit  
both from the lower health plan prices that competition ensures and 
the preservation of quality health care.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aetna provides health care benefits to over 15 million plan  
members nationwide, while Prudential provides care to 5 million 
plan members. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 00:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Miami Wins Title With Team Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- This time, the ball stayed in the park.  
Finally, Miami coach Jim Morris had a new topic for the civic 
luncheon circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	With two big swings from Kevin Brown and a tricky curveball by  
Michael Neu, the Hurricanes at last delivered a national title to 
Morris, the only coach to reach the College World Series each of 
his first six years. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown homered in the second inning and hit a three-run double in  
Miami's five-run fifth, leading the Hurricanes to a 6-5 victory 
over Florida State in the national championship game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great to win for coach Morris,'' Brown said. ``He has  
been here so many times. He definitely deserved to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neu threw the last two innings Saturday for his 16th save,  
retiring the side in the ninth and striking out Kevin Cash to end 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was trying to make the right pitch and focus,'' Neu said.  
``We were one pitch away from the national championship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At that point, Morris couldn't help thinking about what happened  
in Omaha three years ago. Miami was one out from the title when 
LSU's Warren Morris homered in the Tigers' 9-8 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``It did cross my mind,'' the Miami coach said. ``I sure wasn't  
designing a ring in the dugout. I did remember what happened. I had 
a flashback.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neu made sure the ball stayed in the park. Cash missed on a big  
cut and the Hurricanes swarmed Neu with an infield pileup. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mike made a tremendous pitch, a great curveball that was  
impossible to take but impossible to hit,'' Morris said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since losing the title on a dramatic hit by a player who shares  
his last name, coach Morris has repeatedly been asked about it -- by 
reporters, by fans, by diners at civic luncheons in South Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got to admit it,'' he said. ``Sometimes, I had a very,  
very difficult time answering. I don't think people can understand 
how traumatic that was to our team and our coaches. It was 
crushing, just crushing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Hurricanes erased those memories by beating Florida State  
for the sixth time in seven games between the intrastate rivals 
this season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seminoles got a gritty performance from right-hander Blair  
Varnes, a freshman making his first appearance in Omaha after 
tearing a knee ligament during the pileup when Florida State won 
its super regional. 
</P>
<P>
	Varnes will have surgery later this week, but he wore a bulky  
knee brace under his uniform against Miami. He couldn't extend his 
plant foot and he hobbled when he ran to field the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't want to be old and gray and regret that I didn't  
pitch for the national championship,'' Varnes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida State coach Mike Martin had few options besides Varnes  
after using seven pitchers in a 13-inning victory over Stanford to 
reach the final. Varnes threw into the seventh, leaving with his 
team trailing 6-2. 
</P>
<P>
	``Boy, was he gutty,'' Martin said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Seminoles pulled within 6-4 in the seventh and 6-5 in the  
eighth after Ryan Barthelemy hit a leadoff triple over the head of 
center fielder Brian Seever and scored on John-Ford Griffin's 
sacrifice. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, Marshall McDougall, who hit two home runs against Stanford  
and had an NCAA-record six in a victory at Maryland last month, 
flied out deep to left, with Mike Rodriguez making the catch on the 
warning track. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just put it up there in the wind,'' McDougall said. ``I got  
excited when I saw the guy at the wall, but it didn't go out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The victory capped a season of challenges for the Hurricanes,  
who won their last 11 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Catcher Russ Jacobson, a third-round pick by the Philadelphia  
Phillies, was lost to a forearm injury in May. Four pitchers, 
including staff ace Alex Santos, sat out with injuries at various 
times this season. So did Rodriguez, third baseman Lale Esquivel 
and outfielder Manny Crespo. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way this team is, we knew we had to get good pitching and  
play good defense, and we made the plays when it counted,'' Morris 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hurricanes' victory ended a four-week tournament almost as  
the NCAA selection committee scripted. With the brackets expanded 
to 64 teams, seven of the eight top-seeded schools advanced to 
Omaha and the top two teams met in the final. 
</P>
<P>
	It also concluded a season in which teams played with modified  
aluminum bats. They were scaled down last year by the NCAA amid 
concerns for player safety and the game's integrity following USC's 
21-14 championship victory. 
</P>
<P>
	At this year's CWS, an NCAA panel continued its momentum on the  
issue by recommending that manufacturers make the metal bats 
perform as much as possible like wooden bats. A decision is 
expected this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Another announcement was warmly received by fans, coaches, and  
players. The NCAA and city officials have a preliminary agreement 
to keep the tournament in Omaha through 2005, with a five-year 
option after that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't imagine the College World Series being anywhere other  
than Omaha,'' Morris said. ``No one in the whole nation could do 
what they do here.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 21:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Governor: Wife 'Feels Horrible' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Gov. Jeb Bush said Monday that his wife  
``feels horrible'' about failing to declare $19,000 worth of 
clothing and jewelry she bought in Paris, but did it so he wouldn't 
find out how much she spent. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a lot of money. But look, that's between her and me,''  
said Bush, adding that his wife was embarrassed. 
</P>
<P>
	Columba Bush paid $4,100 in duty and fines to the Customs  
Service for failing to declare the merchandise upon her arrival in 
Atlanta last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor, who did not accompany his wife on the trip, was  
asked about the fine Monday before he signed a sweeping education 
reform package into law. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can assure you it was a difficult weekend at our house,'' he  
said. ``She knew that what she did was wrong and made a mistake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	International travelers do not have to pay duties on foreign  
purchases that total less than $400. Mrs. Bush declared only $500 
worth of merchandise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 21:51:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  McGwire: No Postseason Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Mark McGwire knows two things for certain: He  
won't match his 70-homer season and the St. Louis Cardinals won't 
make it to the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with 22 homers after connecting in his third straight game  
Monday night, McGwire is a month off his 1998 pace. And with the 
Cardinals 8 1/2 games out of first going into Monday night's game 
against division-leading Houston, he thinks it will be difficult to 
make up the gap. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to play too perfect,'' McGwire said. ``We can't afford  
to make mistakes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire said the Cardinals must do more than acquiring a pitcher  
such as Curt Schilling or Kevin Appier. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not just one player,'' he said. ``If it was two or three  
players coming into the mix and jelling, I think that might make a 
difference, yeah. But one player is not going to make a huge 
difference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire thought the Cardinals would contend, but that was before  
season-ending injuries to starters Matt Morris and Donovan Osborne 
and before rookie J.D. Drew hurt his quadriceps in early May. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to sit here and say, yeah, we're going to roll off  
seven in a row,'' McGwire said. ``Knowing you have to play perfect, 
it's hard to do over a period of time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	St. Louis came off a four-game series against the New York Mets  
in which they lost three. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look at what the Mets did all weekend, they capitalized on our  
mistakes,'' McGwire said. ``We just can't do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Going into the Astros series, McGwire was hitting .254 with 21  
homers and 54 RBIs. He hit his 22nd in the third off Sean Bergman, 
a drive to the second tier of the upper deck measured at 473 feet -- 
topped this season only by the 484-foot drive he hit out of Dodger 
Stadium on May 23. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're not giving him anything to hit,'' batting coach Mike  
Easler said before the game. ``It's right on the corner, right on 
the black, or way the hell in. They're pitching him nasty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Tony La Russa pointed out even though McGwire hasn't  
recreated his 1998 magic, he's only two homers behind Sammy Sosa, 
the NL leader. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's right there with anybody in the league,'' La Russa said.  
``I think he's been pretty hot. I'll take what he's been doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So will McGwire.  
</P>
<P>
	``There won't be another year like last year, I just want to  
have a normal year,'' McGwire said. ``I don't know if I ever want 
to go through what I went through last year. I'd retire if I had to 
do that again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He doesn't want to hear that his projected home run total would  
make him the major leaguer to hit 50 or more in four straight 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pace,'' he scoffed. ``I don't know why people even talk about  
paces anymore. There's no pace for anything.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 21:51:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
