<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 19:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Abbott Labs To Acquire Alza Corp. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORTH CHICAGO, Ill. (AP) -- Abbott Laboratories announced Monday  
it has agreed to acquire the Alza Corp., research-based 
pharmaceutical company located in Palo Alto, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Under terms of the agreement, Alza shareholders would receive  
1.2 shares of Abbott stock for each share of Alza held in a deal 
worth an estimated $7.3 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our acquisition of Alza is an excellent strategic fit and an  
important step that builds our pharmaceutical business and 
accelerates Abbott's long-term growth,'' Abbott chairman and chief 
executive officer Miles D. White said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal was announced after financial markets had closed.  
Shares of Abbott closed down 50 cents to $44.18 3/4 in trading on the 
New York Stock Exchange. Shares of Alza rose 25 cents to $46.25, 
also on the NYSE. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement, expected to close by year's end, requires  
approval by Alza shareholders and regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	Alza is a 30-year-old firm that until recently concentrated on  
developing drug-delivery technologies such as the nicotine patch 
and subsisted on royalties from the companies that sold the actual 
drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Recently, however, Alza has begun developing its own  
pharmaceuticals, specializing in urology and oncology. 
</P>
<P>
	In February, it started selling Ditropan XL, a new one-a-day  
formula to control weak bladders. Ditropan XL is in direct 
competition with Detrol, an incontinence remedy released last 
spring by Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Alza, which employs 2,000 people, reported net earnings of  
$108.3 million in 1998 on sales of $646.9 million. 
</P>
<P>
	North Chicago-based Abbott is a global, diversified health care  
company that develops, manufactures and markets pharmaceutical, 
diagnostic, nutritional and hospital products. Its brands include 
Similac infant formula and Ensure nutrition supplement. 
</P>
<P>
	Abbott employs 56,000 people and sells its products in 130  
nations. It had net earnings of $2.3 billion in 1998 on sales of 
$12.5 billion. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 19:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ramon Martinez Makes Rehab Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOWELL, Mass. (AP) -- As his family watched from a private box,  
Ramon Martinez walked off the field with a smile on his face after 
his first game appearance in nearly a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez, who had rotator cuff surgery last June 30 after a 7-3  
start for Los Angeles, pitched two hitless innings for Class-A 
Lowell against New Jersey in a New York-Penn League game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very happy because now I'm back again,'' said Martinez,  
who struck out three and walked none. ``It was pretty good. I felt 
that I had very good control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although he was expected to throw about 50 pitches, Martinez  
decided to take himself out of the game after 33 pitches -- 
including 21 strikes -- and seven batters. Martinez said he ``didn't 
want to try and force it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't say that I'd be 100 percent, but I was good enough to  
get people out,'' said Martinez, who may joined the Red Sox after 
the All-Star break. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez was 123-77 with a 3.45 ERA in 11 seasons with the  
Dodgers, winning 20 games in 1990 and pitching a no-hitter against 
the Florida Marlins in July 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez said he wasn't nervous until he saw fans holding their  
``K'' signs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pedro throws the strikes,'' said Martinez, referring to the  
Red Sox ace, his 27-year-old brother. 
</P>
<P>
	Pedro and his parents watched Ramon's performance.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's the person I trust, who knows how I pitch,'' Pedro said.  
</P>
<P>
	Ramon signed with the Red Sox in March and received a $1.5  
million signing bonus as part of a two-year contract with a team 
option for 2001, a deal that could bring him about $24 million for 
three years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
