<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 19:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Cub Santo Has Heart Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Former Chicago Cubs third baseman Ron Santo had a  
mild heart attack Monday and was hospitalized in Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	Santo, 59, a color commentator for Cubs' broadcasts on WGN  
radio, was stricken early Monday at a hotel in Denver, where the 
Cubs are to start a three-game series with the Colorado Rockies on 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ron has spoken with members of the Cubs organization, and they  
say he is in good spirits,'' Cubs spokesman Benjamin De La Fuente 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's comfortable, alert and resting,'' hospital spokesman Jeff  
Schwartz said. 
</P>
<P>
	The five-time Gold Glove winner played for the Cubs from 1960-73  
and for the Chicago White Sox in 1974. Santo is in his 10th year as 
a color commentator for the Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are all very concerned,'' said Steve Stone, who announces  
Cubs games for WGN-TV. ``The best news is that it is termed a mild 
heart attack. Many people don't get a warning, and I think he's 
fortunate for that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Santo, a nine-time All-Star, had a .277 career batting average  
with 342 homers and 1,331 RBIs. Santo ranks in the top 10 among 
Cubs in games played, at bats, runs scored, hits, doubles, RBIs and 
extra-base hits. He led the NL in triples in his second season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
