<DOCNO> APW19990621.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 21:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Qwest Lobbies U S West and Frontier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- U S West Inc., the Denver-based Baby Bell at the  
heart of a takeover battle, decided late Monday to proceed with its 
$32.2 billion merger with Global Crossing Ltd., spurning a slightly 
higher rival bid from Qwest Communications International Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest must now decide whether to raise its offer, take the  
proposal directly to U S West shareholders, or simply walk away. 
Joseph P. Nacchio, chairman and chief executive of Qwest, has said 
in recent days that he intends to win, but has no plans to up the 
ante. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Qwest and Global Crossing have ambitious plans to build  
global fiber optic cable networks to provide high-speed Internet 
access and other telecom services. The two companies both made 
offers to U S West and Frontier Corp., a Rochester, N.Y., 
long-distance and Internet company. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Frontier's board also decided to go forward with  
Global Crossing in a $11.5 billion merger. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Nacchio sent letters to the heads of Frontier and U  
S West, saying, ``We are confident that your board will determine 
that our proposal is financially, structurally and strategically 
superior to Global Crossing's offer and in the best interests of 
your shareholders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U S West, however, issued a statement hours later saying, ``At  
this time, the Board continues to believe its strategic merger with 
Global Crossing announced May 17 provides significant value to U S 
West's shareholders and will ensure that the strategic vision of U 
S West will be implemented.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A call to Qwest on Monday night was not immediately returned.  
</P>
<P>
	The vision all of these companies share is how to reshape their  
operations to meet the Internet age. As telephones, computers, 
televisions and radios become one, companies like Qwest and Global 
Crossing are racing to provide the wires that will carry enormous 
amounts of video, audio and data traffic to homes and businesses 
around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest, based in Denver, launched a $55 billion unsolicited offer  
for both U S West and Frontier on June 13. But the appeal of the 
deal faded on the first day of trading as investors pounded Qwest's 
stock price. Qwest's shares have regained some ground, but are 
still off 19 percent from their pre-bid trading. 
</P>
<P>
	At the close of trading Monday, Qwest's offer was worth about  
$44.1 billion, while Global Crossing's was worth about $43.6 
billion. The gap disappears, however, when including the break up 
fee U S West and Frontier would have had to pay to back out of 
their agreements with Global Crossing. 
</P>
<P>
	Global Crossing, a Bermuda-based company that is building an  
undersea cable network, was quick to claim victory Monday night, 
and is now hoping to avoid a drawn-out battle with Qwest. 
</P>
<P>
	``We remain focused on completing both transactions as quickly  
as possible,'' Robert Annunziata, chief executive of Global 
Crossing, said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	U S West's decision is also expected to be well received by the  
company's union workers, who were worried about an acquisition by 
Qwest which would lead to job cuts. The head of the Communications 
Workers of America warned the governors of the 14 states served by 
U S West that the proposed takeover would drain jobs and investment 
from the region and further imperil already-declining service 
quality. 
</P>
<P>
	U S West's stock rose 31 1/4 cents to $58.31 1/4 on the New York Stock  
Exchange, where Frontier's shares dipped 50 cents to $57.81 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest's shares fell $1.43 3/4 to $36.50 on the Nasdaq Stock Market,  
where shares of Global Crossing dropped $2.62 1/2 to $47.12 1/2. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 12:00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S., Europeans Pledge Cooperation  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- President Clinton and European leaders  
pledged greater cooperation today to ensure that minor disputes 
between economic giants don't mushroom into full-blown conflicts. 
Officials said the new conflict resolution would have been helpful 
in defusing two simmering fights involving European bans on bananas 
sold by American companies and U.S. beef raised with growth 
hormones. Clinton and German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder announced 
that the leaders of the countries that will contribute the bulk of 
the money to rebuild Kosovo will meet with Balkan leaders at a 
summit next month in Sarajevo. 

</P>
<P>
	Explosion Rocks Kosovo School  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- An explosion triggered by a land  
mine or a booby trap ripped through a school west of Pristina 
today, killing two Nepalese soldiers serving in the British army 
and two civilians, NATO officials said. The two soldiers were the 
first fatalities among the NATO peacekeepers since they entered 
Kosovo on June 12 to enforce the Kosovo peace agreement. One 
civilian was also injured, NATO said. The troops were clearing 
ammunition from a school in the village of Negrovce when a mine or 
a booby trap exploded, NATO said. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Praises Slovenia  
</P>
<P>
	LJUBLJANA, Slovenia (AP) -- President Clinton today praised  
Slovenia as an example of what a democratic Balkans could become 
and urged Serbia to ``reject the murderous rule'' of President 
Slobodan Milosevic. Clinton is the first president to visit 
Slovenia, the first Yugoslav republic to break with Milosevic. 
Clinton called on ``all the people of every part of Europe'' to 
choose democracy and respect for human rights over the politics of 
ethnic hatred. ``We want Serbia to be a part of the new Europe,'' 
Clinton said. ``But Serbia must reject the murderous rule of Mr. 
Milosevic and choose the path that Slovenia has chosen.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Court Upholds Texas Death Sentence  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today upheld the death  
sentence of a Texas killer who became the first person in the 
nation condemned under a 1994 federal death penalty law. The court 
ruled that Louis Jones' death sentence for a 1995 murder at an Air 
Force base is valid despite the less-than-clear instructions jurors 
received before voting for the death penalty. The court said jurors 
in death penalty cases do not have to be told about the 
consequences of their failing to agree on whether life or death is 
the appropriate sentence. 

</P>
<P>
	Columbine Memorial Ideas Pour In  
</P>
<P>
	LAKEWOOD, Colo. (AP) -- More than 100 ideas for memorials to the  
massacre at Columbine High School have been submitted to a Colorado 
parks commission. The proposals arrived from as near as Littleton 
and as far away as Washington state. Ideas range from a brief note 
to an elaborate floor plan for a memorial resembling a Greek 
temple, with a cafe, theater and library. Two students went on a 
shooting rampage at Columbine in April, killing 12 students and a 
teacher before killing themselves. 

</P>
<P>
	Evacuation Escalates to Near Riot  
</P>
<P>
	MONROE, Va. (AP) -- Students evacuated from their job training  
center after a bomb threat clashed with police because they were 
angry at being cooped up in stuffy buses, authorities said. 
Students spat on officers and threw cigarette lighters and 
balled-up T-shirts at them during the confrontation yesterday at 
the Old Dominion Job Corps Center. No one was injured, police and 
school officials said. About 40 police officers squared off against 
the students. The center was evacuated after authorities received 
two bomb threats telephoned from inside the campus. No bomb was 
found. 

</P>
<P>
	New Ford Excursion SUV Price Set  
</P>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Ford's Excursion, which will be the  
biggest sport utility vehicle on the road when it debuts in 
September, will be priced starting at $34,135 for the base model. 
Suggested retail prices will range as high as $41,915 for a fully 
loaded 2000 Excursion Limited with four-wheel-drive and a V10 
engine, the automaker said. Ford has been criticized by 
environmental groups because the Excursion is so big and its fuel 
mileage is so low -- as little as 10 miles a gallon with the 
optional V10 engine. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 70  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 70.61 to 10,784.95. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,503-1,366. The Nasdaq was up 51.10 to 
2,614.54. 

</P>
<P>
	Sampras Begins Defense of Title  
</P>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- Pete Sampras began defense of his  
Wimbledon title today with a straight-sets victory over Scott 
Draper. Sampras, the top seed, won his 15th straight match at the 
All England Club, where his record since 1993 is 40-1. He has won 
five of the last six Wimbledon crowns. Other winners today included 
Steffi Graf, Monica Seles, Venus Williams and Anna Kournikova. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief By VINCENT CINISOMO  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
