<DOCNO> APW19990621.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 14:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Major Findings on Breast Implants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Major findings by the Institute of Medicine study on silicone  
breast implants: 
</P>
<P>
	--There is no evidence that the silicone used in implants is  
toxic to humans. Women who have breast implants are no more likely 
than the general population to get cancer, lupus, rheumatoid 
arthritis or other diseases. 
</P>
<P>
	--There is no established link between implants and a unique  
disease syndrome or harmful effects on the immune system. 
</P>
<P>
	--There is no evidence that mothers with implants pass silicone  
to infants when breast-feeding. Much higher levels of silicon -- the 
element on which the silicone family of organic compounds is based 
-- have been found in cows' milk and infant formula than in the milk 
of implant recipients. 
</P>
<P>
	--In developed countries, people are commonly exposed to the  
materials used in implants through foods, cosmetics, lubricants for 
machinery, hypodermic syringes, insulators and other products. 
About 10 million Americans have some type of medical implant, such 
as an artificial joint or pacemaker, and many are made at least in 
part from silicone. 

</P>
<P>
	But there are risks of complications within the breast itself:  
</P>
<P>
	--The implants can frequently break and leak. That risk varies  
according to the model of implant. Newer implants or those filled 
with saline instead of silicone gel may be less prone to leaks 
although more study is needed to know. 
</P>
<P>
	--Scar tissue can form around implants, just as the body often  
forms scar tissue around any foreign object. This can be painful 
and disfiguring. 
</P>
<P>
	--Implants may block a clear mammogram, so special imaging  
procedures may be required. However, women with submuscular 
implants seem to have less problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
