<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Life Terms for Gays' Killer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A man who said he killed five gays to stop  
the spread of AIDS was sentenced Monday to life in prison without 
parole. 
</P>
<P>
	Juan Chavez, 35, got five consecutive life sentences for the  
1986 and 1989 killings. He avoided a possible death sentence in 
March pleading guilty during his trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Mike Duarte said Chavez used the promise of sex to  
lure the men to their homes. Then, he forced them to disclose their 
ATM access codes, strangled them and stole their vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Duarte said the sentence was appropriate given inconsistencies  
between Chavez's confession and the details of the killings. He 
also said prosecutors believe Chavez may have killed other gay men. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was at least one other murder that we thought he could  
have done,'' Duarte said. ``We think he's probably the one that did 
it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
