<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 08:10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Upholds Texas Death Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today upheld the death  
sentence of a Texas killer who became the first person in the 
nation condemned under a 1994 federal death penalty law. 
</P>
<P>
	The court, by a 5-4 vote, ruled that Louis Jones' death sentence  
for a 1995 murder at an Air Force base is valid despite the 
less-than-clear instructions jurors received before voting for the 
death penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	Most notably for all other capital-punishment prosecutions, the  
court said jurors in death penalty cases do not have to be told 
about the consequences of their failing to agree on whether life or 
death is the appropriate sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones' lawyers argued that judges should be required to tell  
jurors that such failures will result, as spelled out in the 
Federal Death Penalty Act of 1994, in a defendant being sentenced 
to life in prison without chance of parole. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a capital sentencing proceeding, the government has a  
strong interest in having the jury express the conscience of the 
community on the ultimate question of life or death,'' Justice 
Clarence Thomas wrote for the court. ``A charge to the jury of the 
sort proposed by ... (Jones) might well have the effect of 
undermining this strong governmental interest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones killed Tracie Joy McBride, a 19-year-old Army private at  
Goodfellow Air Force Base in San Angelo, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, who had retired from the Army in 1993 after a 22-year  
career, confessed to abducting McBride from an on-base laundry room 
and taking her to his home in San Angelo. He said he later took her 
to an isolated area about 20 miles from the city and beat her to 
death with a tire iron. 
</P>
<P>
	He led police to McBride's body.  
</P>
<P>
	Convicted, Jones was sentenced by a federal jury to the ultimate  
punishment provided by the 1994 federal law. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the jurors began considering the appropriate punishment,  
the presiding judge initially told them that they must reach a 
unanimous decision on one of three options: death, life 
imprisonment without possibility of release or ``some other lesser 
sentence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But later in the same instructions the judge mentioned only  
death and life in prison when discussing the 1994 law's requirement 
that the jury recommendation be unanimous. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors also were given four somewhat-confusing verdict forms,  
and the judge rejected Jones' request for instructions aimed at 
clarifying the jury's choices. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld Jones' sentence,  
rejecting his argument that the instructions may have spurred some 
jurors who had been leaning toward a life prison sentence to vote 
for the death penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones said jurors might have been worried that a deadlocked vote  
would result in a court-imposed sentence of less than life without 
release, and changed their vote to death so that would not happen. 
</P>
<P>
	In support of that theory, Jones' lawyers submitted affidavits  
from two of the sentencing jurors who confirmed that they and other 
jurors had been confused over the ramifications of a deadlock. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones contended that such confusion led to a violation of his  
8th Amendment protection against cruel and unusual punishment and 
his due-process rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's decision said the 5th Circuit court was right, and Jones  
was wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no reasonable likelihood that the jury applied the  
instruction incorrectly,'' Thomas said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones also had argued that his trial judge erred in letting the  
sentencing jurors consider some aggravating factors that were 
unconstitutionally too vague or too broad. Thomas said they were 
not. Even if they were, he said, ``The error was harmless.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas was joined by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and  
Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. 
Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	Justices Ruth Bader Ginsburg, John Paul Stevens, David H. Souter  
and Stephen G. Breyer dissented, voting to set aside Jones' death 
sentence and order a new sentencing trial. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Jones vs. U.S., 97-9361.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 13:10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Surgeons Transplant Cadaver's Bone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) -- Surgeons used a bone from a cadaver to  
save the cancerous right arm of a 6-year-old boy in a pioneering 
transplant that will enable the limb to grow as he does. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine months after the surgery, little Adam Johnson used the arm  
to toss around a baseball during a news conference Monday at Joe 
DiMaggio Children's Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Back in September, doctors removed most of Adam's humerus, the  
upper arm bone, because of a tumor the size of a grapefruit. 
</P>
<P>
	The doctors then replaced it by taking the humerus from a dead  
child and fusing it with a piece of Adam's own fibula, the thin 
bone that runs from the knee to the ankle. 
</P>
<P>
	Cadaver bones are commonly used in transplant surgery. But  
surgeons said this is the first time a live bone with its blood 
supply intact was combined with a cadaver bone so that the 
transplant would grow along with the patient. 
</P>
<P>
	Adam will have a full-size arm when he grows up, surgeons said.  
If he had received only a cadaver bone, he would forever have the 
arm of a little boy. 
</P>
<P>
	Adam, who lives with his family in Nassau, Bahamas, hopes to  
become a professional basketball player. His father said he is 
overjoyed his son has a chance to lead a normal life. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would like to thank the almighty God and the staff of the  
hospital,'' Anthony Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	In extremely rare circumstances, surgeons have successfully  
transplanted part of a patient's fibula to another part of the 
body, fusing it to whatever healthy tissue is left in the 
cancer-ravaged bone. The procedure was developed in Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the fibula can fracture because of its narrow diameter.  
</P>
<P>
	In Adam's case, the surgeons decided to form a composite: They  
used part of Adam's fibula, with its blood supply and growth 
cartilage intact, and a cadaver bone to add strength and stability. 
The leg bone and cadaver bone are held together with a titanium 
plate. 
</P>
<P>
	The new procedure is ``a spinoff of the techniques used in  
Italy. It's not anything necessarily new and different, but it's 
really a new twist on old ideas. The combination is really the 
key,'' said Dr. Mark Thomas Scarborough, a member of the surgical 
team and chief orthopedic oncologist at Shands Hospital in 
Gainesville. 
</P>
<P>
	Adam is the second sibling in the Johnson family to be diagnosed  
with this rare form of bone cancer, known as osteosarcoma. His 
sister LaToya Johnson, now 11, had her arm amputated in 1996 and 
replaced with an artificial limb. 
</P>
<P>
	Five months before Adam's surgery, the boy underwent  
chemotherapy to shrink the tumor. He lost his hair but never 
complained, doctors said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Adam did extremely well, in no small part due to his  
indomitable spirit and the support of his family,'' Dr. Michael 
Jofe, who led the 11-member surgical team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 00:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stewart: I Thought About My Father  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PINEHURST, N.C. (AP) -- Payne Stewart stood in front of the  
television and cried his eyes out. Ahead lay the crucible of 
another U.S. Open. What made tears flow, though, was something lost 
in his past. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before I came to the course today, NBC ran a piece about  
myself and my father,'' Stewart said. ``I just stood there and 
bawled. I thought a lot about my father. I probably got a lot of 
strength from that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	William Stewart was a furniture salesman who went out the door  
some mornings wearing a canary yellow sport coat on the theory that 
it was better to have a customer remember you for something than 
not at all. 
</P>
<P>
	But he never had to impress more than a half-dozen people at  
once. And when his oldest son stood over a 15-foot par putt on the 
last green Sunday at Pinehurst No. 2, the audience was several 
million times that. 
</P>
<P>
	But this time, it wasn't so much about inviting attention as  
proving he was worthy of it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that I learned a lot from last year,'' he said. ``If  
you can learn from defeat, I think it makes you a much stronger 
player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Failure, it turns out, changed Payne Stewart more than all his  
past success ever could. A year ago, on a shimmering Sunday at the 
Olympic Club near San Francisco, he began the final round four 
strokes clear of the field, then missed a birdie putt from that 
same 15 feet at the last hole to let the championship escape his 
grasp. 
</P>
<P>
	Olympic is nicknamed the Graveyard of Champions because the same  
thing had happened to Ben Hogan in 1955, Arnold Palmer in 1966 and 
Tom Watson in 1987. And in the way that a curse hounds its victims 
through the years, none of the three ever got hold of another major 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	When Stewart walked away from that disappointment, he vowed it  
wouldn't bury him. As a steady drizzle ranked the Carolina 
sandhills, he made good on that promise. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I wanted to do,'' he said, ``was give myself a chance. I  
never gave up. I kept plugging and I kept playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	William Stewart, a two-time Missouri State Amateur champion,  
wouldn't have settled for anything less. When Payne was younger, 
his father had him stand on his shoes and then waltzed around the 
room teaching him to dance. William died in 1985, but he willed his 
son more than good footwork, a golf game and a taste for outlandish 
clothes. Resolve was a quality that topped the list. 
</P>
<P>
	When Stewart won his first major championship, the 1989 PGA, it  
was cast as much the result of fortune than fortitude. Everybody 
remembered Mike Reid slumped over his putter after dropping three 
strokes to par over the last two holes -- not Stewart tearing up 
Kemper Lakes' back nine in 31 and closing with a flurry of birdies. 
</P>
<P>
	Even his first U.S. Open win, at Hazeltine in 1991, had the feel  
of a man in the right place at the right time. Twice, eventual 
loser Scott Simpson let Stewart climb out of a two-stroke ditch 
over the final three holes -- first to earn a shot at the playoff on 
Sunday, then again to win the national championship. 
</P>
<P>
	But there were no questions left by the end of this one.  
</P>
<P>
	Stewart began the day at 1 under par, one stroke ahead of Phil  
Mickelson and two ahead of Tiger Woods. Another stroke back was 
David Duval and Vijay Singh. Stewart knew one or two of them might 
flinch over the course of the afternoon on a layout as tough as 
this one. But he also knew he was going to have beat one or all of 
them himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Ultimately, it was Mickelson, about to become a father himself,  
who pushed Stewart the hardest. 
</P>
<P>
	Twice on the back nine, the left-hander wrested the lead away.  
But he gave it back the final time at the 191-yard, par-3 17th. 
There, Mickelson hit his tee shot to 8 feet and Stewart to about 
half that distance. Mickelson missed his birdie try and Stewart 
made his, setting up the final act. 
</P>
<P>
	On 18, Stewart dumped his drive into the right rough, hacked it  
out with a 9-iron and then hit a lob wedge to 15 feet. Mickelson 
took the more conventional Open route -- hit the fairway, hit the 
green -- to 25 feet. Again, this time much more improbably, he 
missed and Stewart made. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would have made a cool story for my daughter to read  
about,'' Mickelson said, ``but it's still something special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Exactly how special Mickelson may not realize until he's  
actually raised a family of his own. 
</P>
<P>
	But Stewart had no problem remembering the feeling when someone  
asked him whether this victory would supplant his first win out on 
Tour -- the 1982 Quad Cities Open -- as his most cherished memory. 
</P>
<P>
	``That will never change,'' Stewart said, ``because my dad was  
there to see it.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@ap.org. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
