<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbine Memorial Ideas Pour In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKEWOOD, Colo. (AP) -- Stained-glass artist Barb Fowler was  
1,100 miles away in her hometown of Dayton, Ohio, when she learned 
of the massacre at Columbine High School. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fowler expressed her anguish through her art, designing a  
memorial of 13 stained-glass steppingstones engraved with the names 
of the 12 students and teacher killed April 20 by two Columbine 
teen-agers. 
</P>
<P>
	Her design is one of more than 100 ideas for memorials submitted  
to to the Foothills Parks and Recreation District. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Easton, district executive director, is coordinating the  
project, along with school, parks and county officials, who are in 
the initial stages of reviewing designs, picking a site and lining 
up the money. 
</P>
<P>
	Although no budget has been set, three funds established by the  
parks district, school district and Jefferson County have set aside 
$25,000. About 28 offers of in-kind services have been made by 
contractors, landscapers and others. 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever design is chosen, ``the real key is a high level of  
involvement by the high school students, the parents, victims and 
families,'' Easton said. ``We want to be sure it accurately 
reflects their desires.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The site has not been chosen, although public sentiment seems to  
favor Clement Park, where a makeshift memorial sprang up next to 
the high school soon after the shootings in Littleton. 
</P>
<P>
	Easton expects a committee of 20 to 25 people, including local  
officials, victims and other members of the public, to make the 
final decision. 
</P>
<P>
	There is no talk of remembering the gunmen, Dylan Klebold and  
Eric Harris, who ended their rampage of bombs and bullets by 
killing themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposals stacked on Easton's desk arrived from as near as  
Littleton and as far away as Washington state. Many were created by 
artists, but just as many were not. Some people have children at 
Columbine or are alumni; others have no connection other than their 
sorrow. 
</P>
<P>
	The ideas range from a brief note asking that any design include  
the columbine -- the bell-shaped state flower -- to an elaborate 
floor plan for a memorial resembling a Greek temple, with a cafe, 
theater and library. 
</P>
<P>
	One artist sees a pair of 7-foot bronze hands cupping a  
columbine. Another proposes a sobbing angel in a field of 
columbines, her body draped over a tombstone inscribed with the 
victims' names. 
</P>
<P>
	Denver graphic artist Art Zohn, whose daughter will be a senior  
at Columbine this fall, envisions 13 marble benches, a waterfall 
and a stained-glass window looking out on the mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	Like many of the people who submitted proposals, Zohn said he  
``had to do it to get it out of my system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sculptor Randy Rau, a 1979 graduate of Columbine, has suggested  
a large bronze bell that would ring 13 times each year on the 
anniversary of the shootings. Thirteen concrete pillars intertwined 
by a bronze ribbon held up by 13 doves would surround the bell. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Rohrbough, the father of victim 15-year-old Dan Rohrbough,  
said he would like to see the memorial in Clement Park, ``but 
that's not as big a concern to me as that, overall, every family 
has the opportunity to be involved if they would like to and every 
family has the right of refusal if there's something they object to 
or something that's not in it that they want.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fowler said whichever design is chosen, it is important for  
a memorial to be built ``so that nobody forgets. That would be the 
worst tragedy of all.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
