<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Oil Co. Wants Listing on NYSE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- As part of a sweeping overhaul, China's  
biggest oil company wants to list its shares on the New York Stock 
Exchange as early as this year, a company official said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	State-owned China National Petroleum Corp. is under government  
pressure to reassess its assets, slash its work force and increase 
profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Plans to sell stock abroad could delay a widely anticipated  
listing on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange by another state firm, 
China National Offshore Oil Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	``The government wants CNPC to become China's first state oil  
company to get listed,'' the official told Dow Jones Newswires. He 
spoke on customary condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The official said some foreign investors have expressed concern  
about the value of CNPC assets. 
</P>
<P>
	CNPC plans to divide its operations among five holding  
companies, focusing on oil exploration, sales, refining and other 
areas. 
</P>
<P>
	CNPC is expected to retain only 300,000 of its 1.54 million  
employees. The rest are to be reorganized into companies that sell 
CNPC services on a contract basis. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
