<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: National Homeownership Soars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- The lowest mortgage interest and  
unemployment rates since the 1960s sent national homeownership 
rates soaring in 1998, and will probably continue to do so for the 
next decade, according to a study released Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The state of housing in America is very, very good,'' said  
Nicolas Retsinas, director of Harvard University's Joint Center for 
Housing Studies. ``We continue to set records in a variety of 
different areas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report, ``The State of the Nation's Housing: 1999,'' found  
the national homeownership rate reached 66.3 percent last year. 
Additionally, about 1.8 million homes have been built each year 
since 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the growth has occurred outside of cities and in the  
South and the West. 
</P>
<P>
	The report says that increases in immigration and in the number  
of young or newly formed households will fuel a continued increase 
in the housing market for the next 10 years. Meanwhile, as baby 
boomers become senior citizens, they are expected to help sustain 
the home remodeling market as they revamp their homes, the report 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But while the housing boom has created prosperity for some, it  
hasn't done much for others -- especially minorities and the working 
poor. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are Dickensian times, almost,'' Retsinas said. ``You  
know -- it's the best of times and the worst of times. The irony is, 
this prosperity exacerbates some problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although more minorities are buying homes because of low  
interest rates and specially tailored mortgage loan programs, the 
gap between white and nonwhite home ownership widened between 1994 
and 1998, the report found. 
</P>
<P>
	Education is a major factor in that gap. For minorities, the  
likelihood of becoming a homeowner increases dramatically with the 
completion of a bachelor's degree, Retsinas said. 
</P>
<P>
	The brisk housing market has also driven rent prices upward, and  
the report warns that this is causing problems for the working poor 
and those newly off welfare. 
</P>
<P>
	Some property owners are dropping out of federal affordable  
housing subsidy programs in which landlords agree to rent their 
properties to low-income people, who then pay about 30 percent of 
their income as rent. 
</P>
<P>
	``For no state in the nation could a household with one person  
making $7 per hour working 52 weeks a year be able to pay for a 
two-bedroom apartment without exceeding the 30 percent of their 
income standard,'' Retsinas said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Housing policy has been predicated on the premise that if you  
work, you will be able to afford housing,'' he added. ``The whole 
housing policy is brought into question.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 10:30:23 </DATE_TIME>
