<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Ford Excursion SUV Price Set </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Ford Motor Co.'s Excursion, which will be  
the biggest sport utility vehicle on the road when it debuts in 
September, will be priced starting at $34,135 for the base model. 
</P>
<P>
	Suggested retail prices will range as high as $41,915 for a  
fully loaded 2000 Excursion Limited with four-wheel-drive and a V10 
engine, the automaker said Monday. The base price of $34,135 is for 
an XLT version with standard two-wheel drive. The prices include a 
$675 destination charge. 
</P>
<P>
	The list prices are lower than what many analysts expected.  
</P>
<P>
	George Peterson, an analyst with AutoPacific Inc., said the  
prices were ``pretty reasonable'' and will make the Excursion 
competitive with the most popular versions of its General Motors 
Corp. rivals, the Chevrolet and GMC Suburbans. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices for the '99 Chevrolet Suburban range from $26,640 for the  
base 1500 model with two-wheel drive to $39,640 for a 2500 model 
with four-wheel-drive, V8 engine and the LT option package. 
</P>
<P>
	GM is preparing for the new competition by redesigning the  
Suburbans for the 2000 model year; the GMC version will be renamed 
the Yukon XL. Prices for the new models have not yet been 
announced. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford has been criticized by environmental groups because the  
Excursion is so big and its fuel mileage is so low -- as little as 
10 miles a gallon with the optional V10 engine. Ford notes all 
three engines available on the Excursion will meet California's 
low-emission standard for light trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Excursion will come with a choice of either a 5.4-liter V8,  
a 6.8-liter V10 or a 7.3-liter diesel V8. The truck, to be built on 
Ford's Super Duty pickup truck chassis in Louisville, Ky., seats up 
to nine people in three rows. It measures nearly 19 feet long and 
just under 7 feet tall. 
</P>
<P>
	The Excursion will be available Sept. 30, but its dealers  
already are taking orders, Ford said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
