<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NAACP Receives Million-Dollar Gift </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- After an injury ended his athletic career,  
Reginald Lewis went on to Wall Street and, as owner of TLC Beatrice 
International Holdings Inc., became the first black entrepreneur to 
control a billion-dollar company. 
</P>
<P>
	The foundation he established gave the NAACP on Monday $1  
million to fund training for budding black business leaders who 
might someday become like him. 
</P>
<P>
	The money will allow the National Association for the  
Advancement of Colored People to continue funding a summer business 
program, called the NAACP Reginald F. Lewis Youth Entrepreneurial 
Institute, for the next five years. 
</P>
<P>
	NAACP President Kweisi Mfume joined Loida Nicolas Lewis, who  
became chairman of TLC Beatrice after her husband's death, at a 
news conference to announce the grant. The announcement was made at 
Morgan State University, a historically black college. 
</P>
<P>
	This summer, 120 high school students will take the four-week  
NAACP business course, which includes classes on finance, team 
building and etiquette. The program, first started in 1994, will be 
offered this year in Baltimore; Atlanta; Austin, Tex.; Charlotte, 
N.C.; Columbia, S.C.; Fort Lauderdale, Fla; Gary, Ind.; and 
Richmond, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Mfume said the program is needed to bolster the number of black  
entrepreneurs in America, something that is ``simply not going to 
happen in a vacuum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a talent pool we're creating here,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Lewis formed TLC Beatrice in a $985 million buyout funded partly  
by junk bond mastermind Michael Milken in 1987. Forbes magazine 
listed Lewis among the 400 richest Americans in 1992, when his net 
worth was an estimated $400 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1987, when TLC Beatrice reported revenue of $1.8 billion, it  
became the first black-owned company to record more than $1 billion 
in annual sales. The company then began its reign at the top of 
Black Enterprise magazine's annual list of the country's 100 
biggest black-owned companies. 
</P>
<P>
	But the largely European food conglomerate will be liquidated in  
the coming months, Mrs. Lewis said in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis died of brain cancer in 1993 at age 50. His widow had not  
originally intended to liquidate the company but management 
convinced her it was the best course for investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Lewis called the decision to team up with the NAACP to  
endow the institute a ``no-brainer.'' She said her husband, who 
attended Dunbar High School in Baltimore and eventually went on to 
graduate from Harvard Law School, ``believed in education.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 17:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Replay Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Policies on the use of videotaped replays by on-field  
officials: 
</P>
<P>
                             *Baseball    	
</P>
<P>
	Not allowed.  
</P>
<P>
                               *NFL    	
</P>
<P>
	Used from 1986-91. Reinstated last March after several  
game-turning calls that replays showed were incorrect. Use will be 
for sideline, goal line, end zone and end-line plays; passing 
plays; and other detectable infractions, such as a runner ruled 
down not by defensive contact, and the number of players on the 
field. Outside the final two minutes of each half, each team will 
be permitted two challenges and will be charged a timeout for each 
challenge. During the final two minutes and during any overtime, 
only replay assistant in press box may initiate review. All reviews 
limited to 90 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
                               *NBA    	
</P>
<P>
	Not allowed.  
</P>
<P>
                               *NHL    	
</P>
<P>
	The video goal judge may review puck crossing the goal line,  
puck in the net prior to the goal frame being dislodged, puck in 
the net prior to, or after expiration of time at the end of the 
period, puck directed into the net by a hand or foot, puck 
deflected into the net off an official, puck struck with a high 
stick, above the height of the crossbar, by an attacking player 
prior to entering the goal, and to establish the correct time on 
the official game clock. 
</P>
<P>
                           *NCAA Football    	
</P>
<P>
	Not allowed.  
</P>
<P>
                          *NCAA Basketball    	
</P>
<P>
	Replays allowed for preventing or rectifying a scorer's or  
timer's mistake, for malfunctioning game or shot clocks, and to 
determine if a fight occurred and those individuals who 
participated in a fight. Starting next season, also will be allowed 
to assess whether a correctable error needs to be rectified for 
failure to award a merited free throw, awarding an unmerited free 
throw, permitting a wrong player to attempt a free throw, 
attempting a free throw at the wrong basket and erroneously 
counting or canceling a score. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Soccer    	
</P>
<P>
	Not allowed.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 12:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
