<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Treasury Bills' Interest Rates Fall / T-Bills  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Interest rates on short-term Treasury  
securities declined in Monday's auction. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury Department sold $7.51 billion in three-month bills  
at a discount rate of 4.610 percent, down from 4.620 percent last 
week. An additional $7.51 billion was sold in six-month bills at a 
rate of 4.850 percent, down from 4.855 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-month rate was the lowest since June 7, when the bills  
sold for 4.510 percent. The six-month rate was also the lowest 
since June 7, when the rate was 4.760. 
</P>
<P>
	The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors  
-- 4.741 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling 
for $9,883.50 and 5.055 percent for a six-month bill selling for 
$9,754.80. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the  
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index 
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, fell to 5.03 
percent last week from 5.12 percent the previous week. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
