<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Expected To Pass UN Dues Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Legislation to pay nearly $1 billion of the  
country's debt to the United Nations advanced in the Senate on 
Monday, eased along by a compromise with the Clinton administration 
on reducing future U.S. payments to the world organization. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, expected to win Senate approval on Tuesday, calls for  
a reduction in the U.S. share of the regular U.N. budget from the 
present 25 percent to 20 percent; and a drop in the share of 
peacekeeping operations from 31 percent to 25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Rod Grams, R-Minn., chairman of the Senate Foreign  
Relations subcommittee on international operations, called the 
United Nations ``a bloated bureaucracy'' and said that, without 
housekeeping reforms, ``the U.N. will collapse under its own 
weight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, part of legislation authorizing a variety of State  
Department programs for fiscal 2000, would allow payments of $819 
million in U.S. debts to the United Nations over three years and 
forgive $107 million that the United Nations owes the United 
States; or a total of $916 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also calls for spending $3 billion over the next five  
years to beef up security at U.S. embassies around the world -- the 
same amount requested by the administration in the aftermath of 
last year's attacks on U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania. 
</P>
<P>
	By U.N. calculations, the United States is $1.69 billion in  
arrears, nearly 60 percent of the total debt owed to the 185-nation 
organization. U.N. officials have complained that makes it hard for 
the United Nations to pay its own bills. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States disputes some of the arrears, but concedes  
owing at least $1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Unless a substantial portion is repaid this year, the United  
States will lose its vote in the General Assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation is a result of a compromise among Secretary of  
State Madeleine Albright, committee Chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C., 
and senior Democratic member, Joseph Biden of Delaware. 
</P>
<P>
	Veteran diplomat Richard Holbrooke, President Clinton's nominee  
to be U.N. ambassador, has promised to try to persuade other U.N. 
nations to go along with the reduction in the U.S. share if 
confirmed, Helms told the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Helms' committee, in fact, was to hold a hearing with Holbrooke  
on Tuesday dealing with the U.N. payments issue. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss of a vote in the General Assembly would be an  
embarrassment, but it would not affect Washington's veto power in 
the Security Council, the most powerful decision-making body at the 
United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress authorized legislation last year that would have paid  
off much of the arrears. 
</P>
<P>
	But President Clinton vetoed the bill because it contained  
unrelated abortion restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate debated the bill Monday, but put off a final vote  
until Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 16:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Finals TV Ratings Falling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Other than the night O.J. Simpson's freeway  
chase distracted viewers from basketball, last week's Game 2 got 
the lowest prime-time rating for the NBA Finals since 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's coverage of Friday night's game between the San Antonio  
Spurs and the New York Knicks posted a 9.6 rating and a 19 share. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the lowest rating since June 17, 1994, when the  
Knicks-Rockets Game 5 drew a 8.0 -- the same night the nation was 
riveted by the police chase of Simpson in Southern California 
before his arrest in the killings of his wife and her friend. 
</P>
<P>
	Other than that, no game rated lower since the opener of the  
1985 Finals between the Boston Celtics and the Los Angeles Lakers, 
which wasn't in prime time and got an 8.9. 
</P>
<P>
	The Finals hadn't received this low a rating in prime time since  
1978, when Game 2 between Seattle and Washington got a 9.2 rating 
and a 16 share. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's Game 2 fell 42 percent from last season's  
record-setting second game of the Chicago Bulls-Utah Jazz contest, 
which posted a 16.6/31. 
</P>
<P>
	Through the first two games, NBC is averaging a 10.6/20, down 39  
percent from the two games average of 17.3 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Numerous reasons have contributed to the tumbling ratings,  
including the departure of Michael Jordan, sloppy play, 
noncompetitive games and the fact that San Antonio is the smallest 
market in the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	Six of the eight highest-rated finals involved Jordan's Bulls.  
</P>
<P>
	The 1994 final (12.4 rating), the last season to be played  
entirely without Jordan, was NBC's lowest-rated in its eight years 
of showing the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	The rating is the percentage of TV households in the United  
States tuned to a program, and each point represents 994,000 homes. 
The share is the percentage tuned to a program among televisions in 
use on at the time. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 14:43:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AOL Invests in Satellite TV Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- America Online Inc. will invest $1.5 billion  
in DirecTV creator Hughes Electronics Corp. in an agreement that 
gives AOL a new high-speed option and deepens ties between the 
world's largest Internet provider and the leading U.S. satellite TV 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal announced Monday seeks to combine AOL's Internet  
services with Hughes' digital television system. Company executives 
said the deal would help increase DirecTV's subscriber base while 
boosting the market for AOL's planned interactive TV and high-speed 
Internet services. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement also advances AOL's campaign to acquire the  
broadband platforms necessary to offer customers faster, more 
diverse services. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with the satellite deal, AOL is not limiting its alliances,  
said Steve Case, AOL's chairman and chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think this precludes in any way, shape or form our  
ability to work with telephone companies or cable companies or 
anyone who can provide any piece of the puzzle of this broadband 
tapestry,'' Case said in a conference call with reporters. ``We 
want to provide the best set of choices to the widest audience 
possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts consider access to cable -- with its wide reach into  
American households -- crucial to AOL's campaign to convert to 
high-speed Internet delivery. Cable companies have resisted calls 
for them to allow open access to AOL and other Internet service 
providers. 
</P>
<P>
	``They can't not have a cable deal. Not having that would be a  
difficulty for them,'' said Sajai Krishnan, an analyst with Booz 
Allen &AMP; Hamilton. ``Cable is going to be a strong play in the 
consumer market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	AOL has also made several deals with phone companies such as  
Bell Atlantic Corp. and SBC Communications Inc. to provide 
high-speed services over phone lines. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, AOL and Hughes agreed to jointly develop a set-top  
receiver that would allow DirecTV customers to subscribe to AOL TV, 
an interactive service that would combine Internet access with 
Hughes' entertainment programs. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, television viewers would be able to communicate  
with other AOL users while watching a program 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new deal, the two companies also plan to develop  
content and additional interactive services to be offered through 
DirecTV and AOL TV. For example, viewers would be able to execute 
an online stock purchase while watching a financial program, or buy 
a video cassette of a movie they are watching. 
</P>
<P>
	AOL still needs to cut a deal with cable operators to provide  
its customers with true broadband service, said Josh Bernoff, an 
analyst with Cambridge, Mass.-based Forrester Research. For now, 
satellite technology provides high-speed connection in one 
direction only -- from the satellite to the user's computer. 
Information uploaded from the computer moves via a telephone line, 
usually at a much lower speed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Satellite has a pretty significant problem in that you can't  
deliver high speed data in both directions from a satellite,'' said 
Bernoff. ``To call this broadband is perhaps not completely 
appropriate. I would call this simulated broadband.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes is developing a new satellite system, known as Spaceway,  
that could solve the problem by offering two-way broadband 
connections. Hughes plans to have the system in operation by 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, AOL will invest $1.5 billion in an equity  
security of General Motors Co., parent of El Segundo, Calif.-based 
Hughes. The equity carries a 6 1/4 percent coupon rate that is 
automatically convertible into GM Class H common stock in three 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Dulles, Va.-based AOL is the world's largest Internet provider  
with more than 16 million subscribers to AOL and its CompuServe 
subsidiary. Hughes currently has more than 7 million DirectTV 
subscribers 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of AOL rose $3.68 3/4 to $115.18 1/4 in trading on the New York  
Stock Exchange. Hughes, which trades as the GM Class H stock, rose 
$3.18 3/4 to $56.62 1/2, also on the NYSE. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
