<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 09:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Patrons Turn Out for Gun Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Under a din of banjos and the hum of  
fluorescent lights, the chatter of bartering from a 
larger-than-expected crowd echoed through the region's biggest gun 
show. 
</P>
<P>
	While Congress debates whether to impose more restrictions on  
who can buy a gun -- and when -- rebels and average Joes turned out 
for the weekend show. 
</P>
<P>
	``They want to make a stand,'' said Mike Jones, 36, who was  
carrying his 3-month-old daughter, Debbie. ``They think their 
rights are going to be taken away soon, so they're stocking up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers said the crowd was more than twice what they  
expected, but acknowledged that their promotion might have less to 
do with the size of the crowd than the national debate over gun 
control. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one thing to come to the show and look around and buy.  
It's another when people are coming to oppose something,'' said 
promoter Rex Kehrli, who charges $5 a head for admission to the 20 
shows he arranges throughout the South. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd rather be thought of as a good promoter than someone who  
takes advantage of situations,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun control has become a hot topic amid the increasing death  
toll from school shootings nationwide: among them, three killed in 
West Paducah, Ky., in 1997; five in Jonesboro, Ark., last year; and 
13, plus the two shooters, at Littleton, Colo., in April. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the House rejected a gun control bill that would have  
weakened existing restrictions on gun show sales while requiring 
safety devices to be sold with all handguns. 
</P>
<P>
	The 280-147 vote left President Clinton searching for a way to  
impose new gun laws, especially on shows like these. 
</P>
<P>
	In a line outside the expo center, four men bartered over a  
Ruger handgun. The spacious main hallway opened on both sides to a 
metropolis of armaments that ranged from high-powered hunting 
rifles to semiautomatic weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 600 licensed dealers and unlicensed traders shared the  
same space -- all selling their wares for what some buyers consider 
rock-bottom prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Dealers are required to do a background check of all buyers, but  
unlicensed dealers do not. Instead, they cannot sell long guns to 
those 18 years and younger, sell handguns to people younger than 
21, or sell handguns to out-of-state residents. Patrons also cannot 
be drunk when they purchase a weapon. 
</P>
<P>
	``To most people, we're the bad guys,'' said Harold Pauley, a  
collector who uses money from the shows to upgrade his collection. 
He prominently displayed three Browning BPS 200 shotguns at $395 
each. Handguns also were available for less than $200. 
</P>
<P>
	In an adjacent room that housed more than 100 other dealers,  
banjo music played while everything from M-1 rifles -- $505 with a 
bayonet -- to magazine clips were for sale. The most expensive 
weapons included three M-11 9 mm submachine guns priced around 
$1,000. A suppressor could be added for $600. 
</P>
<P>
	On the cheaper side was a Model EA 3 .380-caliber handgun for  
$105. And high-damage hollow-point bullets could be found for as 
little as 10 cents each. 
</P>
<P>
	Many people come for the cheap prices. Others see it as a way to  
discuss what they say is the slow loss of the right to bear arms. 
In one corner of the exposition center, dealer Fred Bush said his 
fellow dealers are frightened to talk about the weapons they own. 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't trust the government anymore,'' said Bush, 66.  
``This might be the only place left that they have to talk about 
these things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the dingiest merchants -- in dirty jeans and cutoff  
undershirts and a few days removed from their last shave -- answered 
questions with cursing and an occasional obscene gesture. 
</P>
<P>
	Near the middle of the exposition center, four tables were  
loaded with cases of Nazi medals, pistols and flags. These World 
War II relics are popular among gun show regulars, Kehrli said. At 
another table, a Japanese officer's revolver was available for $95. 
</P>
<P>
	One dealer displayed a bumper sticker that said: ``Racial Purity  
is America's Security.'' Kehrli had a worker take it down. 
</P>
<P>
	The bad reputation gun show patrons get sometimes is deserved,  
said Ben Thomas, who chose not to bring his two sons because of the 
people who hang out at shows. ``It's frustrating when a few people 
come here and think they have to act like they're nuts. 
</P>
<P>
	``You see these Confederate flags all over the place, trying to  
prove this bad-boy image,'' he said. ``Most of us aren't like 
that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
