<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Remote Desert City Takes the Heat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE HAVASU CITY, Ariz. (AP) -- There really is no reason for  
this city to exist. 
</P>
<P>
	First, foremost and above all, there's the heat. Mind-boggling,  
thermometer-busting, brain-baking, you-must-be-kidding heat. 
Summertime temperatures around 120 degrees. Overnight lows in the 
80s. A relentless, endless dry sauna from May into October. 
</P>
<P>
	``You learn that you sweat in places that you didn't think  
possible,'' says Bonnie Barsness, a tourism promoter who moved here 
from North Dakota. 
</P>
<P>
	Secondly, the location is inconvenient. Lake Havasu City lies in  
the middle of nowhere along the Arizona-California line, along the 
desolate line where the Mohave and Sonoran deserts meet. 
</P>
<P>
	Phoenix lies 205 miles away; Tucson and Los Angeles, 315 miles;  
Las Vegas, 150. And there's no interstate highway or railroad 
through the city, just a commuter airline offering a handful of 
daily flights to Phoenix and Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	There simply is no good reason for Lake Havasu City to exist.  
Yet it's thriving 36 years after it was established by Robert P. 
McCulloch, founder of chain saw maker McCulloch Corp., who came 
here looking for a motor testing site. 
</P>
<P>
	The main reason is Lake Havasu itself.  
</P>
<P>
	The name, pronounced HAVE - a - soo, is a Havasupai Indian word  
meaning blue-green water. And it's those deep, clean and inviting 
waters that attract visitors and breathe life into a young city 
that wasn't incorporated until 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	Just as Bugsy Siegel saw gold in the desert that eventually  
became the Las Vegas strip, McCulloch looked out upon wasteland and 
envisioned a retirement community filled with stucco houses rising 
above the river toward the Mohave Mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no town when McCulloch landed here in 1963, only an  
abandoned military landing strip and a lake artificially formed by 
the damming of the Colorado River 25 years earlier. But McCulloch 
brought in 100 mobile homes to house his workers, and soon a few 
businesses and houses were built. 
</P>
<P>
	McCulloch hired C.V. Wood, the architect who designed  
Disneyland, to plan a city spread over 26 square miles. Largely as 
a tourism gimmick, he bought London Bridge, which was scheduled for 
demolition, and shipped it in from England block by block. The 
bridge spans a man-made lake channel leading to a small island 
featuring a shopping mall, restaurants and campgrounds. It marked 
its 25th anniversary in Arizona in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The McCulloch Corp. for years was the city's leading employer,  
but the company recently closed its plants and filed for 
bankruptcy, putting 450 out of work. 
</P>
<P>
	It could have been catastrophic. But tourism and the sheer  
livability of Lake Havasu City proved to be its salvation. The area 
attracts 1 million visitors a year, and they contribute $100 
million to the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The city has dozens of small businesses, including eight boat  
manufacturers, said Bob Tippitt, president of the Lake Havasu City 
Partnership for Economic Development. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of small businesses are run by people who wanted to get  
away from city life and live in a small town,'' he said. ``They 
sell all over the United States. They use UPS or FedEx or whatever 
to ship their products. The hot weather doesn't bother them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The overall result: Unemployment is below 2 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	Lake Havasu offers 450 miles of shoreline and open water for  
swimming, angling and sailing. It is the site of international Jet 
Ski championships, power boat competitions and national bass 
fishing contests. 
</P>
<P>
	Long weekends fill the city's 1,600 motel rooms and 3,000  
campsites. Sleek cigar boats with growling inboard motors prowl the 
lake and head for Copper Canyon, a renowned party spot. Bikini tops 
can be optional, particularly during spring break, when college 
students by the thousands rent houseboats and motel rooms, camp out 
and raid store shelves for beer. 
</P>
<P>
	Josh Hernandez, a Phoenix property appraiser, regularly hauls  
his Waverunner to Lake Havasu. He likes to make a four-hour run on 
the water upriver to Laughlin, Nev., to gamble and dine in the 
casinos. 
</P>
<P>
	``We come out here for the openness of the water,'' says  
Hernandez, who races the personal watercraft competitively in 
California. ``The weather in spring and fall is good. Summer is 
just unbearable, like sticking your head in an oven, but the water 
stays cool.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lake Havasu City's population has nearly tripled since 1975, to  
43,000. That figure doubles each winter with an invasion of 
retirees. Many are choosing to live here year round, drawn by the 
friendly, small-town atmosphere and ample services. 
</P>
<P>
	Housing prices are affordable, too. A three-bedroom house with  
swimming pool costs about $90,000. Custom-built homes in the $1 
million range offer unobstructed lake views. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Mayor Jim Spezzano can't imagine a better place to live.  
He moved here from Michigan in 1980, after retiring as a Ford Motor 
Co. executive. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're sitting back in the Midwest or Northwest and hear  
them talking on TV about the nation's high being Lake Havasu 
City,'' he said, ``the only thing you can think of is 'I'm glad I 
don't live there.' 
</P>
<P>
	``Now I watch the weather and see blizzards in the Midwest and  
say 'God, I'm glad I don't live there.''' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 18:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. GOP Primary Plan Gets Setback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- A bid to eliminate the state's  
``winner-take-all'' Republican presidential primary received a 
setback Monday that its sponsor predicted would prove fatal to the 
proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Assembly elections committee postponed a hearing on  
the proposal for two days, dimming the prospect it would be signed 
into law by July 1, as required by national GOP rules, said its 
principal proponent, Sen. Ray Haynes. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Haynes' proposal, the state's winner-take-all Republican  
primary next March 7 would be replaced with one that would allow 
multiple candidates to split the state's delegates by congressional 
district. 
</P>
<P>
	``I cannot see how I can get this thing to the governor by June  
30 with the hearing on Thursday,'' Haynes said by telephone 
immediately after Democratic Assemblyman Edward Vincent delayed the 
hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	The postponement is ``fatal for 2000,'' he said, adding that he  
will pursue it for the 2004 presidential cycle. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Republican Party adopted the change Saturday, and  
Haynes sought to hustle the proposal through the 
Democratic-controlled Legislature before July 1. He acknowledged in 
recent days its prospects were slim. 
</P>
<P>
	Vincent did not immediately respond to a call seeking comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Scrapping ``winner-take-all'' would have energized rank-and-file  
Republicans to get involved in the 2000 campaigns, the state party 
contended. 
</P>
<P>
	Haynes and other proponents said it would make the candidates  
strengthen their California campaigns earlier, producing stronger 
party support for the eventual presidential nominee. 
</P>
<P>
	But the party's move was also seen as a signal to the  
front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, that some want their votes 
to go to more conservative candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the proposed change, candidates would fight for the 156  
California party delegates, district by district. A victory in one 
district would be worth three delegates, with up to two dozen 
at-large delegates probably going to candidates based on their 
proportion of the statewide vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Under current rules, the Republican candidate who draws the  
largest number of votes statewide takes all party delegates to the 
national convention, where the nominee is chosen. California has 
the largest state delegation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 13:50:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Commerce Sec. Wary of Steel Quotas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. farmers and businesses that rely heavily  
on exports to other countries might suffer if the domestic steel 
industry obtains quotas on foreign steel, Commerce Secretary 
William Daley said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The quotas could hurt U.S. steel companies as well if an  
international trade war erupts, cutting off U.S. exports from 
foreign markets, Daley said. He said a fifth of the steel used 
domestically goes into products later sent abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	Daley issued the warning on the eve of a key vote in the Senate  
on a quota measure. The House overwhelmingly passed the bill in 
March, 289-141, despite the threat of a presidential veto. Both 
sides believe Tuesday's Senate vote will be close. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are the world's leading exporter, and steel is a  
significant part of those exports,'' Daley said. ``And it is not 
just the steel industry that stands to suffer. Other industries 
that depend greatly on exports and could pay a steep price include 
pharmaceuticals, high-tech, and above all, agriculture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steelworkers are pushing for quotas as a way to combat  
low-priced foreign shipments that the industry blames for 
bankruptcies at three U.S. companies and for thousands of layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign shipments reached record highs last year in the wake of  
the Asian economic crisis, which reduced demand for steel abroad 
and forced foreign producers to turn to the United States. The U.S. 
industry contends that some of the foreign pricing practices are 
designed to illegally undercut U.S. producers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Quota legislation is the only option right now for making  
certain that foreign countries end their illegal trade practices 
and our steelworkers get back on the job,'' said Sen. Jay 
Rockefeller, D-W.Va., chief sponsor of the quota bill. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference, Daley said steel quotas would violate  
international trade agreements and make it difficult for the 
Clinton administration to persuade other countries to open their 
markets to U.S. products. 
</P>
<P>
	But Daley acknowledged that some senators may ``feel somewhat in  
a box,'' wishing to show their sympathy for workers while 
recognizing that quotas are ``not the right way to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, Daley has been on the phone with several senators  
since last week to persuade them to reject the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, the United Steelworkers of America arranged to send a  
thousand workers to Washington for a rally before the vote. About 
100 steelworkers on motorcycles stopped in Pittsburgh on Monday on 
their way to Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The quota bill would impose monthly quotas on steel shipments  
equal to the average levels in the three years before July 1997. 
The measure also would set up an import notification system to 
better track shipments into the country. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 17:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tigers Manager Picks Tri-Captains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Manager Larry Parrish doesn't deny that his  
latest attempt to shake up the foundering Detroit Tigers might be 
something of a reach. 
</P>
<P>
	Parrish, seeking more vocal leadership in the clubhouse, picked  
pitcher Doug Brocail, catcher Brad Ausmus and third baseman Dean 
Palmer as team captains. The move came in the wake of a 2-hour 
meeting between Parrish, his coaches and the three players 
following a 6-5 loss Sunday to the Oakland Athletics. 
</P>
<P>
	That loss dropped the Tigers (29-40) to a season-low 11 games  
under .500. They had lost five of six heading into Monday night's 
game against the A's. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could say this is a form of grasping,'' Parrish said  
Monday. ``We're not winning, and anything we can do to win, we'll 
try.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parrish wants the tri-captains to exert peer pressure on other  
players, particularly before and after games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted somebody vocal, and that's Brocail,'' Parrish said.  
``We want somebody as a go-between between the pitchers and 
players, and that's Ausmus. Then we wanted a senior player, 
somebody the others respected, and that's Palmer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer, who came to Detroit as a free agent after signing a $36  
million, five-year contract last, is not regarded as a vocal 
player. But Palmer, whose 19 home runs and 44 RBIs easily lead the 
Tigers, says he's willing to try anything. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a role that's something I definitely accept,'' Palmer  
said. ``It makes you feel good that the management has that 
confidence in you. I know I'm going to be here a few years and I 
want to help this team any way I can. I want to be involved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Tigers were a consensus pick to finish second behind  
Cleveland in the AL Central but entered Monday in third place, 17 1/2 
games behind the division-leading Indians. They've also shown no 
signs of becoming a contender, which was a main goal heading into 
next season's move to their new home at Comerica Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Parrish thinks the team has accepted losing too easily.  
</P>
<P>
	``Anything that gets the club talking baseball will make us a  
better team,'' Parrish said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 08:28:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  India Claims Vital Peak in Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BATALIK, India (AP) -- Pounded by Pakistani artillery, Indian  
soldiers dug into newly won positions on a mountain ridge today and 
prepared for an assault on the last pockets of Islamic guerrillas 
in the mountainous Kashmir region. 
</P>
<P>
	As India claimed new military victories, the leaders of the  
world's most industrialized nations and Russia urged a halt to the 
fighting in Kashmir. The divided territory has been the trigger for 
two wars since India and Pakistan won independence from Britain in 
1947. 
</P>
<P>
	The statement by the Group of Eight urged the withdrawal of the  
guerrillas, who had seized mountain posts on the Indian-controlled 
side of the cease-fire line dividing Kashmir. 
</P>
<P>
	India saw the statement from the G-8 summit in Cologne, Germany,  
as a clear-cut demand for Pakistan to withdraw the forces it 
allegedly supports. But the statement did not name Pakistan 
directly -- so Islamabad today called it a vindication of its stance 
in the hostilities. 
</P>
<P>
	India accuses Pakistan of backing the guerrillas in an attempt  
to change the 1972 cease-fire line. Pakistan denies it is behind 
the guerrillas, who it says are Muslim fighters seeking Kashmiri 
independence. 
</P>
<P>
	After a week of fighting, Indian troops scaled an almost  
vertical rock face and took Peak 5140, the highest point on a 
Himalayan ridge dominating a strategic highway, the army announced 
Sunday. Heavy fighting continued for Tiger Hill, the last of three 
towering peaks on the ridge. 
</P>
<P>
	A military spokesman said the next objective was to seize three  
ridge lines and keep the pressure on the militants' supply lines. 
</P>
<P>
	In the nearby Mushko valley, Indian troops have pushed back the  
guerrillas to within two miles of the line of control, said an 
officer, Col. Avtar Singh. The intruders had infiltrated up to four 
miles across the cease-fire line. 
</P>
<P>
	In New Delhi, military spokesman Col. Bikaram Singh said 100  
Pakistani soldiers were dislodged from Peak 5140. Three Indian 
soldiers were killed and nine others wounded in the operation to 
wipe out bunkers on the 16,900-foot peak, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The successful operation left ``one or two pockets'' of rebels  
still overlooking the highway, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Singh said the forces on the peak were being hit by heavy  
artillery and mortar shelling from the Pakistani side of the line 
of control, The Indian Express newspaper reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian forces -- using artillery, air strikes and troops -- have  
been battling the guerrillas since early May, when hundreds of them 
were discovered on undefended ridges along the cease-fire line. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 08:28:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  India Claims Vital Peak in Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BATALIK, India (AP) -- Pounded by Pakistani artillery, Indian  
soldiers dug into newly won positions on a mountain ridge today and 
prepared for an assault on the last pockets of Islamic guerrillas 
in the mountainous Kashmir region. 
</P>
<P>
	As India claimed new military victories, the leaders of the  
world's most industrialized nations and Russia urged a halt to the 
fighting in Kashmir. The divided territory has been the trigger for 
two wars since India and Pakistan won independence from Britain in 
1947. 
</P>
<P>
	The statement by the Group of Eight urged the withdrawal of the  
guerrillas, who had seized mountain posts on the Indian-controlled 
side of the cease-fire line dividing Kashmir. 
</P>
<P>
	India saw the statement from the G-8 summit in Cologne, Germany,  
as a clear-cut demand for Pakistan to withdraw the forces it 
allegedly supports. But the statement did not name Pakistan 
directly -- so Islamabad today called it a vindication of its stance 
in the hostilities. 
</P>
<P>
	India accuses Pakistan of backing the guerrillas in an attempt  
to change the 1972 cease-fire line. Pakistan denies it is behind 
the guerrillas, who it says are Muslim fighters seeking Kashmiri 
independence. 
</P>
<P>
	After a week of fighting, Indian troops scaled an almost  
vertical rock face and took Peak 5140, the highest point on a 
Himalayan ridge dominating a strategic highway, the army announced 
Sunday. Heavy fighting continued for Tiger Hill, the last of three 
towering peaks on the ridge. 
</P>
<P>
	A military spokesman said the next objective was to seize three  
ridge lines and keep the pressure on the militants' supply lines. 
</P>
<P>
	In the nearby Mushko valley, Indian troops have pushed back the  
guerrillas to within two miles of the line of control, said an 
officer, Col. Avtar Singh. The intruders had infiltrated up to four 
miles across the cease-fire line. 
</P>
<P>
	In New Delhi, military spokesman Col. Bikaram Singh said 100  
Pakistani soldiers were dislodged from Peak 5140. Three Indian 
soldiers were killed and nine others wounded in the operation to 
wipe out bunkers on the 16,900-foot peak, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The successful operation left ``one or two pockets'' of rebels  
still overlooking the highway, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Singh said the forces on the peak were being hit by heavy  
artillery and mortar shelling from the Pakistani side of the line 
of control, The Indian Express newspaper reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian forces -- using artillery, air strikes and troops -- have  
been battling the guerrillas since early May, when hundreds of them 
were discovered on undefended ridges along the cease-fire line. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 19:30:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hollins Released by Toronto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Designated hitter Dave Hollins was released  
Monday by the Toronto Blue Jays, who had designated him for 
assignment last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollins appeared in 27 games for Toronto this season and was  
hitting .222 with two homers and six RBIs. He was acquired from 
Anaheim on March 30 for infielder Tomas Perez. 
</P>
<P>
	He was on the disabled list from April 18-May 30 with a  
fractured left hand. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 08:27:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Praises Slovenia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LJUBLJANA, Slovenia (AP) -- Painting a bright portrait of what  
the Balkans could become, President Clinton today celebrated the 
economic success of Slovenia -- the first Yugoslav republic to 
reject President Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want the trip to spark the imagination of others, both  
within the Balkans and beyond it, about the kind of future and kind 
of societies we can build in all those countries if we work at 
it,'' Clinton said before departing Bonn for the first visit to 
Slovenia by a U.S. president. 
</P>
<P>
	A relentless rain didn't dampen the enthusiasm of the welcoming  
committee at Ljubljana, where a military band and honor guard were 
on hand as Air Force One touched down and host officials unrolled 
10 lengths of red carpet. 
</P>
<P>
	On the country road into town, lonely clusters of people stood  
in the downpour to wave at the presidential motorcade passing a 
corn field away. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and Slovenian President Milan Kucan shared not one -- but  
two -- grinning handshakes for news cameras beneath a crystal 
chandelier in the Presidential Palace before meeting privately. 
</P>
<P>
	In a public address in the capital city of Ljubljana and  
official meetings at the parliament building, Clinton wanted to 
congratulate Slovenia for breaking with Milosevic's government and 
establishing stability in a region riven by ethnic tensions. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no future in Europe for Mr. Milosevic and his policy  
of manipulating normal human differences for inhuman ends,'' 
Clinton declared Sunday in Germany, where today he attended a 
summit with European Union leaders before departing for Ljubljana. 
</P>
<P>
	Kucan said Clinton's visit ``marks the recognition of our young  
country, that in its eight years of existence has managed to change 
its profile, become politically stable, economically successful and 
socially secure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A planned dinner with the democratically elected Kucan at Brdo  
Castle, former residence of the late dictator Josip Broz Tito, 
would dramatize that change. 
</P>
<P>
	Slovenia is a country of 2 million people, smaller than New  
Jersey and squeezed between Austria and Croatia. It won 
independence in 1991 and now wants to join NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	Slovenia was the most developed of the Yugoslav republics when  
it won independence in 1991 and has capitalized on that advantage 
since. With key industries including pharmaceuticals and 
electronics, Slovenia has a per capita income of $11,000, similar 
to Portugal and Greece. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Slovenia is a member of NATO's Partnership for Peace,  
which prepares candidate countries to join the alliance, and an 
associate member of the European Union, many Slovenes were 
disappointed to miss the first wave of NATO expansion, which was 
limited this year to Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials clearly held out hope for Slovenia's NATO  
aspirations. ``We fully plan to have a second wave of 
enlargement,'' said White House spokesman Mike Hammer. ``Slovenia 
is definitely on that track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Slovenes also are frustrated by how little the world knows about  
their country, and hope Clinton's visit can change that. 
</P>
<P>
	``Americans, and the whole world, will know now where Slovenia  
is,'' said Marko Macur, a 22-year-old student waiting earlier this 
week for a ticket to see Clinton in Congress Square. 
</P>
<P>
	Slovenia made fevered preparations for Clinton, including $1.5  
million for new wiring, plumbing and curtains at the castle outside 
Ljubljana, where Clinton will have a dinner for about 120 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also is meeting Milo Djukanovic, the president of  
Montenegro, the smaller of the two remaining Yugoslav republics. 
</P>
<P>
	The pro-Western Djukanovic has opposed Milosevic's policies, and  
Sandy Berger, the president's national security adviser, said 
Clinton's meeting with the Montenegrin leader will ``demonstrate 
our support for the steadfastness that he has shown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Twelve days after the last NATO bombing raid on Yugoslavia,  
Clinton was also venturing near the front lines of the battle -- won 
by the United States and its allies -- to stop Milosevic's ethnic 
cleansing of Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Before heading back to Washington on Tuesday, the president was  
visiting the Stenkovich I refugee camp, temporary home to thousands 
of Kosovar Albanians who fled their homes in terror of Milosevic's 
Serb troops. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 08:27:39 </DATE_TIME>
