<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 16:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stars Celebrate Cup Texas-style </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- With a tug of his pant legs, Dallas Stars owner  
Tom Hicks showed off the perfect symbol of a Texas team winning the 
Stanley Cup: black boots with the shiny silver trophy emblazoned on 
each shin. 
</P>
<P>
	Forward Dave Reid added to image by wearing a black cowboy hat  
throughout a downtown parade on Monday and a Reunion Arena pep 
rally in honor of the NHL champions. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 75,000 people lined the streets for the parade. They  
saw the players ride by on four floats, the final one carrying the 
Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``For them to see a team other than the Cowboys win something is  
fun,'' forward Guy Carbonneau said. 
</P>
<P>
	Truth is, Dallas fans have loved the Stars ever since they moved  
from Minnesota in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've been here with us for six years,'' captain Derian  
Hatcher, one of three remaining Minnesota North Stars, told the 
Reunion Arena crowd. ``Now we have (the Cup) here and it looks good 
here. Hopefully, we can build a nice little house for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars won the first title in their 32-year history and the  
first for a team in the Sun Belt early Sunday with a 2-1 
triple-overtime victory over the Buffalo Sabres in Game 6. Although 
a controversy is brewing over the Cup-winning goal scored by Brett 
Hull while his left foot was in the goalie's crease, there were no 
references to it Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	After a 45-minute parade from City Hall to Reunion Arena, the  
players were introduced, each walking through a giant star-shaped 
metal structure. 
</P>
<P>
	The last player out was Hatcher, who ushered in the Cup beneath  
a shower of fireworks and a burning, revolving star. He placed the 
trophy on a 5-foot pedestal in the center of the stage. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as we've got one of these, why not go for two?'' coach  
Ken Hitchcock said. ``Aw, hell, let's go for three!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Each player got a turn hoisting the Cup and most of them kissed  
the trophy, Mike Modano doing so several times. 
</P>
<P>
	Goaltender Ed Belfour, who was serenaded by cheers of ``Ed-die!  
Ed-die!'' throughout the hourlong show, savored the Cup the 
longest. He circled the stage while Hicks, team president Jim Lites 
and general manager Bob Gainey led a standing ovation. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans goaded Belfour into speaking and, with a voice hoarse from  
36 hours of celebrating, he thanked the crowd for their support. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been an unbelievable year,'' said Belfour, who  
inspired one fan to write ``In Eddie We Trust'' on the back of a 
car. ``This is a great moment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The clinching game in Buffalo ended around 12:30 a.m. Sunday --  
after many fans were asleep and too late to make some editions of 
the local newspapers. Only about 200 fans made it to the airport to 
greet the plane at 6:45 a.m. Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Also taking part in the celebration were the Reunion Arena  
Zamboni and the heavy metal band Pantera. 
</P>
<P>
	Band members are fans of the team and friends with several  
players. The group pounded out a song featuring only the words 
``Dallas! Stars!'' 
</P>
<P>
	A full house awaited the team at Reunion Arena, where two 1999  
Stanley Cup champion banners hung from the rafters for the first 
time. It was the 50th straight time the team packed the 17,001-seat 
facility, although with seats on the ice the total attendance was 
closer to 20,000. 
</P>
<P>
	B.J. Thomas, the Grammy-winning singer best known for  
``Raindrops Keep Falling On My Head,'' opened the pep rally by 
singing the national anthem. The Stars were 6-0 this season when he 
sang, including a victory in Game 5 of the finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Ron Kirk read a letter from Gov. George W. Bush, then  
Lites and Hicks addressed the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have never, ever for a minute regretted coming here,'' said  
Lites, who joined the organization following the move from 
Minneapolis. ``It's been a great, great, great experience.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 02:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philly Expects Convention Windfall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Next summer's Republican National Convention  
could turn Philadelphia into the City of Brotherly Lucre. 
</P>
<P>
	The elephant invasion will guarantee a large infusion of cash as  
convention delegates, guests, corporate executives and the media 
spend money on hotel rooms, restaurants, cab rides, parties and the 
like. 
</P>
<P>
	City officials conservatively estimate that the festivities will  
generate $125 million in direct economic activity. And they're 
figuring on another $200 million in indirect benefits -- for 
example, money spent at the supermarket by convention workers. 
</P>
<P>
	And those are only the tangible effects.  
</P>
<P>
	The convention, which will be held the week of July 29 to Aug.  
4, 2000, presents a prime opportunity for the city to market itself 
-- to show to an audience of millions that it is a nice place to 
visit or do business in. 
</P>
<P>
	In San Diego, the economic impact of the 1996 Republican  
convention was pegged at $162 million, but the promotional value, 
according to one official, was priceless. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we had to pay for the favorable mentions of San Diego, we  
couldn't even begin to dream about it,'' said Salvatore Giametta, a 
spokesman for the San Diego Convention and Visitors Bureau. 
``Certainly the costs would be in the hundreds of millions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Philadelphia can expect similar treatment, as reporters from all  
over write about the Liberty Bell, Independence Hall, the art 
museum, the Franklin Institute and other landmarks. 
</P>
<P>
	But Irving J. Rein, a Northwestern University professor who  
specializes in the marketing of places, said the media spotlight 
can be a ``disaster'' if the city doesn't adequately prepare. 
</P>
<P>
	Roads -- especially the road from the airport -- should be  
pothole-free. Trains should run on time. Residents have to be nice 
to convention-goers, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has to work well. If it doesn't, you've not only wasted  
your opportunity, you've ruined your image,'' said Rein, author of 
the book ``Marketing Places.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David Cohen, co-chairman of Philadelphia 2000, the organizing  
committee, said efforts to teach residents to be courteous to 
visitors have been going on for years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have become pretty sophisticated,'' he said. ``We do all  
sorts of survey work, and one of the great strengths of the city is 
how friendly we are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some San Diego hotels were a bit nervous that the stampeding  
elephants would scare away tourists, said Giametta, the visitor's 
bureau spokesman. The convention was held in mid-August, the height 
of the city's tourist season. 
</P>
<P>
	But Giametta said that whatever dip there was in non-convention  
visitors was more than made up by delegates and corporate bigwigs 
who ``spend a lot more freely than the average vacationer would.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You have some business displaced, but you now have it replaced  
by a convention where folks are paying very nice room rates, 
certainly higher than what you have with folks on a leisure 
vacation,'' Giametta said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Chicago, host of the 1996 Democratic convention, one study  
pegged the direct economic impact at $123 million, with another 
$237 million in secondary benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	The study, conducted jointly by the Federal Reserve Bank of  
Chicago and the University of Illinois, also said about 4,200 jobs 
were created, and those workers received about $133 million in 
salaries and wages. Philadelphia officials based their own 
projections on the findings. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Muldoon, president of the Philadelphia Convention and  
Visitors' Bureau, said the timing of the Philadelphia convention 
couldn't be better. 
</P>
<P>
	The facilities are nearly new, it's the start of a new  
millennium and there is already a perception that Philadelphia is a 
city on the way up, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the weather has to cooperate.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think the stars are lined up right, and if the sun stays out  
for 10 days and the humidity isn't too high, people will say, 'What 
a great place,' Muldoon said. ``If it rains for 10 days, we'll have 
to work a little bit harder.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 20:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Camby Starts For Knicks Vs. Spurs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Marcus Camby solution didn't quite work for  
coach Jeff Van Gundy on Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Under pressure to find some offense for the struggling New York  
Knicks in the NBA Finals, Van Gundy turned to Camby, starting him 
for the first time all season in Game 3 against San Antonio. 
</P>
<P>
	But Camby got in fast foul trouble, committing two personals in  
the first six minutes of the game. Then, at the start of the second 
half, he picked up two more quick fouls and headed to the bench 
with no points in the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Camby fouled out of Game 2 and finished Game 1 with five  
personals. 
</P>
<P>
	Camby replaced Chris Dudley in the Knicks lineup. Dudley, who  
had been starting at center in place of injured Patrick Ewing, 
failed to score a field goal in the first two losses at San 
Antonio. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the shoot-around this morning, Jeff came up to me and said,  
`I might start you,' '' Camby said in the locker room before the 
game Monday night. ``I said, `Fine. Whatever it takes to get the 
win.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Camby provided a huge spark as a reserve in the Knicks' victory  
over Indiana in the Eastern Conference finals, but has struggled 
with foul trouble as New York fell behind San Antonio 2-0 in the 
finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``To start the game, I can bring my energy and enthusiasm and  
hopefully get us going and get the crowd going,'' Camby said. 
``Then I can go out and get a blow and come out in the second 
quarter and do the same thing in the second half.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It did not work out that way, though.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 03:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> racing </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coca-Cola Remains Off Paris Shelves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Canned Coca-Cola remained off the shelves for a  
sixth day today, with officials still unable to explain why the 
beverage sickened dozens of people. 
</P>
<P>
	The company counterattacked with a full-page ad saying the  
quality of its soft drinks is ``irreproachable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola France provided consumers with a free telephone number  
to check whether their cans of Coke were among the lots implicated 
in the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	The ad appearing in major French dailies said that analyses by  
Coca-Cola and by independent teams show that ``the drink is not in 
question.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Its quality is irreproachable,'' the add said.  
</P>
<P>
	Some 50 million cans of Coca-Cola, Coca-Light, Sprite and Fanta  
were withdrawn last Tuesday from the French market, following a 
similar move in Belgium, after dozens of people who drank the 
product complained of stomach aches or nausea. 
</P>
<P>
	Coke said last week that the problem Cokes came from plants in  
Dunkirk, France, and Antwerp, Belgium. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coca-Cola plant in Dunkirk announced Wednesday night that it  
was halting manufacture of products destined for markets in France 
and Belgium. Only beverages for the Netherlands were being 
produced. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dunkirk plant can produce 1,600 cans a minute on four  
production lines. 
</P>
<P>
	Coke said substandard gas used to carbonate drinks at the  
Antwerp plant caused a bad taste, and that a fungicide used on 
crates in Dunkirk was absorbed by the underside of cans and gave 
off an ``offensive odor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, tests have so far failed to detect a problem with the  
drink itself or explain why consumers were sickened, French 
officials have said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 06:30:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Energy Workers Get Lie Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The head of a presidential panel on nuclear  
weapons security, backed by congressional Republicans, says 
security problems within the Department of Energy can't be fixed 
without creating a new semi-independent agency to oversee nuclear 
arms programs. 
</P>
<P>
	But Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, said he is successfully  
confronting the security lapses revealed in investigations of 
suspected Chinese spying at weapons laboratories, and that no new 
agency is needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are ready to have a beefed-up security entity within the  
Department of Energy that is stronger,'' Richardson said on ``Fox 
News Sunday.'' ``What I don't want is a new agency that is 
autonomous that does not report to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But former Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H., who chaired a panel of  
the president's Foreign Intelligence Advisory Board that issued a 
highly critical report of the DOE's counterintelligence efforts 
last week, said the department has failed to carry out two key 
security measures that President Clinton ordered 16 months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	It has yet to fully implement polygraph tests for scientists at  
the labs and tighter security checks for foreign visitors, Rudman 
said on NBC's ``Meet the Press.'' ``The attitude of people within 
that department, in that bureaucracy, is astounding,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Post reported today that the federal government  
has begun administering polygraphs on the first of 5,000 nuclear 
weapons scientists and other sensitive employees at DOE. 
</P>
<P>
	It could take four years to complete an initial round of  
examinations on the federal workers and private contractors working 
with highly classified nuclear secrets, said Edward J. Curran, head 
of Energy's counterintelligence office. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, only that office's staff has been given the tests, he  
said. Richardson told the Post some employees and civil liberties 
groups are likely to protest the polygraphs and ``I fully expect 
lawsuits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president of the University of California, Richard C.  
Atkinson, has ordered a review of security at the three nuclear 
laboratories managed by the university to make sure national 
security is not being compromised. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI has investigated allegations that a former employee of  
Los Alamos National Laboratory near Santa Fe, N.M., was a spy for 
China. The university also manages Lawrence Livermore National 
Laboratory and Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory. 
</P>
<P>
	Atkinson has asked his Council on National Laboratories to  
examine whether newly tightened measures are being implemented and 
whether additional measures are needed. He also wants to compare 
the university's security to the protocol used by Lockheed Martin, 
which manages the Sandia National Laboratories. 
</P>
<P>
	Rudman, meanwhile, is expected to receive a good reception  
Tuesday when he testifies to Congress on his panel's recommendation 
that the weapons program become semi-autonomous, reporting only to 
the energy secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	``I agree with the Rudman report,'' said Sen. Richard Shelby,  
R-Ala., chairman of the Senate Intelligence Committee. ``We've said 
all along that the labs are not safe today. They're not safe 
tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson, he said, is trying to ``seal the leaks at the labs.  
He's trying to bring accountability to the labs. But I believe it's 
going to take statutory change to do it. I don't believe ultimately 
he can do it just by himself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shelby said Republican Sens. Frank Murkowski of Alaska, Jon Kyl  
of Arizona and Pete Domenici of New Mexico would try to attach 
language on such a separation of powers to an intelligence spending 
bill coming before the Senate soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson said there were still problems to resolve but ``we  
have had dramatic improvements.'' He said he ordered a two-day 
stand-down at all the nuclear labs to test security measures, and 
that he plans to dismiss some people responsible for security 
lapses in about three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson last week also named retired Air Force Gen. Eugene  
Habiger, the former commander of all U.S. strategic nuclear forces, 
to head security operations at DOE. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 10:20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Economic Growth Plan Stalled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- The construction workers putting the  
finishing touches on Shanghai's second international airport are 
soldiers in an economic war against recession. 
</P>
<P>
	For months, China has poured money into building airports, roads  
and other large construction projects. It hopes putting extra cash 
in Chinese pockets will fuel a domestic consumer boom, creating new 
sources of growth for its slowing, export-oriented economy. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, that isn't happening. Retail sales, corporate profits  
and housing prices are stuck at lackluster levels as government 
debt grows. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really a challenge for them to jump-start private  
consumption before the money runs out,'' said Dong Tao, chief 
regional economist for Credit Suisse First Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	China's use of capitalist-style deficit spending to perk up an  
economy still dominated by communist state industry highlights the 
unique struggle facing the only big East Asian economy to dodge the 
1997 financial crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	China is trying to overhaul decrepit state industries, an effort  
that is costing millions of jobs. But it also wants to boost 
consumer spending to prop up slumping prices that threaten to ruin 
Chinese companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall growth looks healthy enough. The government target for  
1999 is 7 percent, down from 7.8 percent last year. The State 
Information Research Center says growth could surpass that in the 
first half of the year, hitting an annualized rate of 8.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But such figures can be deceptive. Compared with other major  
economies, inefficient China wastes state money on dubious building 
projects and production of goods that nobody buys. 
</P>
<P>
	``In my opinion, the economy is not growing at all, or at most  
by no more than 3 percent,'' said Marc Faber, a financial 
consultant in Hong Kong. ``It would be better to get government out 
of spending and focus on private investment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An avalanche of ominous statistics shows the fragility of many  
sections of the economy. Exports fell sharply in the first four 
months of 1999, ranging from a 3.7 percent drop for steel to a 23.7 
fall for textiles. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, the government says public-works spending  
should soar by 21 percent in the first half of the year. Projects 
include Pudong International Airport in Shanghai, due to open in 
October at a cost of $1.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite infusions of cash, growth in retail sales has held  
steady for six months at about 6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Housing sales are growing but supply so outstrips demand that  
average prices hit a record low in April of $22 per square foot, 
the official Xinhua News Agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Slack consumer demand has accelerated a steady decline in prices  
that began last year. In April, they were 3.5 percent below the 
same month in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	That has fed fears of a disastrous downward spiral that could  
bankrupt producers. In some industries, the government has imposed 
minimum prices to keep companies from ruining each other with price 
wars. 
</P>
<P>
	Pepping up the private economy is crucial for Chinese leaders  
who need to create new jobs as state companies fire workers in a 
frantic drive to become profitable. Companies that can't do so by 
2002 are threatened with being shut down. 
</P>
<P>
	Word of new layoffs comes almost weekly. The China National  
Petroleum Co. plans to cut 75,000 jobs this year. The government of 
Fujian province in the southeast says it will lay off 240,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The government made a bid in early June for more foreign money  
to pay for reform. Regulators announced that Chinese private and 
joint-venture companies will be allowed for the first time to sell 
stock priced in U.S. dollars to foreign investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Previously, only state companies could issue shares meant for  
foreigners, but many had pulled out of the market because of low 
profits. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, China can afford to keep spending to stimulate growth,  
economists say. Its debt is low by world standards, and Chinese 
households save on average 40 percent of their incomes, creating a 
huge pool of money available for loans. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest danger to an economy still heavily dependent on  
exports lies in the threat of recession in the United States, its 
key market, Faber said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I see the prospect of a recession or at least a slowdown in  
the next 18 months,'' he said. ``The impact would be very heavy on 
China.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
