<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US, Cuba Hold Counter-Narcotics Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Amid protests from Cuban-American lawmakers,  
four U.S. officials met Monday in Havana with Cuban officials to 
discuss ways of improving counter-narcotics cooperation, a State 
Department official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meetings between U.S. and Cuban officials on issues other than  
migration are rare but not unprecedented. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a change in U.S. policy,'' said Michael  
Ranneberger, who heads the State Department's office of Cuban 
affairs. He said the meeting was taking place within guidelines for 
law enforcement efforts on counter-narcotics. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. team consisted of two State Department and two Coast  
Guard officials, none of whom holds a high rank. They were to spend 
only one day in Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's meeting was aimed at elevating communications on  
counter-narcotics issues from an existing telex link to a phone 
link and other means, an official said, adding that the U.S. team 
had no plans to offer assistance to Cuba, to share intelligence or 
to discuss joint operations. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. counter-drug specialists have become increasingly concerned  
about South American traffickers' use of Cuban waters and air space 
to transport drugs to the United States, and the law enforcement 
community had requested that a team be sent, said the official, who 
spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, R-Fla., objected strongly to the  
decision, saying it was ridiculous for the administration to give 
Cuban President Fidel Castro credibility on the drug issue. She 
said Castro is notorious for helping drug traffickers. Similar 
objections were voiced by Rep. Lincoln Diaz-Balart who, like 
Ros-Lehtinen, is a Cuban-born South Florida Republican. 
</P>
<P>
	In a telephone interview, Diaz-Balart said a grand jury in U.S.  
District Court in South Florida prepared an indictment against the 
Castro government concerning tons of cocaine that entered the 
United States. The Clinton administration shelved the indictment in 
1993 despite ``massive'' evidence of Cuban involvement with drug 
kingpins, the congressman said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Barry McCaffrey, the White House drug control policy chief,  
said last month that Cuba has shown a willingness to help the 
United States fight international drug trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a small portion of the drugs entering the United States  
come through Cuba, McCaffrey said, adding that the island's 
location and a growing tourist market could make it an opportune 
target for drug traffickers. 
</P>
<P>
	McCaffrey also credited Cuba with acting on intelligence the  
United States provides to Cuban authorities. Cuba lacks the 
resources to counter large drug-trafficking organizations, so drugs 
are routinely flown over Cuba or dumped in Cuban waters without 
effective resistance by local authorities, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 07:46:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stars Shine in Stanley Cup Clincher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- A long game ended too quickly for the  
Buffalo Sabres and the Dallas Stars walked off with the Stanley Cup 
under a cloud of controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	All of a sudden, the troublesome man-in-the crease rule had  
become a major issue in the NHL. The question now over the summer: 
Should it be changed? 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody will remember this as the Stanley Cup that was never  
won in '99,'' said Buffalo's Joe Juneau after the Stars won a 2-1 
triple-overtime thriller on Brett Hull's questionable goal Saturday 
night in Game 6 of the Stanley Cup finals. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Sabres wanted to put an asterisk next to the Stars' name  
in the Stanley Cup record book, you couldn't blame them. They felt 
they had been cheated out of a chance to win the Cup because of a 
bad call by NHL officials. The television replay showed Hull had a 
skate in the crease when he scored the game winner with 5:09 left 
in the third overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	Usually the man-in-the-crease rule is a strict interpretation  
with no gray matter: It disallows a goal if an offensive player has 
any part of his body in the goalie crease. Not this time. 
</P>
<P>
	The official response from the league: This one counted because  
the player (Hull) had full control of the puck. 
</P>
<P>
	``The debate here seems to be, did he or did he not have  
possession and control,'' said Bryan Lewis, the NHL's director of 
officiating. ``Our words from upstairs and our view was that, yes, 
he did. He played the puck from his foot to his stick, shot and 
scored.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rule has been the bane of skaters for some time. Many a goal  
has been disallowed even by infractions that are purely incidental 
to the play, such as a teammate's skate in the crease away from the 
action. 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, the NHL's general managers met just a few days before  
at the finals to discuss the controversial ruling. Commissioner 
Gary Bettman said the league was worried about the game losing some 
of its spontaneity when play is stopped for a video review of a 
goal. He added the ruling was under review for a possible change. 
</P>
<P>
	He didn't have to worry about spontaneity Saturday night.  
</P>
<P>
	As soon as Hull scored, the Stars, wearing Stanley Cup  
championship baseball caps, leaped over the bench onto the ice and 
started hugging each other. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's got to be the worst nightmare right there,'' Sabres coach  
Lindy Ruff said. ``They knew that they ran the risk of an overtime 
goal meaning a series. Stanley Cup pandemonium sets in and they 
can't go back to review it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis said the goal was, in fact, reviewed quite thoroughly.  
</P>
<P>
	``Our immediate reaction is to take a look at it, back up tapes  
from a variety of angles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said officials looked at the play ``probably six, eight  
(times).'' 
</P>
<P>
	The controversy at the end overshadowed a superb contest between  
two evenly matched teams. Every game in the finals was pretty much 
a carbon copy of the next -- low scoring and high tension. There was 
plenty of hard hitting and good goaltending from Dallas' Ed Belfour 
and Buffalo's Dominik Hasek. 
</P>
<P>
	Belfour, shaking off the tag that he couldn't win big games,  
made 53 saves in the clinching Game 6. Hasek pretty much lived up 
to his title as ``World's Greatest Goalie'' with 48. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were such a great team,'' Hull said of the Sabres, who  
came into the finals as underdogs to the top-ranked Stars after 
finishing as the seventh seed in the Eastern Conference. ``They are 
so well coached and worked so hard. I tip my hat to them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Playing underdog all the way through, the Sabres knocked off  
Ottawa, Boston and Toronto to make it into the finals. 
</P>
<P>
	In a remarkably close series, the Sabres and the Western  
champion Stars were either tied or just one goal apart for all but 
5:05 of the six-plus games, including two that went into overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars were pretty much bucking odds themselves. The last  
team to win both the Presidents' Trophy with the league's best 
record and the Stanley Cup was the New York Rangers in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoping to redeem themselves after winning the trophy and then  
losing in the playoffs last year, the Stars beat Edmonton, St. 
Louis and Colorado before Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had it in our minds that we were going to do this in  
September,'' said Stars forward Brian Skrudland, ``and we were 
going to win this in any way we could.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In some ways, the Sabres felt the Stars had gone too far. Sabres  
captain Michael Peca charged that the Stars were a dirty team. 
</P>
<P>
	They were certainly an injured team. That didn't keep their top  
players off the ice for long, however. Hull was forced to miss one 
game with an injured groin, but came back to play with a vengeance. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday night, he was at his best while also playing with an  
injured knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Jere Lehtinen scored a first-period goal for Dallas and Stu  
Barnes in the second for Buffalo. That was all the scoring until 
Hull found himself in front of the net late in the third overtime, 
won the battle over several other players for the puck and punched 
the game winner over a prone Hasek. 
</P>
<P>
	The game winner went to Hull and the Conn Smythe Trophy as the  
playoffs' MVP to Joe Nieuwendyk, who had six game-winning playoff 
goals. 
</P>
<P>
	``It feels incredible,'' said Nieuwendyk, who won the first Cup  
in Calgary in 1989 before winning the first for Dallas. ``It is 
just one battle after another and it makes it all the worthwhile in 
the end. It has been a great ride for us.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
