<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Working on Cloning Panda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Scientists have taken a step toward cloning a  
giant panda by growing an embryo that contains a dead animal's 
genes -- a development China hailed as a possible breakthrough in 
efforts to save the endangered species. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists from the government-funded Chinese Academy of  
Sciences grew the embryo by introducing cells from a dead female 
panda into the egg cells of a Japanese white rabbit, the state-run 
Xinhua News Agency said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The embryo was nurtured over 10 months and scientists are now  
trying to implant it in a host animal's uterus. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it works, they will possibly have created the world's first  
cloned panda,'' Xinhua said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although scientists have cloned other large animals, notably the  
sheep Dolly, the cloning has required repeated efforts -- with many 
failed pregnancies. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, China announced plans to try to clone a giant panda  
within three to five years. 
</P>
<P>
	But Chen Dayuan, who leads the government-backed panda cloning  
project, said scientists now believe they will need less time, 
Xinhua reported. 
</P>
<P>
	It hailed the development as a potentially ``critical and  
exciting breakthrough'' for saving the species, which is unique to 
China. 
</P>
<P>
	Only about 1,000 pandas live in the wild, with another 100 in  
zoos. Experts have warned that the animal could become extinct in a 
couple of dozen years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 00:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stewart Gets Advice on Putting  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PINEHURST, N.C. (AP) -- We learned one thing about U.S. Open  
champion Payne Stewart -- he's not too vain to take some putting 
advice from his wife. 
</P>
<P>
	After watching the third round of the Open on TV, Tracey Stewart  
was waiting for her husband Saturday night to offer some tips on 
his poor putting. 
</P>
<P>
	She told him to hold his head still and see the club hit the  
ball. Stewart, who admitted he had been lifting his head, listened. 
He then proceeded to the practice putting green and stroked some 
putts with his eyes shut. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a routine that would ultimately land him his second  
national golfing title of the '90s. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've heard on television before that one of the detriments of  
Payne Stewart's golf game is he's not a good putter. Well, maybe I 
squelched those rumors,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	After taking 31 putts to get around Pinehurst No. 2 with a  
2-over 72 in the third round, Stewart needed only 24 putts Sunday 
to put away playing partner Phil Mickelson. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart's par-saving 15-footer on the 18th hole won him the  
Open, and proceeded to set off a fist-waving, caddie-hugging, teary 
celebration on one of Donald Ross' turtleback greens. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know how high I jumped, but it felt like I was sky  
high,'' Stewart said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart is third on the PGA Tour in putting average and sixth in  
putts per round. He finished in a tie for eighth in putting at the 
Open and only Dudley Hart's 23 putts were fewer than Stewart's 24 
on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart did more than nail his clutch putt on No. 18. A  
25-footer on 16 to save par kept Stewart in the tournament. A 
3-footer on the next hole put him ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	``The putts Payne made on 16 and 18 showed what a great champion  
he is,'' Mickelson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart ended up with 12 one-putts Sunday -- the mark of a steady  
champion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said to myself, `You've always wanted a putt to win the U.S.  
Open,''' Stewart said. ``I can't describe the feeling in my body 
when I looked up and the ball was going in the hole. It was 
unbelievable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was quite a difference from last year at the Olympic Club,  
where Stewart missed putts coming down the stretch, including one 
on the 18th that would have given him a tie with Lee Janzen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had something to prove to myself this time,'' Stewart said.  
``I had to get in position and I had to deal with it once I got 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mickelson, who one-putted four of the first six holes for par,  
missed down the stretch when it counted the most. 
</P>
<P>
	He gave himself a chance, but when his 40-footer for birdie on  
15 hit the cup, seemed ready to drop, and then spun out, his luck 
seemingly ran out. 
</P>
<P>
	Mickelson missed a 7-footer for par on 16 that dropped him into  
a tie with Stewart, then missed a 7-footer for birdie on the next 
hole. Still, even when his 25-footer slid past the cup on 18 he was 
heading toward a Monday playoff if Stewart didn't make his. 
</P>
<P>
	``He waits for players to falter,'' Mickelson said when  
addressing Stewart's strategy and success in recent Opens. ``This 
time, he made something happen in that he ended up playing under 
par the last few holes.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
