<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Arrest warrants have been issued against  
two top leaders of the leftist rebel group which has kidnapped 
nearly 200 people, prosecutors said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief federal prosecutor, Alfonso Gomez called Antonio Garcia  
and Pablo Beltran of the National Liberation Army, or ELN, the 
``intellectual authors'' of the April 12 hijacking of an Avianca 
domestic flight with 41 passengers and crew aboard. 
</P>
<P>
	Gomez said Garcia and the ELN's highest-ranking commander,  
Nicolas Rodriguez, are also under investigation for ordering the 
rebels' May 30 raid on a Catholic Mass. About 140 worshippers were 
trucked into the mountains in the assault in the western city of 
Cali. 
</P>
<P>
	The ELN still holds 54 hostages from the two operations, as well  
as nine people seized June 6 by guerrillas who ambushed a fishing 
expedition. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Chile's president reshuffled five Cabinet  
posts Monday, re-assigning the foreign minister who failed to 
broker the release of ex-dictator Gen. Augusto Pinochet from arrest 
in Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	President Eduardo Frei, who is poised to announce measures to  
boost Chile's economy, kept his economic team intact. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Miguel Insulza, the foreign minister who failed to win  
Pinochet's release from arrest in Britain, was made chief of staff. 
He was replaced by Juan Gabriel Valdes, an economist. 
</P>
<P>
	Edmundo Perez, currently the ambassador to Argentina, was named  
defense minister, a job he had held three years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Perez's job may prove crucial, as the military has given  
indications for the first time that it may cooperate in efforts to 
find the remains of more than 1,000 dissidents who remain 
unaccounted for after being arrested under Pinochet's 1973-90 
dictatorship. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinochet has been under police custody in Britain since last  
October, fighting extradition to Spain where a judge wants to try 
him for human rights violations during his regime. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The body of a U.S. man who apparently drowned  
along with three other Americans has been found on a beach on 
Mexico's southern Pacific coast, local media reported Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The body of John Weems, a 19-year-old student at Delta State  
University in Cleveland, Miss., was found Sunday at the Playa Linda 
beach in the Chiapas port city of Puerto Madero, the newspaper 
Reforma reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Weems, of Nacogdoches, Texas, played on the university's tennis  
team, said Fred Singston, Delta State's sports information 
director. 
</P>
<P>
	Weems' body and that of another drowning victim, 9-year-old Joy  
Love Murphy, will be returned to the United States for burial. No 
information on the child's hometown was immediately available. 
</P>
<P>
	The four Americans, members of a group of Baptist missionaries,  
drowned when they were pulled into a strong Pacific Ocean current 
at the popular beach spot. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Lynn Sloan, 37, and his 11-year-old daughter Carla, both of  
Lufkin, Texas, also drowned. Their bodies will be buried in the 
Chiapas city of Tapachula, on the Guatemalan border, as a tribute 
to the missionary work they were carrying out in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Two Argentine brothers convicted in the  
1989 kidnapping of a leading Brazilian businessman started their 
second hunger strike in six months Monday to pressure authorities 
to send them home. 
</P>
<P>
	Horacio and Humberto Paz insisted they would end their strike  
only after being transferred to Argentina. During the earlier fast 
in November, two Canadians who were also on strike were transferred 
to a Vancouver prison under a prisoner-transfer treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	The Paz brothers, who are serving sentences of 15 to 18 years,  
were convicted of abducting Abilio Diniz, owner of Brazil's largest 
supermarket chain. Diniz was freed unharmed. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at Brazil's Justice and Foreign Ministries were not  
immediately available for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) -- President Hugo Banzer replaced nine  
Cabinet members Monday evening, declaring he intended intensify 
efforts to curb drug trafficking and corruption. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes were sparked by the resignation last week of  
Interior Minister Guido Nayer, who accused Banzer and his party of 
corruption and inefficiency. 
</P>
<P>
	Banzer ratified Foreign Minister Javier Murillo, Finance  
Minister Herbert Muller, Education Minister Tito Hoz de Vila and 
Health Minister Guillermo Cuentas. 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- A tractor-trailer crashed into three  
pick-up trucks during a rainstorm on a Guatemalan highway, killing 
seven people, including two children, Guatemalan police said. 
Fourteen people were seriously injured. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident occurred Sunday near Santa Lucia Cotzumalguapa 53  
miles southwest of Guatemala City. Police were investigating the 
cause of the crash. 
</P>
