<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NAACP Receives Million-Dollar Gift </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A foundation established by the late owner of  
the food conglomerate TLC Beatrice gave the NAACP $1 million to 
continue training future budding black business leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	The money will allow the National Association for the  
Advancement of Colored People to continue funding the NAACP 
Reginald F. Lewis Youth Entrepreneurial Institute for five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis formed TLC Beatrice International Holdings Inc. in a $985  
million buyout funded partly by junk bond mastermind Michael Milken 
in 1987. The deal made Lewis the first black executive to control a 
billion-dollar company. 
</P>
<P>
	He died of brain cancer in 1993.  
</P>
<P>
	This summer, 120 high school students will take the four-week  
course that bears his name, which includes classes on finance, team 
building and etiquette. The program, first started in 1994, will be 
offered this year in Baltimore; Atlanta; Austin, Tex.; Charlotte, 
N.C.; Columbia, S.C.; Fort Lauderdale, Fla; Gary, Ind.; and 
Richmond, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	NAACP President Kweisi Mfume said the program is needed to  
bolster the number of black entrepreneurs in the United States, 
something that is ``simply not going to happen in a vacuum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a talent pool we're creating here,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Forbes magazine listed Lewis among the 400 richest Americans in  
1992, when his net worth was an estimated $400 million. After his 
death the following year, the company suffered both management and 
shareholder turmoil. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis' widow, Loida Nicolas Lewis, took the helm of the company.  
In May, she announced plans to liquidate the largely European food 
conglomerate her husband oversaw. Management convinced her it was 
the best course for investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout its short life, TLC Beatrice has been hailed as a  
success story. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1987, when TLC Beatrice reported revenue of $1.8 billion, it  
became the first black-owned company to have more than $1 billion 
in annual sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The company then began its reign at the top of Black Enterprise  
magazine's annual list of the country's 100 biggest black-owned 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	TLC Beatrice, which was closely held by the Lewis family and  
associates, hit its peak in 1996 when it had $2.23 billion in 
revenue. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 22:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Votes on Lobbying Wait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former House Appropriations Committee chairman  
Bob Livingston, who opened his own lobbying firm after leaving 
Congress in February, must wait a year before he can talk to his 
former colleagues about his new clients. 
</P>
<P>
	Under legislation that has passed the Senate, future  
lawmakers-turned-lobbyists would have to wait a second year. 
</P>
<P>
	As under current law, however, they could still sell advice and  
counsel to corporate clients and could immediately set up a 
lobbying shop by hiring underlings to make the formal contacts with 
House and Senate members. They just couldn't call their former 
colleagues on behalf of a client for two years, double the current 
moratorium. 
</P>
<P>
	While the proposal won't affect ex-lawmakers like Livingston, he  
still doesn't like it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's ridiculous,'' the Louisiana Republican said.  
``Once they're outside the jurisdiction of the Congress, to impinge 
on one's right to practice law or to lobby or to speak is a 
violation of the First Amendment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the Senate legislation, staff members also would have to  
wait two years before lobbying any member in the house of Congress 
that employed them. Currently, former staffers are under a one-year 
moratorium that only prohibits lobbying the lawmaker or committee 
they worked for. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis., added the little-noticed provision  
to the Senate version of a spending bill for congressional 
operations approved last week. The House version of the spending 
bill, passed last month, does not include the provision. 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional negotiators will decide whether the tougher  
moratorium will be in the final spending bill. A similar 
Feingold-sponsored provision passed the Senate in 1996 but 
negotiators left it out of the final legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Feingold said the longer ban means that an entire two-year  
session of Congress would end before an ex-lawmaker could lobby 
former colleagues. 
</P>
<P>
	``It addresses a perception that too often rises to the level of  
reality -- that the interests that hire former members or staffers 
from Congress have special access when they lobby Congress,'' 
Feingold said. 
</P>
<P>
	The American League of Lobbyists opposes special restrictions on  
lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's punitive to former members,'' said organization president  
Kenneth Feltman. ``Simply because someone has been a member of 
Congress should not lead to the presumption that they need two 
years to reform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The measure wouldn't affect lawmakers who have already left  
office. 
</P>
<P>
	Livingston has registered to lobby on behalf of several defense  
contractors, including Avondale Industries, Bollinger Shipyards and 
Halter Marine Group. Each is seeking a share of the federal funds 
Livingston helped allocate as chairman of the powerful House 
Appropriations Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	While in Congress, he received more financial support from the  
defense industry than any other interest, and he helped the 
Pentagon fend off bigger budget cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Livingston was in line to succeed Newt Gingrich as House  
speaker, but resigned his seat amid the impeachment proceedings 
against President Clinton after admitting to his own extramarital 
affair. 
</P>
<P>
	Among former lawmakers who did not seek re-election in 1998,  
former House Rules Committee Chairman Gerald B.H. Solomon, R-N.Y., 
set up his own lobbying shop, while ex-Sens. Dan Coats, R-Ind., and 
Wendell Ford, D-Ky., and ex-Reps. Bill Paxon, R-N.Y., and Vic 
Fazio, D-Calif. all joined established firms. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
