<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Music Ace 2 Offers Basics of Music </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The SPCA (Society for Prevention of Cruelty to Adults) should  
seek laws making it a felony to provide anyone under 10 years of 
age with a violin, but music -- and music education -- is nonetheless 
an important part of learning. 
</P>
<P>
	It's also one of the education areas that hasn't benefited a lot  
from the ubiquity of personal computers. True, there have been 
spates of software and MIDI (Musical Instrument Digital Interface) 
keyboards, as well as instrument-specific instruction software. But 
most music basics and theory are still delivered in school or at 
private lessons. 
</P>
<P>
	A Windows-Macintosh product called Music Ace 2 might change  
that. It's from Harmonic Vision, an Evanston, Ill., company. 
</P>
<P>
	Music Ace 2 uses delightful animation in a crisp,  
well-structured learning environment to walk anyone older than 
around eight years old through the world of rhythm, harmony, 
syncopation, standard notation, melody and time signatures -- the 
nuts and bolts of how those dots on lines get turned into music. 
The student's guide throughout is Maestro Max, an animated 
conductor. Appropriate behavior is rewarded by praise and audience 
applause. 
</P>
<P>
	What makes Music Ace 2 stand out is attention to detail.  
</P>
<P>
	When an audio clip is played to illustrate a concept, for  
example, the composer and title appear and the notes are displayed 
as animated heads that sing the appropriate tone at the appropriate 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	The Singing Notes are cute. But they are also so  
attention-grabbing that students learn, without being told 
directly, to associate notes with tones on both the treble and bass 
clefs of the musical staff (the horizontal lines on which notes are 
positioned.) 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, the software contains more than 2,000 music examples  
from 75 composers, used to deliver 24 lessons. The lessons are 
teamed with games that reinforce the content. 
</P>
<P>
	A Music Doodle Pad allows students to drag-and-drop notes to a  
music staff and play and save the resulting compositions, and while 
the software tracks a student's progress. 
</P>
<P>
	Music Ace 2 would be an ideal supplement to one-on-one music  
instruction. Harmonic Vision also offers a classroom or teaching 
studio version. An adult thinking of taking up music as a hobby 
would be well served, as would someone trying to recall music 
basics after a 30-year rest. 
</P>
<P>
	System requirements as listed on the Harmonic Vision Web site  
(http://www.harmonicvision.com): 
</P>
<P>
	--Windows 3.1: 486-66 megahertz CPU or better -- 8 megabytes of  
RAM; 640x480 256-color Super VGA; 24 megabytes hard disk space; 
CD-ROM drive; MPC compatible sound card or General MIDI required; 
no MIDI keyboard required (optional). Additional requirements for 
Windows 95-98, 16 megabytes of RAM. 
</P>
<P>
	--Macintosh: Macintosh 68040 CPU at 33 megahertz or higher;  
System 7.5 or better; 12 megabytes of RAM; 640 x 480 256-color 
monitor; 24 megabytes free hard disk space; CD-ROM drive; no MIDI 
keyboard required (optional). Additional requirements for Mac OS8 
and higher: 24 megabytes of RAM. 
</P>
<P>
	The suggested retail price of Music Ace 2 is $49.95, toward the  
high end these days, but in this case worth it. Harmonic Vision 
says the software is available at retail, but they'll take your 
money directly at (800) 644-4994. A free demo of the original Music 
Ace software is available on the company's Web site. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Questions and comments are welcome. E-mail via the Internet to  
lblasko(at)ap.org, or send regular mail to Larry Blasko, AP, 50 
Rockefeller Plaza, New York, NY 10020. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
