<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Leniency Deals Policy Left Intact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today refused to resurrect a  
ruling that shocked federal prosecutors last year by telling them 
it was unlawful to offer leniency in exchange for testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices, without comment, left intact a federal appeals  
court ruling that in January removed any cloud of constitutional 
doubt from such leniency deals. 
</P>
<P>
	Controversy arose immediately after a three-judge panel of the  
Denver-based 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled in a Kansas 
case last summer that plea-bargained testimony violates a federal 
law making it a crime to give or offer anything of value in 
exchange for a trial witness' testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-judge panel's unanimous ruling had overturned the  
Kansas cocaine-trafficking conviction of Sonya Singleton. The panel 
said the chief prosecution witness illegally received leniency in 
return for his testimony against others involved in a Wichita drug 
ring. 
</P>
<P>
	The full 10th Circuit court, however, overturned the panel's  
decision last January. 
</P>
<P>
	``In light of the longstanding practice of leniency for  
testimony, we must presume that if Congress had intended that ... 
(the law) overturn this ingrained aspect of American legal culture, 
it would have done so in clear, unmistakable and unarguable 
language,'' the full appeals court said in its 9-3 ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	The January decision reinstated Ms. Singleton's conviction,  
spurring the appeal that was acted on today. 
</P>
<P>
	In it, her lawyer argued that the three-judge panel merely had  
read the federal law as Congress wrote it. The law states: 
``Whoever directly or indirectly gives, offers or promises anything 
of value to any person for or because of the testimony under oath 
or affirmation given or to be given by such person as a witness 
upon a trial ... before any court ... shall be fined ... or 
imprisoned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The word ``whoever'' should include government prosecutors, Ms.  
Singleton's appeal said, adding, ``The lenient treatment of an 
accused is clearly a valuable thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The appeal said the full 10th Circuit court's ruling, if allowed  
to stand, ``will eat away at the integrity of the judicial system. 
... The government's practice of buying testimony must be 
stopped.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Department lawyers urged the nation's highest court to  
reject the appeal. ``This claim is contrary to well-settled law and 
does not warrant this court's review,'' they said. ``Federal courts 
of appeals that have considered that claim in the wake of the 
short-lived panel decision in this case have squarely rejected 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Singleton vs. U.S., 98-8758.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
