<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 14:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hawkins Is Honored as NBA Sportsman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Before receiving the NBA's sportsmanship award  
on Monday, Hersey Hawkins had a confession for commissioner David 
Stern. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were a couple of times in the year where I actually  
tried to get technicals, but they wouldn't give it to me,'' said 
Hawkins, the Seattle SuperSonics guard. ``The refs would just walk 
away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hawkins ended up walking away with the league's fourth  
sportsmanship award, following Joe Dumars, Terrell Brandon and 
Avery Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can still play this game and be supportive of your  
teammates and still accomplish your goals and still put yourself in 
a position where you are considered one of the best players in the 
league,'' Hawkins said. 
</P>
<P>
	He received 70 of 118 votes by a panel of 31 media members. Eric  
Snow of Philadelphia was second with 23 votes, Kevin Garnett of 
Minnesota was third with 18 votes and rookie Vince Carter of 
Toronto received seven votes. 
</P>
<P>
	Stern praised Hawkins as ``somebody who has conducted himself  
both on and off the court in an exemplary fashion. We are proud to 
have him in the National Basketball Association.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, the NBA fined Larry Johnson and the Knicks in the  
wake of the forward's profane tirade directed at a league official 
and reporters who were trying to interview him during a mandatory 
media session. Though Hawkins didn't address Johnson's behavior 
directly, he had a lot to say about the state of sportsmanship in 
the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since I came into the league, oh yeah, definitely it has  
gotten worse,'' Hawkins said. ``It always gets worse when you're 
making a lot more money. That's been the case. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no idea why it has changed. When you're paying young  
guys all the money that they're making, why do they think they have 
to listen to anybody else or have to be respectful to anybody 
else?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hawkins also addressed the winds of change blowing through  
Seattle, which failed to make the playoffs this season for the 
first time in nine years. Hawkins said he met with Sonics 
executives recently and said he will not opt out of the remaining 
two years on his contract. 
</P>
<P>
	But he is already preparing for the possibility that the deal  
makes him a tradable commodity for a team seeking to make changes. 
Hawkins, 32, is coming off the lowest 3-point shooting percentage 
in his career (31 percent), and his scoring average has dropped 
every season since 1995-96. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm quite sure that the Sonics are going to make some  
changes,'' Hawkins said. ``I don't know if they're going to look at 
trying to package me and try to send me somewhere. I'm sure that's 
something they're going to think about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One reported deal has Hawkins and the Sonics' No. 13 pick going  
to Vancouver for the No. 2 pick in the upcoming draft. It is not a 
deal that intrigues Hawkins. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he does not have any type of no-trade clause in his  
contract, Hawkins said, ``I cannot show up. But I guess they'd have 
to take this award away from me. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would hope that if they did trade me somewhere that they  
would trade me somewhere where I'd have an opportunity to possibly 
win a championship or at least get in the playoffs,'' Hawkins said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't want them to trade me somewhere where I was in a  
rebuilding process where I'm going to be looking at losing 50-60 
games a year. I don't want that. I would hope that they have enough 
respect for me.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990621.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 16:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pianist Brubeck Plays Carnegie Hall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Jazz pianist Dave Brubeck, 78, last heard at the  
JVC Jazz Festival five years ago, played a concert of old and new 
music at Carnegie Hall which thoroughly delighted the audience. 
</P>
<P>
	With Brubeck as special guests were James Moody, known for his  
bebop saxophone and his writing and singing of funny, partly 
scatted lyrics to jazz tunes, and his son, trombonist Chris 
Brubeck, who appeared because the concert was on Father's Day. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of Sunday night's selections started with Brubeck playing  
delicate solo piano then opened up as Bobby Militello, playing 
saxophone and flute, bassist Alec Dankworth and drummer Randy Jones 
joined in. 
</P>
<P>
	Brubeck began with ``Someday My Prince Will Come,'' then played  
some pieces he wrote for the quartet's recent 40th anniversary tour 
of Britain. A live recording will come out June 29. Flashing his 
wide smile, the pianist promised ``tunes that you'll know'' for the 
second half of the evening. 
</P>
<P>
	One new piece was ``Marian McPartland,'' which Brubeck composed  
on his way to a benefit concert he did for her ``Piano Jazz'' radio 
show. The rhythm, which becomes quite emphatic, is based on the 
syllables of her name. 
</P>
<P>
	He also played two versions of a piece influenced by Chopin that  
he wrote in Poland during a 12-concert tour there in 1958. 
</P>
<P>
	The second half included a Duke Ellington medley, Moody having  
fun with ``Pennies From Heaven,'' and ``I Got Rhythm'' as an 
encore. 
</P>
<P>
	The JVC Jazz Festival began the previous Monday with  
``Revisiting the Kingdom of Swing'' -- clarinetist Ken Peplowski 
leading a band in the Benny Goodman arrangements, with pianist Dick 
Hyman joining in for ``Tiger Rag.'' Guitar lovers got an enormous 
treat the next night when, at a tribute to Johnny Smith, 15 
guitarists played. 
</P>
<P>
	Pianist Herbie Hancock and trumpeter Wayne Shorter played mainly  
dreamy, contemplative, evocative jazz at Friday night's concert at 
Carnegie Hall. Trumpeter Roy Hargrove's quintet jolted the hall to 
attention with its pulse and drive, using tempo changes and a wide 
range of musical dynamics. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
