<HEADLINE> Doctors' Bargaining Bill Considered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Doctors across the nation are seeking the right to  
join together in negotiating fees with HMOs, after 
precedent-setting legislation was approved in Texas over the 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Gov. George W. Bush signed a bill allowing Texas  
doctors to become the first in the nation to bargain collectively 
with health plans. A congressional committee will take up a similar 
proposal Tuesday, and doctors are pushing the issue in several 
state legislatures. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas law received support from the American Medical  
Association and its Texas affiliate, which cast doctors as 
advocates for patients in a struggle with ruthless insurers and 
health-maintenance organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's almost a David-and-Goliath situation,'' Dr. Randolph D.  
Smoak, a South Carolina surgeon and the AMA's president-elect, said 
in an interview from the organization's convention in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we attempt to get a test done or get a hospitalization,  
we have a great deal of restrictions placed on us by health 
carriers and HMOs,'' Smoak said. ``We certainly believe Texas has 
taken a great step forward. Many other states will be looking at 
this closely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new Texas law, which takes effect Sept. 1, doctors who  
band together to negotiate with health plans would be exempt from 
federal antitrust laws. The health plans wouldn't be required to 
recognize the doctors' bargaining units, but the Texas AMA said it 
would draw public attention to reluctant HMOs. 
</P>
<P>
	Health insurers, who had expected defeat in Texas, remain  
adamantly opposed to letting independent doctors organize. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will be very substantial costs to this,'' said Don  
Young, chief operating officer of the Health Insurance Association 
of America, which represents large health insurers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Say all of the people who do cataract surgery say, 'We want to  
be paid 20 percent more than last year.' What's the plan going to 
do? The doctors are a monopoly,'' Young said. 
</P>
<P>
	The next battleground over doctors' bargaining rights will be  
the U.S. House of Representatives. The House Judiciary Committee is 
scheduled to hold a hearing on a bill by Rep. Tom Campbell, 
R-Calif., to allow health care professionals to temporarily band 
together to negotiate with HMOs. 
</P>
<P>
	One-fourth of the House members have endorsed the bill,  
including a majority on the Judiciary Committee, but health 
insurers and the Clinton administration's Justice Department and 
Federal Trade Commission oppose it. 
</P>
<P>
	The AMA also is pushing legislatures in Pennsylvania, New  
Jersey, Florida and elsewhere to consider bills similar to the new 
Texas law. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill had been opposed by some lawmakers who said it could  
lead to an increase in medical costs by limiting the ability of 
health insurers to control costs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
