<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hungarians Promoting Aug. Eclipse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SIOFOK, Hungary (AP) -- ``Darkness at noon'' fever is catching  
hold in Hungary, a prime viewing area for the last total solar 
eclipse of the millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	Hungarians are pushing hard to promote the Aug. 11 darkening,  
with local governments and private entrepreneurs alike ready to 
cash in with T-shirts, commemorative stamps and specially made 
eclipse glasses. 
</P>
<P>
	While the eclipse will be visible in several other countries in  
Europe and Asia, Hungarians are touting their country as the place 
to be -- particularly since popular Lake Balaton is in the path of 
the full eclipse. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are hoping to get this day declared a holiday,'' says  
Karoly Herenyi, a Balaton-area member of parliament. ``Nobody will 
be doing much work anyway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NASA, the U.S. space agency, says the ``instant of greatest  
eclipse'' will occur in the rolling hills of south-central Romania, 
near Rimnicu-Vilcea. Bucharest, Romania's capital, is the only 
capital city in Europe affording a view of the full eclipse. 
</P>
<P>
	But while tens of thousands of eclipse seekers are expected in  
Romania, Hungary is gearing up for a much bigger influx of 
visitors. 
</P>
<P>
	A solar eclipse, not seen in Hungary in 157 years, occurs when  
the moon crosses between the Earth and sun, casting a shadow on 
Earth. 
</P>
<P>
	The shadow of the Aug. 11 eclipse will pass across the center of  
Hungary, from northwest to southeast, in a 70-mile-wide swath. 
</P>
<P>
	The shadow will enter Hungary at 12:47 p.m. local time, and it  
will take the moon about 80 minutes to fully block out the sun. 
After barely two minutes of total darkness, full sunlight will 
return to normal in another 80 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Cloudy day? No problem. Hungarian state television has arranged  
with the air force to have a camera mounted on a MiG-29 fighter jet 
that will follow the eclipse from the Austrian to the Romanian 
borders. The supersonic jet is needed because the shadow moves at 
1,522 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Nowhere are hopes higher for eclipse tourism than in Siofok, a  
town of 23,000 people on the southern shore of Lake Balaton, which 
is the biggest lake in central Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	The sky over Siofok will be completely dark for two minutes, 22  
seconds -- a second less than in Romania -- and stars normally seen 
only in the winter will become visible. 
</P>
<P>
	It could be a lucrative 142 seconds.  
</P>
<P>
	All rooms in the area are already booked, and municipal  
officials optimistically predict 200,000 visitors, many of whom 
they say will be out in rental boats. 
</P>
<P>
	Tourists have been wooed with packages that offer zodiac suppers  
-- each dish named after an astrological sign -- wine tastings and 
music festivals, where the U2 hit ``Staring at the Sun'' may be a 
tad overplayed. 
</P>
<P>
	The post office has issued 200,000 commemorative stamps showing  
a map of the country and the path of the eclipse. 
</P>
<P>
	Szombathely, a medieval town on the Austrian border, will set up  
a giant model of the solar system on the main square and hold an 
international astronomy conference. A Japanese orchestra will give 
a concert of music by Verdi and Saint-Saens. 
</P>
<P>
	Hungary's last eclipse, in 1842, has remained memorable for  
Hungarians because the country's most beloved poet, Sandor Petoefi, 
nearly went blind from looking directly at the sun. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sun Hunters company is ready to help with that risk. It is  
selling U.S.-made glasses with special filtered lenses designed for 
safely viewing eclipses. 
</P>
<P>
	Sun Hunters also has put out a book, the inevitable T-shirts and  
caps and a double CD made jointly with the Hungarian Astronomers' 
Association that contains instrumental music and scientific 
information in Hungarian, English and German. 
</P>
<P>
	It won't be all fun and games in the dark.  
</P>
<P>
	Gabor Goesi, director of a wildlife preserve near Szeged in  
southern Hungary, and his staff will be studying the reaction of 
wildlife. 
</P>
<P>
	``Such a full solar eclipse is a rare event, something animals  
have not been conditioned to prepare for in the course of their 
evolution,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting in the Atlantic, the eclipse's path will cross Belgium,  
southern Germany, Austria, Slovakia, Hungary, northern Yugoslavia, 
Romania, Turkey and on to Pakistan and India. 
</P>
<P>
	The next full solar eclipse in Hungary won't be until Oct. 7,  
2135. 
</P>
<P>
	Americans won't have to wait that long -- they'll have a full  
solar eclipse on Aug. 21, 2017, and a partial one on May 20, 2012. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
