<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court OKs County Fees for Judges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An Alabama county can collect an occupational  
fee from two federal judges who work there, the Supreme Court ruled 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	By a 7-2 vote, the justices overturned a federal appeals court  
ruling that had deemed the fee unconstitutional when applied to the 
two judges. 
</P>
<P>
	Imposing such county fees against federal employees is rare, but  
today's decision could encourage other counties across the nation 
to emulate the revenue-raising fees imposed by Jefferson County, 
Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	``The record shows no discrimination,'' Justice Ruth Bader  
Ginsburg wrote for the court. ``between similarly situated federal 
and state employees. ... Should Alabama or Jefferson County 
authorities take to exempting state officials while leaving federal 
officials or a subcategory of them subject to the tax, that would 
indeed present a starkly different case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She added: ``There is no sound reason to deny Alabama counties  
the right to tax with an even hand the compensation of federal, 
state and local officeholders whose services are rendered within 
the county.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Jefferson County Commission voted in 1987 to require all  
people who work in the county to pay an occupational license fee of 
0.5 percent of their before-tax income. The ordinance exempts 
people who already pay licensing fees to the state. Doctors, 
contractors, dentists, lawyers, magicians and fortunetellers are 
among the exempt occupations. 
</P>
<P>
	Judges, state and federal, are not exempt.  
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judges William M. Acker Jr. and U.W. Clemon  
refused to pay the fee. The two work primarily out of the Hugo L. 
Black Courthouse in Birmingham. Their $136,700 salaries could 
subject them to an annual fee of a little less than $700. 
</P>
<P>
	County officials sued the two judges as scofflaws in 1992,  
seeking to collect back fees. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit originally was filed in a state court, but the  
judges successfully had the case transferred to a federal court 
where a Georgia judge was specially appointed to preside. 
</P>
<P>
	He struck down the fee as applied to the two federal judges, and  
the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld his ruling by a 9-3 
vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court set aside those rulings last year and ordered  
the appeals court to reconsider federal court authority over the 
case. 
</P>
<P>
	Jefferson County officials and Clinton administration lawyers  
urged the justices to rule that the Tax Injunction Act precludes 
any federal court authority in the license fee case. The court 
rejected that argument. 
</P>
<P>
	On the constitutionality of the tax, only Justice Stephen G.  
Breyer and Sandra Day O'Connor voted to strike it down. In an 
opinion by Breyer, they said it violates a doctrine barring 
intergovernmental taxation. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Jefferson County vs. Acker, 98-10.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
