<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Qwest Lobbies U S West and Frontier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The leader of the telecommunications company  
Qwest sent letters to the heads of U S West Inc. and Frontier 
Corp., trying to convince them to abandon their merger deals with a 
rival and support his competing bids. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph P. Nacchio, chairman and chief executive of Qwest  
Communications International Inc., send the letters Thursday as 
part of his attempt to trump his takeover rival, Global Crossing 
Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are confident that your board will determine that our  
proposal is financially, structurally and strategically superior to 
Global Crossing's offer and in the best interests of your 
shareholders,'' Nacchio wrote in the letters, copies of which were 
released to the media. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Frontier said it would carry on with its agreement to  
merge with Global Crossing. U S West has yet to announce its 
intentions. 
</P>
<P>
	Naccio has ambitious plans to build a global fiber optic cable  
network to provide high-speed Internet access and other telecom 
services. 
</P>
<P>
	He wants the customer and sales base of U S West, a Denver-based  
regional phone company, and Frontier, a local and long-distance 
company based in Rochester, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest has offered to buy U S West and Frontier in a combined  
$44.1 billion offer. Global Crossing's deals to buy U S West and 
Frontier total $43.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	While U S West's board of directors has yet to be heard from,  
its union workers are showing some resistance to the Qwest bid. The 
head of the Communications Workers of America warned the governors 
of the 14 states served by U S West that the proposed takeover 
would drain jobs and investment from the region and further imperil 
already-declining service quality. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecommunications companies are under pressure to cut costs and  
reshape their operations to meet the Internet age. As telephones, 
computers, televisions and radios become one, companies like Qwest 
and Global Crossing are racing to provide the wires that will carry 
enormous amounts of video, audio and data traffic to homes and 
businesses around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	To that end, Qwest on Monday announced a joint-venture  
partnership with the accounting firm KPMG LLC. The venture, to be 
called Qwest Cyber.Solutions LLC, will help small- and medium-size 
businesses put their operations on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, U S West unveiled a plan Monday to test a new  
service that allows customers to surf the Internet, use e-mail and 
talk on a speaker phone while watching television -- all at the same 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	U S West will test the new service, called WebVision, in Denver,  
Minneapolis and Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	U S West's stock rose 31 1/4 cents to $58.31 1/4 on the New York Stock  
Exchange, where Frontier's shares dipped 50 cents to $57.81 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest's shares fell $1.43 3/4 to $36.50 on the Nasdaq Stock Market,  
where shares of Global Crossing dropped $2.62 1/2 to $47.12 1/2. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
