<HEADLINE> Stars Fans Cheer Departing Goalie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Some of the loudest cheers at the pep rally  
honoring the Stanley Cup champion Dallas Stars were for a guy who 
didn't play a minute in the postseason and who won't be on the team 
next season. 
</P>
<P>
	Call it a fond farewell to backup goaltender Roman Turek, who  
was traded Sunday to the St. Louis Blues for a third-round draft 
pick. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars had little choice but to deal Turek, who went 16-3-3  
in the regular season, because otherwise he would've been likely 
lost in the upcoming expansion draft. 
</P>
<P>
	The salute began when team play-by-play announcer Ralph Strangis  
asked fans to, ``Say hello and unfortunately say goodbye to 
goaltender Roman Turek.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was the first player introduced because he wore jersey No. 1.  
</P>
<P>
	Team president Jim Lites and coach Ken Hitchcock led a standing  
ovation and the crowd of nearly 20,000 fans obliged. Turek had a 
big smile as he blew kisses to the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	Hitchcock again paid tribute to Turek later in the show,  
prompting a standing ovation from his teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	``Roman Turek is going to go somewhere else to play,'' Hitchcock  
said, ``but he's going to be a Dallas Star for life as far as we're 
concerned.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
